
Parachute technology evolved over time with contributions from visionary inventors. Faust Vrančić was inspired by Leonardo da Vinci''s innovative designs and experiments in 16th-century Italy, using the principles of air resistance to study deceleration and its benefits for human safety. Concurrently, Leonardo da Vinci, one of history’s most celebrated polymaths, created early concepts that demonstrated a deep understanding of how air resistance could be harnessed to protect individuals from harm during falls. His designs showcased an advanced grasp of the mechanics involved in slowing descent, reflecting a blend of theoretical knowledge and practical application.

