	 ('dc5bb227-d17f-4c98-84c9-78ea16a88de6'::uuid,'OTTO LILIENTHAL''S EXPERIMENTS','MODEL','{}','OTTO LILIENTHAL''S EXPERIMENTS (1891) encompassed a series of controlled gliding experiments that involved both monoplanes and biplanes. These experiments utilized wings designed with characteristics reminiscent of birds or bats, reflecting Lilienthal''s innovative approach to flight. During this period, Lilienthal employed a technique known as the whirling arm to test wing forces in free air environments. Through these experiments, he meticulously researched the principles behind flapping flight. Despite the potential shown by such designs, Lilienthal eventually abandoned the concept due to inherent limitations in achieving effective and sustainable flight through flapping mechanisms alone.

