	 ('66ed161c-2b04-4edf-8923-96a1885c71eb'::uuid,'SPEED OF SOUND','MECHANISM','{}','The Speed of Sound refers to the rate at which sound waves travel through various media, including air. In the context of atmospheric conditions, it has significant implications for understanding compressibility and aerodynamics. For ideal gases under standard atmospheric conditions (with a gamma value \( k = 1.4 \) and gas constant \( R = 287.14 \, \text{J/(kg·K)} \)), the speed of sound can be calculated using the formula:
\[ v = \sqrt{\frac{kRT}{\gamma - 1}} \]
where \( T \) is the temperature in Kelvin.

The propagation velocity varies with temperature, increasing as the square root of the absolute temperature. Notably, at standard atmospheric pressure and a reference temperature (such as 0°C or 273 K), this formula provides an approximate value for sound speed in air. It is important to note that this speed not only depends on temperature but also height within the atmosphere due to changes in density and temperature profiles.

