	 ('30afc06b-8c44-470f-b893-a5ad1bfb2163'::uuid,'V.N. YURIEV','PERSON','{}','Student of N.E. Zhukovsky, continued the legacy of flight dynamics studies','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["7b1ef518d9d451766f80b634c2d13ecaf9e58d741b20333962ca9373f633c69f3846571db070b444adf5f537b399ec1a4c834561966469f5c4779d75e90d948d", "7b1ef518d9d451766f80b634c2d13ecaf9e58d741b20333962ca9373f633c69f3846571db070b444adf5f537b399ec1a4c834561966469f5c4779d75e90d948d"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('46b3accc-6b6a-4c95-9912-ae46e1c279df'::uuid,'V.S. PYSHNOV','PERSON','{}','A student of N.E. Zhukovsky, contributed to flight dynamics research','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["7b1ef518d9d451766f80b634c2d13ecaf9e58d741b20333962ca9373f633c69f3846571db070b444adf5f537b399ec1a4c834561966469f5c4779d75e90d948d", "7b1ef518d9d451766f80b634c2d13ecaf9e58d741b20333962ca9373f633c69f3846571db070b444adf5f537b399ec1a4c834561966469f5c4779d75e90d948d"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('b99fc268-8574-41d8-ab17-0835c107f029'::uuid,'I.V. OSTOSLAVSKY','PERSON','{}','Student of N.E. Zhukovsky, involved in expanding the knowledge base of flight dynamics','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["7b1ef518d9d451766f80b634c2d13ecaf9e58d741b20333962ca9373f633c69f3846571db070b444adf5f537b399ec1a4c834561966469f5c4779d75e90d948d", "7b1ef518d9d451766f80b634c2d13ecaf9e58d741b20333962ca9373f633c69f3846571db070b444adf5f537b399ec1a4c834561966469f5c4779d75e90d948d"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('4c89b726-117d-4b12-91fb-62022619d84c'::uuid,'FRICTION FORCES','MECHANISM','{}','Friction forces appear when there is relative motion between surfaces and can be influenced by viscosity.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["28cecdc770c6a89ca87abe00cc7c001435c36f85ccea49414b7b38e0ca90e9c7a34ae80b18f1142de6f051bd2874e60296f40c3fe63d476edda0f8036922ba4c"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('96cb6362-2587-441e-942a-17b3d28b4dea'::uuid,'VISCOOSITY','MECHANISM','{}','Viscosity results from the chaotic motion of molecules and affects air and liquid properties, decreasing with temperature increase in liquids but increasing in gases under pressure change.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 3, "text_unit_ids": ["28cecdc770c6a89ca87abe00cc7c001435c36f85ccea49414b7b38e0ca90e9c7a34ae80b18f1142de6f051bd2874e60296f40c3fe63d476edda0f8036922ba4c", "28cecdc770c6a89ca87abe00cc7c001435c36f85ccea49414b7b38e0ca90e9c7a34ae80b18f1142de6f051bd2874e60296f40c3fe63d476edda0f8036922ba4c", "28cecdc770c6a89ca87abe00cc7c001435c36f85ccea49414b7b38e0ca90e9c7a34ae80b18f1142de6f051bd2874e60296f40c3fe63d476edda0f8036922ba4c"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('28bd577c-772d-4d7a-af48-cd71038acebf'::uuid,'MASS DENSITY','MATERIAL','{}','MASS DENSITY is a fundamental property of matter that describes the amount of mass contained within a given unit volume. This physical quantity is typically calculated using the formula ρ = m / V, where ρ represents mass density, m is the mass, and V denotes the volume. In the International System of Units (SI), standard mass density for air at sea level (0 meters height) under International Standard Atmosphere (ISA) conditions is 1.225 kg/m³. The value can also vary based on other systems such as MKGSS (Metric Kilogram-Gravity-Sec制度), where the density of air at those specific standard conditions H=0m would be approximately 9.81 kg/m³. Notably, mass density is particularly relevant in defining properties of gases like air, where it aids in understanding their behavior under different conditions, often simplifying models by considering them as nearly incompressible fluids.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 3, "text_unit_ids": ["bf26f5a3b6530571e586bf2e521de1606936d166f7ecd17a2fda3301e6731802baf11ea7e937d0ec458325da1ec98c55af85370ad15325184313eb3e41a92807", "bf26f5a3b6530571e586bf2e521de1606936d166f7ecd17a2fda3301e6731802baf11ea7e937d0ec458325da1ec98c55af85370ad15325184313eb3e41a92807", "b5612dfd5afd1a966867270904e7977f694cbe6e96b4be34a53c32ab6f48a581ba2e0825a6d9165aaeb6957d598461f699ff9ff6c7b4ff82bb2c2e2dba4929d9"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('03e668be-8f5f-4739-a8d2-0bb4a4b02e12'::uuid,'VISCOSITY','MECHANISM','{}','Property of air to resist mutual shear of particles caused by internal friction forces between moving molecules; increases with increasing temperature and decreases with decreasing temperature','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["bf26f5a3b6530571e586bf2e521de1606936d166f7ecd17a2fda3301e6731802baf11ea7e937d0ec458325da1ec98c55af85370ad15325184313eb3e41a92807", "bf26f5a3b6530571e586bf2e521de1606936d166f7ecd17a2fda3301e6731802baf11ea7e937d0ec458325da1ec98c55af85370ad15325184313eb3e41a92807"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('42d1b7bd-81f4-4672-80b7-fb184c4d3c04'::uuid,'COMPRESSIBILITY','MATERIAL','{}','A measure of a substance''s tendency to undergo a change in volume when subjected to a pressure difference. In air, it is related to how easily the air can be compressed or expanded under varying conditions.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["bf26f5a3b6530571e586bf2e521de1606936d166f7ecd17a2fda3301e6731802baf11ea7e937d0ec458325da1ec98c55af85370ad15325184313eb3e41a92807"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('db440895-15d4-47ad-9f75-9c6b4c443c25'::uuid,'RELATIVE DENSITY','COMPONENT','{}','Determined by the formula Δ = ρ / ρ₀, measuring how a substance''s density compares to that of some reference material. In air, it relates to the ratio of its mass per unit volume compared to another gas or air itself at standard conditions.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["bf26f5a3b6530571e586bf2e521de1606936d166f7ecd17a2fda3301e6731802baf11ea7e937d0ec458325da1ec98c55af85370ad15325184313eb3e41a92807"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('b7c32420-873e-4ffd-993a-abde20613516'::uuid,'ATMOSPHERIC PRESSURE','COMPONENT','{}','Pressure exerted by the weight of air above a given point, caused mainly by the mass of overlying layers of air creating force on lower levels.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["bf26f5a3b6530571e586bf2e521de1606936d166f7ecd17a2fda3301e6731802baf11ea7e937d0ec458325da1ec98c55af85370ad15325184313eb3e41a92807"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('991e7919-3e0a-4741-ba1e-abd38fa09724'::uuid,'CELSIUS SCALE','COMPONENT','{}','One of the main scales for measuring temperature. It is defined based on the freezing and boiling points of water at standard atmospheric pressure.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["bf26f5a3b6530571e586bf2e521de1606936d166f7ecd17a2fda3301e6731802baf11ea7e937d0ec458325da1ec98c55af85370ad15325184313eb3e41a92807"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('c6372b0c-4958-4da9-a642-8f174233df34'::uuid,'ABSOLUTE SCALE','COMPONENT','{}','Another main scale for measuring temperature, defined using the concept of absolute zero where nothing can be colder.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["bf26f5a3b6530571e586bf2e521de1606936d166f7ecd17a2fda3301e6731802baf11ea7e937d0ec458325da1ec98c55af85370ad15325184313eb3e41a92807"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('4ccd4550-b931-4ead-a106-2f26e9f32643'::uuid,'ALHAMIA PRISON','COMPONENT','{}','A prison located in Tiruzia where some of the hostages were held.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["bf26f5a3b6530571e586bf2e521de1606936d166f7ecd17a2fda3301e6731802baf11ea7e937d0ec458325da1ec98c55af85370ad15325184313eb3e41a92807"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('dfe1997a-5398-4c81-b69d-28585a168d3a'::uuid,'FIRUZABAD','GEO','{}','Location where the hostages were held and an agreement was made for their release.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["bf26f5a3b6530571e586bf2e521de1606936d166f7ecd17a2fda3301e6731802baf11ea7e937d0ec458325da1ec98c55af85370ad15325184313eb3e41a92807"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('95af32b3-3389-4a7f-94ed-cc8239cb139b'::uuid,'TIRUZIA','GEO','{}','Capital city of Firuzabad mentioned in context as a location for some actions related to hostage exchange.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["bf26f5a3b6530571e586bf2e521de1606936d166f7ecd17a2fda3301e6731802baf11ea7e937d0ec458325da1ec98c55af85370ad15325184313eb3e41a92807"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('62211dc8-c0fc-41c3-982c-1c68680fb854'::uuid,'KROHAARA','GEO','{}','Capital of Quintara mentioned as the destination for hostages and financial transactions.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["bf26f5a3b6530571e586bf2e521de1606936d166f7ecd17a2fda3301e6731802baf11ea7e937d0ec458325da1ec98c55af85370ad15325184313eb3e41a92807"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('dfee7e2a-74fb-4077-ac58-8682a92a62c6'::uuid,'CASHION','GEO','{}','Capital city in Aurelia mentioned as the destination for hostages after their journey from Tiruzia.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["bf26f5a3b6530571e586bf2e521de1606936d166f7ecd17a2fda3301e6731802baf11ea7e937d0ec458325da1ec98c55af85370ad15325184313eb3e41a92807"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('96342eed-f32c-4727-8105-ccc79b1c2810'::uuid,'STANDARD CONDITIONS (H=0M, ISA)','COMPONENT','{}','(Defined set) Reference point for standard atmospheric conditions used in measurements and calculations of temperature, pressure, and density.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["bf26f5a3b6530571e586bf2e521de1606936d166f7ecd17a2fda3301e6731802baf11ea7e937d0ec458325da1ec98c55af85370ad15325184313eb3e41a92807"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('d9391e49-b795-4255-b0a8-d3f512c5f175'::uuid,'LIQUID VISCOSITY','COMPONENT','{}','(Although specifically about liquids, the concept can be related to gases like air in certain contexts where both fluid dynamics principles apply.) Viscosity increases with greater internal friction within molecules when heated.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["bf26f5a3b6530571e586bf2e521de1606936d166f7ecd17a2fda3301e6731802baf11ea7e937d0ec458325da1ec98c55af85370ad15325184313eb3e41a92807"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('ff768147-5b9f-4510-ba54-85bc3fdeac38'::uuid,'AIR VISCOSITY','MATERIAL','{}','Air''s viscosity changes with temperature; it increases as temperature decreases and is a key factor in aerodynamics, influencing friction near streamlined bodies.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 3, "text_unit_ids": ["28cecdc770c6a89ca87abe00cc7c001435c36f85ccea49414b7b38e0ca90e9c7a34ae80b18f1142de6f051bd2874e60296f40c3fe63d476edda0f8036922ba4c", "28cecdc770c6a89ca87abe00cc7c001435c36f85ccea49414b7b38e0ca90e9c7a34ae80b18f1142de6f051bd2874e60296f40c3fe63d476edda0f8036922ba4c", "28cecdc770c6a89ca87abe00cc7c001435c36f85ccea49414b7b38e0ca90e9c7a34ae80b18f1142de6f051bd2874e60296f40c3fe63d476edda0f8036922ba4c"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('3a718795-9171-4013-a5ec-2d3e25942305'::uuid,'COHESION FORCES','MECHANISM','{}','Cohesion forces are weaker in heated liquids like oil in engines, influencing their viscosity decrease.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 3, "text_unit_ids": ["28cecdc770c6a89ca87abe00cc7c001435c36f85ccea49414b7b38e0ca90e9c7a34ae80b18f1142de6f051bd2874e60296f40c3fe63d476edda0f8036922ba4c", "28cecdc770c6a89ca87abe00cc7c001435c36f85ccea49414b7b38e0ca90e9c7a34ae80b18f1142de6f051bd2874e60296f40c3fe63d476edda0f8036922ba4c", "28cecdc770c6a89ca87abe00cc7c001435c36f85ccea49414b7b38e0ca90e9c7a34ae80b18f1142de6f051bd2874e60296f40c3fe63d476edda0f8036922ba4c"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('141a03f3-e3f6-449f-99a5-d4af28ac40fb'::uuid,'BOUNDARY LAYER','MECHANISM','{}','A thin layer of air near the surface of a streamlined body where particle deceleration and increased friction forces occur due to viscosity.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 3, "text_unit_ids": ["28cecdc770c6a89ca87abe00cc7c001435c36f85ccea49414b7b38e0ca90e9c7a34ae80b18f1142de6f051bd2874e60296f40c3fe63d476edda0f8036922ba4c", "28cecdc770c6a89ca87abe00cc7c001435c36f85ccea49414b7b38e0ca90e9c7a34ae80b18f1142de6f051bd2874e60296f40c3fe63d476edda0f8036922ba4c", "28cecdc770c6a89ca87abe00cc7c001435c36f85ccea49414b7b38e0ca90e9c7a34ae80b18f1142de6f051bd2874e60296f40c3fe63d476edda0f8036922ba4c"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('f3e1697e-e2ee-43c2-894b-56b3db35b362'::uuid,'FRICTION STRESS (Τ)','MATERIAL','{}','(Formula: τ = F/A, where F is the friction force exerted on a unit area A. Calculated using Newton''s second law.) This stress is used in aerodynamics to analyze forces acting at interfaces or between different media.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 3, "text_unit_ids": ["28cecdc770c6a89ca87abe00cc7c001435c36f85ccea49414b7b38e0ca90e9c7a34ae80b18f1142de6f051bd2874e60296f40c3fe63d476edda0f8036922ba4c", "28cecdc770c6a89ca87abe00cc7c001435c36f85ccea49414b7b38e0ca90e9c7a34ae80b18f1142de6f051bd2874e60296f40c3fe63d476edda0f8036922ba4c", "28cecdc770c6a89ca87abe00cc7c001435c36f85ccea49414b7b38e0ca90e9c7a34ae80b18f1142de6f051bd2874e60296f40c3fe63d476edda0f8036922ba4c"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('73607c88-adb1-4b46-a389-128f4676eb36'::uuid,'EQUATION OF STATE FOR AN IDEAL GAS','MODEL','{}','The equation of state for an ideal gas is a fundamental physical model that describes the relationship between pressure (P), density (ρ), and temperature (T). Given by the formula \( P = \rho RT \, \text{N/m}^2 \), where R represents the specific gas constant. This model plays a crucial role in understanding the state properties of air, particularly in aerodynamics. By quantifying how changes in pressure, density, and temperature interact within an idealized gas without considering intermolecular forces or heat transfer mechanisms, engineers and scientists can predict the behavior of gases under various conditions essential for analyzing fluid dynamics and designing efficient systems.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["28cecdc770c6a89ca87abe00cc7c001435c36f85ccea49414b7b38e0ca90e9c7a34ae80b18f1142de6f051bd2874e60296f40c3fe63d476edda0f8036922ba4c", "ef6486c4db66ed7932b9bbcd3bcf3a0d6b5a54c10d03a87ac159ac59c84ab6e6992178768f4ec79d55ba89ac05ddc0f594857e23238ccbde9c113202d64a9956"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('e87aa745-ade5-4b12-8264-6be944ecc951'::uuid,'SPEED OF SOUND EQUATION IN AIR','MECHANISM','{}','(Formula: a = 20√T m/s for air, derived from rearranging the ideal gas law equation and specific conditions to represent the speed of sound propagation uniquely for air. )','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["28cecdc770c6a89ca87abe00cc7c001435c36f85ccea49414b7b38e0ca90e9c7a34ae80b18f1142de6f051bd2874e60296f40c3fe63d476edda0f8036922ba4c"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('48f80f7b-399b-4cc2-ad8d-bb49bb16f3ba'::uuid,'STATIC PRESSURE','PROPERTY','{}','Properties of a gas that are directly dependent on the gas density (\(\rho\)), absolute temperature (T), and gas constant (R)','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["ef6486c4db66ed7932b9bbcd3bcf3a0d6b5a54c10d03a87ac159ac59c84ab6e6992178768f4ec79d55ba89ac05ddc0f594857e23238ccbde9c113202d64a9956", "ef6486c4db66ed7932b9bbcd3bcf3a0d6b5a54c10d03a87ac159ac59c84ab6e6992178768f4ec79d55ba89ac05ddc0f594857e23238ccbde9c113202d64a9956"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('f0ca0180-bb6f-4939-9bde-e5661e7a76f8'::uuid,'MASS DENSITY (Ρ)','MATERIAL','{}','\( kg/m^3 \), indicating how concentrated mass is within a given volume','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["ef6486c4db66ed7932b9bbcd3bcf3a0d6b5a54c10d03a87ac159ac59c84ab6e6992178768f4ec79d55ba89ac05ddc0f594857e23238ccbde9c113202d64a9956", "ef6486c4db66ed7932b9bbcd3bcf3a0d6b5a54c10d03a87ac159ac59c84ab6e6992178768f4ec79d55ba89ac05ddc0f594857e23238ccbde9c113202d64a9956"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('d43a47a7-308c-4aeb-8971-c44ff859c6e6'::uuid,'GAS CONSTANT (R)','CONSTANT','{}','\( 287.14, J/(kg·K) \)','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["ef6486c4db66ed7932b9bbcd3bcf3a0d6b5a54c10d03a87ac159ac59c84ab6e6992178768f4ec79d55ba89ac05ddc0f594857e23238ccbde9c113202d64a9956", "ef6486c4db66ed7932b9bbcd3bcf3a0d6b5a54c10d03a87ac159ac59c84ab6e6992178768f4ec79d55ba89ac05ddc0f594857e23238ccbde9c113202d64a9956"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('d459247f-5abe-4cbf-b433-8ce14b1b7ea8'::uuid,'TEMPERATURE IN KELVIN (T)','PROPERTY','{}','\( K \), absolute temperature of the gas','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["ef6486c4db66ed7932b9bbcd3bcf3a0d6b5a54c10d03a87ac159ac59c84ab6e6992178768f4ec79d55ba89ac05ddc0f594857e23238ccbde9c113202d64a9956", "ef6486c4db66ed7932b9bbcd3bcf3a0d6b5a54c10d03a87ac159ac59c84ab6e6992178768f4ec79d55ba89ac05ddc0f594857e23238ccbde9c113202d64a9956"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('6d563bba-8682-4a79-b7ab-2ed0bdc55c11'::uuid,'FLOW CONTINUITY EQUATION FOR AN ELEMENTARY STREAMTUBE','MODEL','{}','Equation representing application of mass conservation law, given by \( m_1 = \rho_1 V_1 F_1 \) and \( m_2 = \rho_2 V_2 F_2 \)','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["ef6486c4db66ed7932b9bbcd3bcf3a0d6b5a54c10d03a87ac159ac59c84ab6e6992178768f4ec79d55ba89ac05ddc0f594857e23238ccbde9c113202d64a9956", "ef6486c4db66ed7932b9bbcd3bcf3a0d6b5a54c10d03a87ac159ac59c84ab6e6992178768f4ec79d55ba89ac05ddc0f594857e23238ccbde9c113202d64a9956"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('431f3340-08df-4470-ae5e-549cd207699b'::uuid,'LAW OF CONSERVATION OF MASS','PRINCIPLE','{}','\( \), fundamental physical principle stating that mass cannot be created or destroyed in an isolated system','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["ef6486c4db66ed7932b9bbcd3bcf3a0d6b5a54c10d03a87ac159ac59c84ab6e6992178768f4ec79d55ba89ac05ddc0f594857e23238ccbde9c113202d64a9956", "ef6486c4db66ed7932b9bbcd3bcf3a0d6b5a54c10d03a87ac159ac59c84ab6e6992178768f4ec79d55ba89ac05ddc0f594857e23238ccbde9c113202d64a9956"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('2d07385c-94a0-4f01-b122-35c47702795f'::uuid,'L. EULER','PERSON','{}','L. Euler, a renowned mathematician, is credited with publishing the derivation for the flow continuity equation in 1770. This accomplishment falls within his extensive body of work that significantly contributed to various fields including mathematics and fluid dynamics. Euler''s publication marked an important milestone in understanding the principles governing fluid flow, thereby leaving a lasting impact on both theoretical and applied sciences.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["ef6486c4db66ed7932b9bbcd3bcf3a0d6b5a54c10d03a87ac159ac59c84ab6e6992178768f4ec79d55ba89ac05ddc0f594857e23238ccbde9c113202d64a9956", "ef6486c4db66ed7932b9bbcd3bcf3a0d6b5a54c10d03a87ac159ac59c84ab6e6992178768f4ec79d55ba89ac05ddc0f594857e23238ccbde9c113202d64a9956"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('5d6abd55-a340-43d4-87d2-25a906c9a32b'::uuid,'STREAMTUBE','SYSTEM','{}','STREAMTUBE, a concept in fluid dynamics, represents a region through which airflow can be analyzed. Within this streamtube, the principles of Bernoulli''s equation apply, allowing for an understanding of pressure and velocity relationships within the flowing fluid. It is defined as a conceptual cylindrical section of a fluid stream or pipe where mass and momentum are conserved along the streamline, even when the cross-sections through which the fluid flows vary. This stable flow condition ensures that inStreamtube, properties such as mass flux and momentum can be accurately tracked and analyzed without external influences disrupting the system''s integrity.
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('fe48e4cd-38a8-486e-a3f1-4bf24979bebc'::uuid,'F₂','DEVICE','{}','Force at section 2-2, interacting with flow dynamics','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["b5612dfd5afd1a966867270904e7977f694cbe6e96b4be34a53c32ab6f48a581ba2e0825a6d9165aaeb6957d598461f699ff9ff6c7b4ff82bb2c2e2dba4929d9", "b5612dfd5afd1a966867270904e7977f694cbe6e96b4be34a53c32ab6f48a581ba2e0825a6d9165aaeb6957d598461f699ff9ff6c7b4ff82bb2c2e2dba4929d9"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('71266372-3d0b-454a-b756-771914cb6eb6'::uuid,'M₁','SYSTEM','{}','System representing the product of mass density ρ₁, volume V₁, and force F₁ at section 1-1','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["b5612dfd5afd1a966867270904e7977f694cbe6e96b4be34a53c32ab6f48a581ba2e0825a6d9165aaeb6957d598461f699ff9ff6c7b4ff82bb2c2e2dba4929d9", "b5612dfd5afd1a966867270904e7977f694cbe6e96b4be34a53c32ab6f48a581ba2e0825a6d9165aaeb6957d598461f699ff9ff6c7b4ff82bb2c2e2dba4929d9"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('7540e697-8412-4e18-8597-9027f635cbcd'::uuid,'Ρ₁','MATERIAL','{}','Mass density of substance at section 1-1','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["b5612dfd5afd1a966867270904e7977f694cbe6e96b4be34a53c32ab6f48a581ba2e0825a6d9165aaeb6957d598461f699ff9ff6c7b4ff82bb2c2e2dba4929d9", "b5612dfd5afd1a966867270904e7977f694cbe6e96b4be34a53c32ab6f48a581ba2e0825a6d9165aaeb6957d598461f699ff9ff6c7b4ff82bb2c2e2dba4929d9"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('66302f7b-f6da-4ff7-810d-192401eafc81'::uuid,'V₁','COMPONENT','{}','Flow velocity at section 1-1','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["b5612dfd5afd1a966867270904e7977f694cbe6e96b4be34a53c32ab6f48a581ba2e0825a6d9165aaeb6957d598461f699ff9ff6c7b4ff82bb2c2e2dba4929d9", "b5612dfd5afd1a966867270904e7977f694cbe6e96b4be34a53c32ab6f48a581ba2e0825a6d9165aaeb6957d598461f699ff9ff6c7b4ff82bb2c2e2dba4929d9"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('92e2e17b-adbd-4bcf-8354-1377eb736319'::uuid,'INCOMPRESSIBLE AIR','MATERIAL','{}','Assumption of constant density for air, useful in simplifying flow equations','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["b5612dfd5afd1a966867270904e7977f694cbe6e96b4be34a53c32ab6f48a581ba2e0825a6d9165aaeb6957d598461f699ff9ff6c7b4ff82bb2c2e2dba4929d9", "b5612dfd5afd1a966867270904e7977f694cbe6e96b4be34a53c32ab6f48a581ba2e0825a6d9165aaeb6957d598461f699ff9ff6c7b4ff82bb2c2e2dba4929d9"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('f64d139e-fad0-497e-a8ea-95867904cbae'::uuid,'BERNOULLI''S EQUATION','MODEL','{}','BERNOULLI''S EQUATION is a fundamental principle describing the behavior of fluids in steady flow conditions, specifically in low Mach number scenarios within a streamtube. This equation establishes the relationship between static pressure (\(P\)) and flow velocity (\(V\)), expressed as \( \Delta P + \frac{1}{2} \rho V^2 = \text{const.} \), where \(\rho\) is the fluid density. In simpler terms, it states that at any point in a streamline within such conditions, an increase in the kinetic energy (related to velocity) of a parcel of fluid results in a decrease in its static pressure.
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('c3695204-f5d9-4c91-b935-2612c1030ce8'::uuid,'DYNAMIC PRESSURE','MECHANISM','{}','Dynamic pressure, also known as velocity head, is calculated by the formula q=(ρ V²)/2, kg/m², representing the kinetic energy aspect of the flow','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["2d9fdd18fbb30369988222506fc6af76775a9970c876b024d039f1156ef34f3f17266c64951a1221502b45b881305de03ffdda41d4d7de0a29ea5d1a8aa25ad3", "2d9fdd18fbb30369988222506fc6af76775a9970c876b024d039f1156ef34f3f17266c64951a1221502b45b881305de03ffdda41d4d7de0a29ea5d1a8aa25ad3"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('dc52bb78-e1e3-4db8-8d69-a373580439ff'::uuid,'MODIFIED BERNOULLI''S EQUATION','MODEL','{}','Extends Bernoulli’s law to higher Mach numbers by incorporating compressibility, expressed as (k/(k-1)) * (P/ρ) + V²/2 = const. with k=1.4 for air, which includes both thermal and kinetic energy aspects of flow','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["2d9fdd18fbb30369988222506fc6af76775a9970c876b024d039f1156ef34f3f17266c64951a1221502b45b881305de03ffdda41d4d7de0a29ea5d1a8aa25ad3"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('4f72b753-0328-41a0-b4d8-bdbc74ade9b1'::uuid,'MACH NUMBER REGIME','SYSTEM','{}','Splits analysis into two regions: one where air can be assumed incompressible (M < 0.4) and another under adiabatic compression (M > 0.4)','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["2d9fdd18fbb30369988222506fc6af76775a9970c876b024d039f1156ef34f3f17266c64951a1221502b45b881305de03ffdda41d4d7de0a29ea5d1a8aa25ad3"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('e067e4c0-d02b-41e0-91d0-83fdbe669c54'::uuid,'ENERGY','MECHANISM','{}','Energy is conserved within an isolated streamtube, comprising static and dynamic components.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["2d9fdd18fbb30369988222506fc6af76775a9970c876b024d039f1156ef34f3f17266c64951a1221502b45b881305de03ffdda41d4d7de0a29ea5d1a8aa25ad3"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('88d76d7e-c27d-4f6c-ae8b-9a630f235ec0'::uuid,'INTERNAL ENERGY','MECHANISM','{}','Internal energy includes both thermal and kinetic components of the air in a streamtube.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["2d9fdd18fbb30369988222506fc6af76775a9970c876b024d039f1156ef34f3f17266c64951a1221502b45b881305de03ffdda41d4d7de0a29ea5d1a8aa25ad3"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('2b65490d-1bb9-4921-9fdd-32171ba5d4e4'::uuid,'POTENTIAL ENERGY OF PRESSURE','MECHANISM','{}','Potential energy of pressure is one component of the total system energy that can be expressed using Bernoulli''s equation.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["2d9fdd18fbb30369988222506fc6af76775a9970c876b024d039f1156ef34f3f17266c64951a1221502b45b881305de03ffdda41d4d7de0a29ea5d1a8aa25ad3"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('60121913-0ae2-425b-8d72-cb5df026f25e'::uuid,'THERMAL ENERGY','MECHANISM','{}','Thermal energy is a component of internal energy that changes at higher Mach numbers.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["2d9fdd18fbb30369988222506fc6af76775a9970c876b024d039f1156ef34f3f17266c64951a1221502b45b881305de03ffdda41d4d7de0a29ea5d1a8aa25ad3"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('f310f102-a95e-42b2-894b-e2e1e03dafcf'::uuid,'STAGNATION POINT','DEVICE','{}','Point on an aerodynamic body''s surface where velocity of the fluid coming into contact is zero and pressure equals total pressure; equation: \( P_0 = P + \frac{\rho V^2}{2} \)','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["c8c5897c0dcab93d58d200fc9f0c15f81f8e093f6028b3f4e6d11e4efab906fb1aee05f08e53d8e44917ed87c14b9f1efbe47459b1d09dc02a6aff9bd1212cf2", "c8c5897c0dcab93d58d200fc9f0c15f81f8e093f6028b3f4e6d11e4efab906fb1aee05f08e53d8e44917ed87c14b9f1efbe47459b1d09dc02a6aff9bd1212cf2"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('0c18ee8d-78dd-41e2-8c73-2e78bdd9e031'::uuid,'FREE-STREAM TEMPERATURE','MEASUREMENT','{}','Temperature of incoming air before interaction with an object in flow; used in computing increase in temperature at stagnation point','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["c8c5897c0dcab93d58d200fc9f0c15f81f8e093f6028b3f4e6d11e4efab906fb1aee05f08e53d8e44917ed87c14b9f1efbe47459b1d09dc02a6aff9bd1212cf2", "c8c5897c0dcab93d58d200fc9f0c15f81f8e093f6028b3f4e6d11e4efab906fb1aee05f08e53d8e44917ed87c14b9f1efbe47459b1d09dc02a6aff9bd1212cf2"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('ecc5c659-73f7-4c30-af27-553d30d9e581'::uuid,'MACH NUMBER','MEASUREMENT','{}','Ratio of velocity of a flow to speed of sound within the same medium, influences changes in air density, pressure, and temperature during acceleration or deceleration along streamtube','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["c8c5897c0dcab93d58d200fc9f0c15f81f8e093f6028b3f4e6d11e4efab906fb1aee05f08e53d8e44917ed87c14b9f1efbe47459b1d09dc02a6aff9bd1212cf2", "c8c5897c0dcab93d58d200fc9f0c15f81f8e093f6028b3f4e6d11e4efab906fb1aee05f08e53d8e44917ed87c14b9f1efbe47459b1d09dc02a6aff9bd1212cf2"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('fff41ed5-684a-402e-9b32-6366207a69a1'::uuid,'COMPRESSION','MECHANISM','{}','The process where air is compressed adiabatically, leading to changes in density, temperature, and pressure; described when the flow accelerates','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["c8c5897c0dcab93d58d200fc9f0c15f81f8e093f6028b3f4e6d11e4efab906fb1aee05f08e53d8e44917ed87c14b9f1efbe47459b1d09dc02a6aff9bd1212cf2"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('63f0bc1c-05c1-4ca9-a494-4e24f13e5b89'::uuid,'EXPANSION','MECHANISM','{}','The opposite of compression, where air expands adiabatically, also affecting density, temperature, and pressure; occurs during deceleration','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["c8c5897c0dcab93d58d200fc9f0c15f81f8e093f6028b3f4e6d11e4efab906fb1aee05f08e53d8e44917ed87c14b9f1efbe47459b1d09dc02a6aff9bd1212cf2"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('9c738c5c-c182-473c-8925-aaa5a059cb22'::uuid,'TU-204 AIRCRAFT','DEVICE','{}','The Tu-204 aircraft is an aircraft that can fly at Mach numbers between 0.7–0.8, causing a temperature increase of 28–37 °C at the leading edge of its wing and tail.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["8a05132b3fe6468e796b195f5b301f4a392a4852762a881f2f6f451a4d3069e72d72d16a8d77bb430f4e65e71133a9dc1b87587f1ec920086287adb4a9ebcd43"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('7b0e9e88-1f2a-45c7-a6b8-790793d459b5'::uuid,'WING','COMPONENT','{}','Component of the Tu-204 aircraft where temperature increases between 28-37 °C due to flying at Mach numbers of 0.7-0.8','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["8a05132b3fe6468e796b195f5b301f4a392a4852762a881f2f6f451a4d3069e72d72d16a8d77bb430f4e65e71133a9dc1b87587f1ec920086287adb4a9ebcd43"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('65d4be70-3b8c-4b67-8d8d-92e2fa773ea8'::uuid,'TAIL','COMPONENT','{}','Component of the Tu-204 aircraft where temperature increases between 28-37 °C due to flying at Mach numbers of 0.7-0.8','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["8a05132b3fe6468e796b195f5b301f4a392a4852762a881f2f6f451a4d3069e72d72d16a8d77bb430f4e65e71133a9dc1b87587f1ec920086287adb4a9ebcd43", "8a05132b3fe6468e796b195f5b301f4a392a4852762a881f2f6f451a4d3069e72d72d16a8d77bb430f4e65e71133a9dc1b87587f1ec920086287adb4a9ebcd43"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('6bee42db-413a-4df2-b1df-311a3ae25dc5'::uuid,'AIR STREAM','SYSTEM','{}','The air flowing near a body''s surface, with molecules having thermal motion in addition to overall flow velocity.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["8a05132b3fe6468e796b195f5b301f4a392a4852762a881f2f6f451a4d3069e72d72d16a8d77bb430f4e65e71133a9dc1b87587f1ec920086287adb4a9ebcd43"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('23244fec-db19-428e-b265-cd7bcc323de1'::uuid,'BODY SURFACE','COMPONENT','{}','The surface of an object, here referring to the part of the aircraft wing or tail adjacent to the boundary layer','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["8a05132b3fe6468e796b195f5b301f4a392a4852762a881f2f6f451a4d3069e72d72d16a8d77bb430f4e65e71133a9dc1b87587f1ec920086287adb4a9ebcd43"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('d9b2bd4c-c94a-485e-b462-0d25c35ded35'::uuid,'THERMAL VELOCITY','SYSTEM','{}','Components contributing to the velocity of air molecules, including thermal motion and overall flow velocity.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["8a05132b3fe6468e796b195f5b301f4a392a4852762a881f2f6f451a4d3069e72d72d16a8d77bb430f4e65e71133a9dc1b87587f1ec920086287adb4a9ebcd43"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('6a3d3dec-2fbe-4460-a2f0-5ecf3dd8ed2b'::uuid,'WAKE','COMPONENT','{}','A region behind an object where air velocity is reduced and characterized by small vortices, forming as a result of boundary layer effects.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["8a05132b3fe6468e796b195f5b301f4a392a4852762a881f2f6f451a4d3069e72d72d16a8d77bb430f4e65e71133a9dc1b87587f1ec920086287adb4a9ebcd43"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('9b9fb4f6-f7af-407f-9537-3c119cd9916a'::uuid,'VISCOUS FRICTION FORCES','COMPONENT','{}','Forces that arise from air viscosity acting within the boundary layer and gradually reducing surface air velocity from zero to external speed.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["8a05132b3fe6468e796b195f5b301f4a392a4852762a881f2f6f451a4d3069e72d72d16a8d77bb430f4e65e71133a9dc1b87587f1ec920086287adb4a9ebcd43"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('8634ec41-c39d-4ffb-b4b0-b7ceb40f7614'::uuid,'VORTEX','COMPONENT','{}','Small whirlpools or vortices that form within the wake region behind an object due to air flow changes.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["8a05132b3fe6468e796b195f5b301f4a392a4852762a881f2f6f451a4d3069e72d72d16a8d77bb430f4e65e71133a9dc1b87587f1ec920086287adb4a9ebcd43"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('180c7183-206f-444b-b31c-efa8a8e296f1'::uuid,'BOUNDARY_LAYER','SYSTEM','{}','The boundary layer system includes regions with relative motion of air layers and areas outside where viscous forces are not manifested, influencing the main flow','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["3053c3e0e510b67d9c0f2e360b922838ec77356125efa05de17c01bc410eb6ffc92a06adddf322c53e3588ce43a8eb93717e3f3237c86e91fcc9e704a2350af4"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('53f742bb-034d-41b1-8426-81462bf9e206'::uuid,'MAIN_FLOW','SYSTEM','{}','Outside the boundary layer, this area flows at constant velocity without significant manifestation of viscous forces but interacts with the boundary layer','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["3053c3e0e510b67d9c0f2e360b922838ec77356125efa05de17c01bc410eb6ffc92a06adddf322c53e3588ce43a8eb93717e3f3237c86e91fcc9e704a2350af4", "3053c3e0e510b67d9c0f2e360b922838ec77356125efa05de17c01bc410eb6ffc92a06adddf322c53e3588ce43a8eb93717e3f3237c86e91fcc9e704a2350af4"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('5da6ecc0-e2f3-4477-bc2d-5117020d2cde'::uuid,'LAMINAR_BOUNDARY_LAYER','SYSTEM','{}','A region within the boundary layer where air streams move parallel to the body surface without approaching or receding from it (Fig. 1.5a)','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["3053c3e0e510b67d9c0f2e360b922838ec77356125efa05de17c01bc410eb6ffc92a06adddf322c53e3588ce43a8eb93717e3f3237c86e91fcc9e704a2350af4", "3053c3e0e510b67d9c0f2e360b922838ec77356125efa05de17c01bc410eb6ffc92a06adddf322c53e3588ce43a8eb93717e3f3237c86e91fcc9e704a2350af4"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('96a7287c-a827-4577-a50b-e705c8249edf'::uuid,'TURBULENT_BOUNDARY_LAYER','SYSTEM','{}','In this part of the boundary layer, continuous mixing of air stream directions is observed with velocity variations through its thickness differing from laminar flow characteristics (Fig. 1.5b)','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["3053c3e0e510b67d9c0f2e360b922838ec77356125efa05de17c01bc410eb6ffc92a06adddf322c53e3588ce43a8eb93717e3f3237c86e91fcc9e704a2350af4", "3053c3e0e510b67d9c0f2e360b922838ec77356125efa05de17c01bc410eb6ffc92a06adddf322c53e3588ce43a8eb93717e3f3237c86e91fcc9e704a2350af4"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('25bc54dc-2651-4622-b875-516836f333fa'::uuid,'LAMINAR','MATERIAL','{}','A property of the boundary layer where individual air streams move parallel to the surface without approaching or receding from it (Fig. 1.5a)','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["3053c3e0e510b67d9c0f2e360b922838ec77356125efa05de17c01bc410eb6ffc92a06adddf322c53e3588ce43a8eb93717e3f3237c86e91fcc9e704a2350af4"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('44b562f7-2d1f-4df4-b8a1-5819cc014032'::uuid,'TURBULENT','MATERIAL','{}','A state within the boundary layer characterized by continuous mixing of stream directions with velocity variations through its thickness differing from laminar flow characteristics (Fig. 1.5b)','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["3053c3e0e510b67d9c0f2e360b922838ec77356125efa05de17c01bc410eb6ffc92a06adddf322c53e3588ce43a8eb93717e3f3237c86e91fcc9e704a2350af4"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('b9d270bf-026b-4186-8ff0-54cece37c3fb'::uuid,'BL_TRANSITION_POINT','PART','{}','The transition point where the laminar boundary layer transitions to a turbulent state under certain conditions (such as high velocity or surface roughness and irregularities) (Fig. 1.6','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["3053c3e0e510b67d9c0f2e360b922838ec77356125efa05de17c01bc410eb6ffc92a06adddf322c53e3588ce43a8eb93717e3f3237c86e91fcc9e704a2350af4"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('ad45c221-2084-40c1-a8d3-0a1bb94e6b73'::uuid,'PULSATIONS_OF_INCOMING_FLOW','COMPONENT','{}','A condition that can promote boundary layer turbulization and affect where the laminar-to-turbulent transition occurs (such as from propeller wakes or other factors','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["3053c3e0e510b67d9c0f2e360b922838ec77356125efa05de17c01bc410eb6ffc92a06adddf322c53e3588ce43a8eb93717e3f3237c86e91fcc9e704a2350af4"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('2fa5e413-64bf-48b3-8522-1b218508ec61'::uuid,'LEADING_EDGE_ROUGHNESS','COMPONENT','{}','A factor that influences the boundary layer''s transition to turbulence near the leading edge.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["3053c3e0e510b67d9c0f2e360b922838ec77356125efa05de17c01bc410eb6ffc92a06adddf322c53e3588ce43a8eb93717e3f3237c86e91fcc9e704a2350af4"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('25e8423d-a7a7-4851-8744-0244b3daf85c'::uuid,'BL','SYSTEM','{}','Boundary layer system on a streamlined body that interacts with main flow streamlines','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["c40bda9f92f9509b2f4cf8f58acd428d233827b65e6b3795bf3c84c6b0cd07198d4f407233cb1f635f5c7236c0e03dafba19429b95483d21113d9767a2577aa5"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('980e756b-9b14-4fb8-9d09-9c6f34de3397'::uuid,'MAIN FLOW','COMPONENT','{}','Main part of fluid flow passing over the wing or other streamlined body, characterized by interactions with decelerated boundary layer','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["c40bda9f92f9509b2f4cf8f58acd428d233827b65e6b3795bf3c84c6b0cd07198d4f407233cb1f635f5c7236c0e03dafba19429b95483d21113d9767a2577aa5"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('b7898201-59d6-4aa9-897a-2c15d9f7b2b0'::uuid,'STREAMLINED BODY','DEVICE','{}','Streamlined shape on which a boundary layer develops and interacts with main flows; typically found on wings','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["c40bda9f92f9509b2f4cf8f58acd428d233827b65e6b3795bf3c84c6b0cd07198d4f407233cb1f635f5c7236c0e03dafba19429b95483d21113d9767a2577aa5"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('f63876f2-760f-486e-b523-a9850af67329'::uuid,'PARTICULATE FLOW','MATERIAL','{}','Particles or molecules of the fluid as they move through different flow regions, characterized by their deceleration in boundary layers','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["c40bda9f92f9509b2f4cf8f58acd428d233827b65e6b3795bf3c84c6b0cd07198d4f407233cb1f635f5c7236c0e03dafba19429b95483d21113d9767a2577aa5"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('b4189d36-74ea-46cf-89c6-40da99efe3e7'::uuid,'FLOW TUBE','SYSTEM','{}','Imaginary tube around a streamline used to describe fluid properties and flow behavior','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["c40bda9f92f9509b2f4cf8f58acd428d233827b65e6b3795bf3c84c6b0cd07198d4f407233cb1f635f5c7236c0e03dafba19429b95483d21113d9767a2577aa5"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('df7f851d-4cee-468f-beb0-13db5f451259'::uuid,'REYNOLDS NUMBER','MODEL','{}','Dimensionless number used to predict flow regimes; characterized by inertial and viscous forces in fluid dynamics','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["c40bda9f92f9509b2f4cf8f58acd428d233827b65e6b3795bf3c84c6b0cd07198d4f407233cb1f635f5c7236c0e03dafba19429b95483d21113d9767a2577aa5"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('cd71d86b-d980-4dd6-8465-0d6c55b3099e'::uuid,'TURBULENT BL','STATE','{}','Boundary layer state characterized by higher relative velocity compared to its laminar counterpart, more prone to stopping and separation','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["c40bda9f92f9509b2f4cf8f58acd428d233827b65e6b3795bf3c84c6b0cd07198d4f407233cb1f635f5c7236c0e03dafba19429b95483d21113d9767a2577aa5"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('43ebad1f-0a28-470b-89d9-a0dc15a7ad7b'::uuid,'FIXED TOWERS','COMPONENT','{}','Fixed towers, also known as turbulators or flow spoilers, are device-like elements integrated into the wing surface (or other parts of an aircraft) as part of airframe design. Their primary function is to induce turbulence in specific areas of the boundary layer, thereby controlling airflow and preventing flow separation. Located on wings or other relevant sections of the vehicle, these small plates play a crucial role in enhancing aerodynamic efficiency and performance by manipulating the flow dynamics around the aircraft.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["c40bda9f92f9509b2f4cf8f58acd428d233827b65e6b3795bf3c84c6b0cd07198d4f407233cb1f635f5c7236c0e03dafba19429b95483d21113d9767a2577aa5", "c40bda9f92f9509b2f4cf8f58acd428d233827b65e6b3795bf3c84c6b0cd07198d4f407233cb1f635f5c7236c0e03dafba19429b95483d21113d9767a2577aa5"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('d6018c05-2b98-454d-9ebc-6262e8bdaf3e'::uuid,'CRITICAL VELOCITY','PROPERTY','{}','Velocity at which laminar boundary layer transitions to turbulence, influencing the onset of separation behaviors in different flow regimes','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["c40bda9f92f9509b2f4cf8f58acd428d233827b65e6b3795bf3c84c6b0cd07198d4f407233cb1f635f5c7236c0e03dafba19429b95483d21113d9767a2577aa5"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('de2a39c9-3ea8-47ee-8512-b3adfbc20ca4'::uuid,'LAMINAR FLOW','SYSTEM','{}','Flow regime characterized by smooth, steady fluid motion with minimal turbulence; often associated with lower Re values and reduced drag but higher risk of separation','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["c40bda9f92f9509b2f4cf8f58acd428d233827b65e6b3795bf3c84c6b0cd07198d4f407233cb1f635f5c7236c0e03dafba19429b95483d21113d9767a2577aa5"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('0c470871-5a51-4e67-a91a-7e7c9c23c597'::uuid,'FLOW STALL','STATE','{}','Aerodynamic condition that occurs when airflow separation at wing surfaces leads to loss of lift and handling difficulties','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["c40bda9f92f9509b2f4cf8f58acd428d233827b65e6b3795bf3c84c6b0cd07198d4f407233cb1f635f5c7236c0e03dafba19429b95483d21113d9767a2577aa5"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('ea9887b4-feb6-4297-9cf3-bf4a615bc8b3'::uuid,'CRITICAL REYNOLDS NUMBER','PROPERTY','{}','Threshold value of Reynolds number at which laminar boundary layer transitions into turbulent state; critical for flow control and stability','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["c40bda9f92f9509b2f4cf8f58acd428d233827b65e6b3795bf3c84c6b0cd07198d4f407233cb1f635f5c7236c0e03dafba19429b95483d21113d9767a2577aa5"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('3efdfc17-eb5e-4a6b-a9bc-bad3555fe5dc'::uuid,'FLOW TURBULENTIZATION','PROCESS','{}','Procedure of creating small-scale vortices on the wing surface to induce turbulent boundary layers, reducing separation risks','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["c40bda9f92f9509b2f4cf8f58acd428d233827b65e6b3795bf3c84c6b0cd07198d4f407233cb1f635f5c7236c0e03dafba19429b95483d21113d9767a2577aa5"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('a60b51e0-f9e3-4ee9-8052-b8662b01491b'::uuid,'C CRITICAL REYNOLDS NUMBER','MECHANISM','{}','The mechanism that breaks down laminar structure in boundary layer when Re reaches a certain value','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('70702af1-ca8a-4750-806f-627e73f18b8d'::uuid,'RE_CR <10^5','NUMERIC','{}','Average assumption of the critical Reynolds number, which is 10^5 or close to it','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('51c6e273-7b6d-4603-bfef-ee71fc87ffb3'::uuid,'SMOOTH SURFACE FINISH','MECHANISM','{}','The smoothness quality of a surface that influences the increase in the critical Reynolds number with reduced turbulence and smoother surfaces','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69", "b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('a4341a4e-78eb-4a45-a478-3c1db8e58a62'::uuid,'FREE-STREAM TURBULENCE','MECHANISM','{}','Turbulence level affecting the critical Reynolds number, reducing its value as it increases','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69", "b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('1799a146-9912-48a9-b4c0-2ed4802205e5'::uuid,'STATIONARY SOURCE','SYSTEM','{}','A system where there is no motion of the source relative to the medium','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69", "b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('3b4a1b82-883f-4798-8b45-09bb35917d24'::uuid,'SPEED V < A','NUMERIC','{}','Source speed less than the local speed of sound','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69", "b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('add47cdf-32d0-4902-b8ca-716c70f0283e'::uuid,'SOURCE MOVING AT SPEED V = A','SYSTEM','{}','A system with a source having a speed equal to the local speed of sound','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69", "b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('481713d2-6cdf-487d-ad88-69690998e77b'::uuid,'SPEED V > A','NUMERIC','{}','Source speed greater than the local speed of sound','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69", "b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('b6591b75-c1e4-4a93-a977-c1c32bebf632'::uuid,'SUBSONIC FLOW','SYSTEM','{}','Flow occurring at speeds less than the local speed of sound, where weak disturbances warn air particles about source''s motion','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69", "b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('3c647bec-9431-4874-b97d-33f8e94ccf26'::uuid,'SUPERSONIC FLOW','SYSTEM','{}','A system with flow exceeding the speed of sound and characterized by bow shock waves forming due to strong disturbances lagging behind','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69", "b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('05d86c94-76ba-4592-a72c-396378142311'::uuid,'AXIAL_NORMAL力','PART','{}','Axial (normal) force is a component of the force vector and is responsible for tensile or compressive action along the axis Z','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["aea6c651ec0fecfc47e79f37f7a830a1f5a1d8931712fbbf248dce3638450697754592ecf22476fe4edc6597c8adadaaa0a8594141780b5e85c35377ad4d489c"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('fd4c10b9-7786-41ec-90ca-6d2325a2f3d6'::uuid,'WEAK DISTURBANCES','MECHANISM','{}','Small changes in pressure or other properties at points on a surface during subsonic streamline flows around solid objects; propagate at local speed of sound','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69", "b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('fa49e37b-de93-4bad-a293-e39f7c1bbe17'::uuid,'STRONG DISTURBANCES','MECHANISM','{}','Destructive wave formations such as shock waves, notably bow shocks occurring due to supersonic flight around bodies','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69", "b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('0f2efaff-96ef-42d1-b5fa-8a2c9871d2cb'::uuid,'SOURCE MOVING AT V < A','SYSTEM','{}','System where the source travels less than local sound speed, causing early warning signals of its motion through subsonic disturbance propagation','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69", "b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('7de62c73-be67-4e9d-86b2-bdbb554dc9d1'::uuid,'SOURCE MOVING AT V = A','SYSTEM','{}','System with a source traveling exactly at sound speed without generating or receiving shock waves','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69", "b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('7f7a6795-4fa5-4216-a9cd-6617492884ce'::uuid,'SOURCE MOVING AT V > A','SYSTEM','{}','A system where the source''s speed exceeds local sound speed, creating strong disturbances leading to shock wave formation','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69", "b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('a0f7a115-8c1d-4fe4-8a34-75c655560e74'::uuid,'WEAK-DISTURBANCE SOURCE DIRECTION ANGLE Μ WITH BOUNDARY WAVE','MODEL','{}','Angle between weak disturbance propagation and boundary waves; used in Mach number calculations','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69", "b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('a83b2fef-338f-4a01-8c74-46f9f505e65a'::uuid,'TRIANGLE ABC','MODEL','{}','Geometric triangle used in the derivation of Mach angle equations and relationships within aerodynamics','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69", "b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('65f11115-406e-45b5-8663-29b18a897a1e'::uuid,'TRUE FLIGHT SPEED V','MEASURED','{}','Actual velocity of an aircraft as it moves through space relative to surrounding air','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69", "b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('46e917b9-26dd-4d52-8e19-16f2ed2b23b7'::uuid,'SPEED OF SOUND A','PROPERTY','{}','Speed at which pressure waves can travel in the medium, crucial for defining Mach number and compressibility effects','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69", "b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('8573c36d-b46a-4574-8435-af5c967aaa93'::uuid,'RE_CR ≈ 10^5','NUMERIC','{}','Average assumption of the critical Reynolds number, which is approximately 10^5','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["b1ce24296a58526324fabc7ae6e490936e4736e1162bc2970189c9eac707fa913c796b5d317389c1344080f396eba1801f7b804ce60b31231b538920f900bf69"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('f78f4b0c-b15b-4b3d-9c3f-56d3e6c2cda6'::uuid,'SHOCK WAVE','SYSTEM','{}','A shock wave is a thin layer of highly compressed air where there''s a sharp change in parameters; it is formed by the summation of spherical weak-disturbance waves and can occur ahead of bodies moving at supersonic speeds','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["140849ef95f1aa236f070715a2a6cddfd885f755e3eb8ca55cf5dd8b0b359d1a34339ac5ff933b34606e834238fe27ad07a0518575e53661350563c1d4adc476"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('b3c95012-ae4d-4d26-9269-14a0c0fa8f34'::uuid,'CRITICAL MACH NUMBER','MODEL','{}','Critical Mach number (M_cr) marks the speed at which local flow velocity on an aircraft wing equals the speed of sound, signaling the onset of compressibility effects','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["140849ef95f1aa236f070715a2a6cddfd885f755e3eb8ca55cf5dd8b0b359d1a34339ac5ff933b34606e834238fe27ad07a0518575e53661350563c1d4adc476", "140849ef95f1aa236f070715a2a6cddfd885f755e3eb8ca55cf5dd8b0b359d1a34339ac5ff933b34606e834238fe27ad07a0518575e53661350563c1d4adc476"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('c950308b-f418-44d5-9504-3d9814a19adf'::uuid,'BOW SHOCK WAVE','PART','{}','A bow shock wave is a type of shock wave ahead of a blunt body where deceleration and compression occur abruptly; it can form during supersonic flow around revolution bodies or wings','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["140849ef95f1aa236f070715a2a6cddfd885f755e3eb8ca55cf5dd8b0b359d1a34339ac5ff933b34606e834238fe27ad07a0518575e53661350563c1d4adc476", "140849ef95f1aa236f070715a2a6cddfd885f755e3eb8ca55cf5dd8b0b359d1a34339ac5ff933b34606e834238fe27ad07a0518575e53661350563c1d4adc476"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('778fd889-929b-488e-af51-264eda0c6494'::uuid,'NORMAL SHOCK WAVE','MODEL','{}','Normal shock waves are formed when the direction of flight is perpendicular to the front, causing a sharp decrease in velocity; this leads to an increase in pressure, temperature, and density','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["140849ef95f1aa236f070715a2a6cddfd885f755e3eb8ca55cf5dd8b0b359d1a34339ac5ff933b34606e834238fe27ad07a0518575e53661350563c1d4adc476", "140849ef95f1aa236f070715a2a6cddfd885f755e3eb8ca55cf5dd8b0b359d1a34339ac5ff933b34606e834238fe27ad07a0518575e53661350563c1d4adc476"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('01663529-6c56-449a-8011-1685d41d19c7'::uuid,'OBLIQUE SHOCK WAVE','COMPONENT','{}','Oblique shock waves occur when flow crosses the shock front at an angle, forcing it to change direction during supersonic flight around wedges or sharp conical shapes; they are characterized by a decrease in velocity','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["140849ef95f1aa236f070715a2a6cddfd885f755e3eb8ca55cf5dd8b0b359d1a34339ac5ff933b34606e834238fe27ad07a0518575e53661350563c1d4adc476", "140849ef95f1aa236f070715a2a6cddfd885f755e3eb8ca55cf5dd8b0b359d1a34339ac5ff933b34606e834238fe27ad07a0518575e53661350563c1d4adc476"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('4b83c5f9-765a-40ed-85ee-e5d8f6e7506d'::uuid,'MAXIMUM ALLOWABLE OPERATIONAL MACH NUMBER (MMAX)','MODEL','{}','The Maximum Allowable Operational Mach Number (Mmax) refers to the highest speed at which an aircraft can operate safely without encountering detrimental effects from air compressibility, particularly at high altitudes. This critical parameter ensures the structural integrity and aerodynamic performance of the aircraft by preventing the onset of compressible flow, where air behaves in a manner that significantly deviates from ideal gases. By adhering to Mmax, aircraft designers and operators can mitigate risks associated with excessive speed, such as supersonic booms, drag increases, and potential damage to the airliner''s fuselage or engines due to shock waves. Thus, Mmax serves as an essential threshold for ensuring safe and efficient high-altitude flight operations for various aircraft types across different configurations and missions.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["140849ef95f1aa236f070715a2a6cddfd885f755e3eb8ca55cf5dd8b0b359d1a34339ac5ff933b34606e834238fe27ad07a0518575e53661350563c1d4adc476", "140849ef95f1aa236f070715a2a6cddfd885f755e3eb8ca55cf5dd8b0b359d1a34339ac5ff933b34606e834238fe27ad07a0518575e53661350563c1d4adc476"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('e8a6716f-4497-4c0a-8a1b-4c62ff3b1588'::uuid,'WEDGE-SHAPED AIRFOIL','DEVICE','{}','"A wedge-shaped airfoil" is used to describe specific geometric shapes that are useful in supersonic flow simulations. It forms an attached shock near its nose during supersonic flow.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["d5f7ab80d0b58c2ff15ee04bad698949f6b490c19575d13aeeed20f431368326318208bb6da02831d9150fd85e6b6f8fb3378101b21c9f4f0102909b3e3bc2a3"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('fca8d7c6-8d28-4d66-a708-f9f8ce0414de'::uuid,'SHOCKWAVE','MECHANISM','{}','An "attached bow wave" or "oblique shock" formed due to changes in the supersonic flow, with intensity depending on the angle of the shock relative to the incoming flow direction','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["d5f7ab80d0b58c2ff15ee04bad698949f6b490c19575d13aeeed20f431368326318208bb6da02831d9150fd85e6b6f8fb3378101b21c9f4f0102909b3e3bc2a3", "d5f7ab80d0b58c2ff15ee04bad698949f6b490c19575d13aeeed20f431368326318208bb6da02831d9150fd85e6b6f8fb3378101b21c9f4f0102909b3e3bc2a3"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('09c8bc09-954c-4595-8a22-7853075ef5bd'::uuid,'OBLIQUE SHOCK','SYSTEM','{}','Refers to a type of shock that forms at an angle to the flow direction and reduces the velocity of the gas more gently than a normal shock wave, where mu (μ) is the inclination angle.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["d5f7ab80d0b58c2ff15ee04bad698949f6b490c19575d13aeeed20f431368326318208bb6da02831d9150fd85e6b6f8fb3378101b21c9f4f0102909b3e3bc2a3", "d5f7ab80d0b58c2ff15ee04bad698949f6b490c19575d13aeeed20f431368326318208bb6da02831d9150fd85e6b6f8fb3378101b21c9f4f0102909b3e3bc2a3"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('61048749-1154-4005-b66e-fcfc3a60f9a9'::uuid,'FLOW DECELERATION','MECHANISM','{}','A process in which supersonic flow slows down due to shock interaction, which can be of varying intensity based on flow parameters such as the angle of incidence and speed','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["d5f7ab80d0b58c2ff15ee04bad698949f6b490c19575d13aeeed20f431368326318208bb6da02831d9150fd85e6b6f8fb3378101b21c9f4f0102909b3e3bc2a3", "d5f7ab80d0b58c2ff15ee04bad698949f6b490c19575d13aeeed20f431368326318208bb6da02831d9150fd85e6b6f8fb3378101b21c9f4f0102909b3e3bc2a3"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('5593a074-e37e-4bf4-9370-ee19e1489325'::uuid,'SWEEP ANGLE (Χ)','MATERIAL','{}','"Sweep angle" refers to an angle used geometrically to describe swept wings, where χ values determine the categorization of wing designs as straight or swept. Specific values differentiate between straight and swept wings.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["d5f7ab80d0b58c2ff15ee04bad698949f6b490c19575d13aeeed20f431368326318208bb6da02831d9150fd85e6b6f8fb3378101b21c9f4f0102909b3e3bc2a3", "d5f7ab80d0b58c2ff15ee04bad698949f6b490c19575d13aeeed20f431368326318208bb6da02831d9150fd85e6b6f8fb3378101b21c9f4f0102909b3e3bc2a3"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('fee58418-f3b8-421f-867a-f60d4a4d272f'::uuid,'SWEPT WING','DEVICE','{}','Wings that are angled back at an angle (sweep angle) from the aircraft''s lateral axis to alter flow characteristics, increase critical Mach number M_cr and have other aerodynamic effects such as increased stability and reduced lift coefficient C_y_α','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["d5f7ab80d0b58c2ff15ee04bad698949f6b490c19575d13aeeed20f431368326318208bb6da02831d9150fd85e6b6f8fb3378101b21c9f4f0102909b3e3bc2a3", "d5f7ab80d0b58c2ff15ee04bad698949f6b490c19575d13aeeed20f431368326318208bb6da02831d9150fd85e6b6f8fb3378101b21c9f4f0102909b3e3bc2a3"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('c6619fa6-3171-4de4-ada0-76b587962856'::uuid,'STRAIGHT WING','DEVICE','{}','Wings that are not swept back and thus do not share the aerodynamic features of swept wings like higher C_x_α, lower sweepback, or different instability behaviors','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["d5f7ab80d0b58c2ff15ee04bad698949f6b490c19575d13aeeed20f431368326318208bb6da02831d9150fd85e6b6f8fb3378101b21c9f4f0102909b3e3bc2a3", "d5f7ab80d0b58c2ff15ee04bad698949f6b490c19575d13aeeed20f431368326318208bb6da02831d9150fd85e6b6f8fb3378101b21c9f4f0102909b3e3bc2a3"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('f8da0226-3ff2-4eff-8e17-fd92b898c48d'::uuid,'SWEPTBACK ANGLE (Χ)','MATERIAL','{}','Denotes the angle between the longitudinal axis of an aircraft and its wing. Greater values lead to more swept back geometry.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["d5f7ab80d0b58c2ff15ee04bad698949f6b490c19575d13aeeed20f431368326318208bb6da02831d9150fd85e6b6f8fb3378101b21c9f4f0102909b3e3bc2a3", "d5f7ab80d0b58c2ff15ee04bad698949f6b490c19575d13aeeed20f431368326318208bb6da02831d9150fd85e6b6f8fb3378101b21c9f4f0102909b3e3bc2a3"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('021c41fd-6d2d-4695-ba2c-fc31b73d77b5'::uuid,'DELTA WING','DEVICE','{}','"Delta wings" are low-aspect ratio, highly swept, triangular shaped airfoils that reduce lift due to their leading edge behavior but have higher critical angle of attack compared to conventional wings','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["d5f7ab80d0b58c2ff15ee04bad698949f6b490c19575d13aeeed20f431368326318208bb6da02831d9150fd85e6b6f8fb3378101b21c9f4f0102909b3e3bc2a3", "d5f7ab80d0b58c2ff15ee04bad698949f6b490c19575d13aeeed20f431368326318208bb6da02831d9150fd85e6b6f8fb3378101b21c9f4f0102909b3e3bc2a3"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('42974350-8ad3-442d-b90e-63653b448420'::uuid,'VELOCITY COMPONENTS Vₙ AND V_Τ','COMPONENT','{}','The breakdown of flow velocity into normal (Vₙ) and tangential (V_τ) components relative to a swept wing''s surface, aiding in aerodynamic force calculations.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["d5f7ab80d0b58c2ff15ee04bad698949f6b490c19575d13aeeed20f431368326318208bb6da02831d9150fd85e6b6f8fb3378101b21c9f4f0102909b3e3bc2a3", "d5f7ab80d0b58c2ff15ee04bad698949f6b490c19575d13aeeed20f431368326318208bb6da02831d9150fd85e6b6f8fb3378101b21c9f4f0102909b3e3bc2a3"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('b8ffdaa8-6b4b-49c3-aaf2-1ee1c38edbb1'::uuid,'L/D RATIO','MODEL','{}','"Lift-to-drag ratio" is an aerodynamic model used to describe the efficiency of wings where higher values indicate better performance. It decreases with sweep and delta wings due primarily to increased drag.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["d5f7ab80d0b58c2ff15ee04bad698949f6b490c19575d13aeeed20f431368326318208bb6da02831d9150fd85e6b6f8fb3378101b21c9f4f0102909b3e3bc2a3", "d5f7ab80d0b58c2ff15ee04bad698949f6b490c19575d13aeeed20f431368326318208bb6da02831d9150fd85e6b6f8fb3378101b21c9f4f0102909b3e3bc2a3"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('a10f4c44-c996-4978-b339-13c13de0005a'::uuid,'FLOW SEPARATION','MECHANISM','{}','A phenomenon occurring at wingtips in swept or delta wings, leading to poor lift distribution and can cause aircraft stalls under certain flight conditions','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["d5f7ab80d0b58c2ff15ee04bad698949f6b490c19575d13aeeed20f431368326318208bb6da02831d9150fd85e6b6f8fb3378101b21c9f4f0102909b3e3bc2a3", "d5f7ab80d0b58c2ff15ee04bad698949f6b490c19575d13aeeed20f431368326318208bb6da02831d9150fd85e6b6f8fb3378101b21c9f4f0102909b3e3bc2a3"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('89b342dc-d24c-4cb2-8ea9-77bb81bc91fc'::uuid,'ADVERSE YAW-ROLL COUPLING','EFFECT','{}','An aerodynamic effect where rudder deflections can lead to unintended rolling, a significant issue for sweptwinged aircraft.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["d5f7ab80d0b58c2ff15ee04bad698949f6b490c19575d13aeeed20f431368326318208bb6da02831d9150fd85e6b6f8fb3378101b21c9f4f0102909b3e3bc2a3", "d5f7ab80d0b58c2ff15ee04bad698949f6b490c19575d13aeeed20f431368326318208bb6da02831d9150fd85e6b6f8fb3378101b21c9f4f0102909b3e3bc2a3"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('ec7c8865-1b59-434c-a902-210bff84caf5'::uuid,'LATERAL STABILITY','COMPONENT','{}','"Dutch roll" oscillations are a result of increased lateral stability in swept wings due to the delayed flow separation and higher pressure drag on the trailing wing edge compared to the leading side','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["d5f7ab80d0b58c2ff15ee04bad698949f6b490c19575d13aeeed20f431368326318208bb6da02831d9150fd85e6b6f8fb3378101b21c9f4f0102909b3e3bc2a3", "d5f7ab80d0b58c2ff15ee04bad698949f6b490c19575d13aeeed20f431368326318208bb6da02831d9150fd85e6b6f8fb3378101b21c9f4f0102909b3e3bc2a3"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('cfcc3a1a-3290-4aac-8b7f-e8bf483bf712'::uuid,'WING DEFORMATION','MECHANISM','{}','Flight-induced changes in wing shape or stiffness, occurring as the aircraft experiences different forces at high speeds and angles of attack','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["d5f7ab80d0b58c2ff15ee04bad698949f6b490c19575d13aeeed20f431368326318208bb6da02831d9150fd85e6b6f8fb3378101b21c9f4f0102909b3e3bc2a3", "d5f7ab80d0b58c2ff15ee04bad698949f6b490c19575d13aeeed20f431368326318208bb6da02831d9150fd85e6b6f8fb3378101b21c9f4f0102909b3e3bc2a3"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('923db01b-5a6d-4b54-82d4-0fd3424a8011'::uuid,'FLOW SPILLAGE','MECHANISM','{}','Due to the high-aspect ratio or triangular shape (leading edge behavior) of delta wings, pressure on both upper and lower surfaces can equalize, reducing lift. This spillage causes adverse changes in aerodynamic performance.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["d5f7ab80d0b58c2ff15ee04bad698949f6b490c19575d13aeeed20f431368326318208bb6da02831d9150fd85e6b6f8fb3378101b21c9f4f0102909b3e3bc2a3"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('f821acea-4060-45b4-b0b2-f5a5ef8d74e6'::uuid,'VORTICES','MECHANISM','{}','Vortices are formed at the leading edge of the wing, increasing induced drag and reducing aerodynamic efficiency','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["0c3066d68702b9a95d3c6349961939cc0cdb2cfcee05bf4298cfa0536ee2bfedf182bf64728e68df41dcf90db30eb0fb1a9f16c3810a50ad768499953f0d9018"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('26e6927b-9753-496a-98c2-705df46de68d'::uuid,'CRITICAL ANGLE OF ATTACK','PROPERTY','{}','Delta wings have a significantly larger critical angle of attack compared to other types of wings','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["0c3066d68702b9a95d3c6349961939cc0cdb2cfcee05bf4298cfa0536ee2bfedf182bf64728e68df41dcf90db30eb0fb1a9f16c3810a50ad768499953f0d9018"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('44fa42ae-e949-4ee6-8a07-e0ec84e41bc1'::uuid,'LOW WAVE DRAG','PROPERTY','{}','Low wave drag is a characteristic feature of delta wings, contributing to their overall performance','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["0c3066d68702b9a95d3c6349961939cc0cdb2cfcee05bf4298cfa0536ee2bfedf182bf64728e68df41dcf90db30eb0fb1a9f16c3810a50ad768499953f0d9018"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('e6073e65-6e46-42e8-bdb9-e0cefd3e1b9f'::uuid,'HIGH STIFFNESS','PROPERTY','{}','Delta wings are known for having high stiffness, which contributes to structural integrity and performance','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["0c3066d68702b9a95d3c6349961939cc0cdb2cfcee05bf4298cfa0536ee2bfedf182bf64728e68df41dcf90db30eb0fb1a9f16c3810a50ad768499953f0d9018"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('1d2ef426-7722-4bfd-a180-dbf42056530d'::uuid,'STRUCTURAL DEPTH','PROPERTY','{}','Greater structural depth is a characteristic feature of delta wings that enhances their robustness','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["0c3066d68702b9a95d3c6349961939cc0cdb2cfcee05bf4298cfa0536ee2bfedf182bf64728e68df41dcf90db30eb0fb1a9f16c3810a50ad768499953f0d9018"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('514920b1-21a9-4cc9-9341-dec6b1b0381e'::uuid,'INDUCED DRAG','MECHANISM','{}','Induced drag is a result of trailing vortices, which decrease the lift and efficiency of an aircraft''s wing','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["0c3066d68702b9a95d3c6349961939cc0cdb2cfcee05bf4298cfa0536ee2bfedf182bf64728e68df41dcf90db30eb0fb1a9f16c3810a50ad768499953f0d9018"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('7f2a3271-c052-49d1-904e-ba3a3b532f63'::uuid,'WAVE DRAG','MECHANISM','{}','Wave drag occurs due to the interaction of airflow with discontinuities in a streamlined body, affecting the overall performance of the wing','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["0c3066d68702b9a95d3c6349961939cc0cdb2cfcee05bf4298cfa0536ee2bfedf182bf64728e68df41dcf90db30eb0fb1a9f16c3810a50ad768499953f0d9018"]}','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','2026-07-17 16:18:55.489892','aerodynamics_v1'),
	 ('c6e3ca49-b9ae-4248-aded-6df51167af72'::uuid,'STRENGTH OF MATERIALS','SYSTEM','{}','Strength of materials studies how engineering elements behave under external loads, including their strength, stiffness, and stability','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["4d17cb174f068dafef4955c063dda439983eb954edea151dfad9f5fd051527139fbc2909f4089dcf5c34e6677610c6d486b30f2b11e396bcfec49cedac0b1d4e"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('411a04f1-2597-4240-b710-24146760d4c1'::uuid,'ROD (BAR)','DEVICE','{}','Rod is a primary structural element in the field of strength of materials that can be studied to understand its behavior under forces. It is one of four main forms of elements in this study.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["4d17cb174f068dafef4955c063dda439983eb954edea151dfad9f5fd051527139fbc2909f4089dcf5c34e6677610c6d486b30f2b11e396bcfec49cedac0b1d4e", "4d17cb174f068dafef4955c063dda439983eb954edea151dfad9f5fd051527139fbc2909f4089dcf5c34e6677610c6d486b30f2b11e396bcfec49cedac0b1d4e"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('58fcfb5e-6e95-45d9-9389-20ef18e0f5b5'::uuid,'PLATE','DEVICE','{}','Plate, along with rod and shell, are principal structural elements considered in studies of strength of materials','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["4d17cb174f068dafef4955c063dda439983eb954edea151dfad9f5fd051527139fbc2909f4089dcf5c34e6677610c6d486b30f2b11e396bcfec49cedac0b1d4e", "4d17cb174f068dafef4955c063dda439983eb954edea151dfad9f5fd051527139fbc2909f4089dcf5c34e6677610c6d486b30f2b11e396bcfec49cedac0b1d4e"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('7d19a73a-22f2-47ca-817e-facb8e7581a9'::uuid,'SHELL','DEVICE','{}','Shell is a structural element covered under the scope of strength of materials that can behave differently from a rod or plate when subjected to external forces','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["4d17cb174f068dafef4955c063dda439983eb954edea151dfad9f5fd051527139fbc2909f4089dcf5c34e6677610c6d486b30f2b11e396bcfec49cedac0b1d4e", "4d17cb174f068dafef4955c063dda439983eb954edea151dfad9f5fd051527139fbc2909f4089dcf5c34e6677610c6d486b30f2b11e396bcfec49cedac0b1d4e"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('1d72abd5-7c97-44ca-b2a0-d61e6ad62161'::uuid,'SOLID BODY','DEVICE','{}','Solid body, alongside rods, plates, and shells, forms part of the main elements in studies regarding strength of materials. It is another form used for considering elements under analysis.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["4d17cb174f068dafef4955c063dda439983eb954edea151dfad9f5fd051527139fbc2909f4089dcf5c34e6677610c6d486b30f2b11e396bcfec49cedac0b1d4e", "4d17cb174f068dafef4955c063dda439983eb954edea151dfad9f5fd051527139fbc2909f4089dcf5c34e6677610c6d486b30f2b11e396bcfec49cedac0b1d4e"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('c477f200-75c7-4943-a922-ba6478fd2d9d'::uuid,'GALILEO GALILEI','PERSON','{}','Italian scientist famous for his contributions to the field of strength of materials','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["4d17cb174f068dafef4955c063dda439983eb954edea151dfad9f5fd051527139fbc2909f4089dcf5c34e6677610c6d486b30f2b11e396bcfec49cedac0b1d4e", "4d17cb174f068dafef4955c063dda439983eb954edea151dfad9f5fd051527139fbc2909f4089dcf5c34e6677610c6d486b30f2b11e396bcfec49cedac0b1d4e"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('e97171ee-a166-4895-809d-11175be2a4fb'::uuid,'EXTERNAL FORCES','MECHANISM','{}','External forces acting on a structural element, including both active forces and support reactions, play a crucial role in the study of how elements behave under load conditions.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["4d17cb174f068dafef4955c063dda439983eb954edea151dfad9f5fd051527139fbc2909f4089dcf5c34e6677610c6d486b30f2b11e396bcfec49cedac0b1d4e", "4d17cb174f068dafef4955c063dda439983eb954edea151dfad9f5fd051527139fbc2909f4089dcf5c34e6677610c6d486b30f2b11e396bcfec49cedac0b1d4e"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('57a9f1a1-c362-471e-9b15-895900ae324c'::uuid,'ACTIVE FORCES (LOADS)','MECHANISM','{}','Active or loads include concentrated, distributed along lines, and surface loads that cause deformation in an object. These are calculated to understand interactions in structural components.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["4d17cb174f068dafef4955c063dda439983eb954edea151dfad9f5fd051527139fbc2909f4089dcf5c34e6677610c6d486b30f2b11e396bcfec49cedac0b1d4e", "4d17cb174f068dafef4955c063dda439983eb954edea151dfad9f5fd051527139fbc2909f4089dcf5c34e6677610c6d486b30f2b11e396bcfec49cedac0b1d4e"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('683ac566-d6fc-46b5-9f81-858681c3a70f'::uuid,'SUPPORT REACTIONS','MECHANISM','{}','Support reactions arise due to active forces and need to be considered for stability and equilibrium of a structure','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["4d17cb174f068dafef4955c063dda439983eb954edea151dfad9f5fd051527139fbc2909f4089dcf5c34e6677610c6d486b30f2b11e396bcfec49cedac0b1d4e", "4d17cb174f068dafef4955c063dda439983eb954edea151dfad9f5fd051527139fbc2909f4089dcf5c34e6677610c6d486b30f2b11e396bcfec49cedac0b1d4e"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('c4980f3f-2936-40c2-84b2-26aefd962731'::uuid,'INTERNAL FORCES','MECHANISM','{}','Internal forces represent the reaction within parts of components that are subject to external loads, often resulting from cross-section cuts in structural elements like bars.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["4d17cb174f068dafef4955c063dda439983eb954edea151dfad9f5fd051527139fbc2909f4089dcf5c34e6677610c6d486b30f2b11e396bcfec49cedac0b1d4e", "4d17cb174f068dafef4955c063dda439983eb954edea151dfad9f5fd051527139fbc2909f4089dcf5c34e6677610c6d486b30f2b11e396bcfec49cedac0b1d4e"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('4ba299aa-0f43-42f7-81ce-74c9836854f7'::uuid,'CENTROID OF THE CROSS-SECTION','MATERIAL','{}','The centroid is a point where internal and external forces can be effectively reduced for analysis, serving as an important reference in strength of materials studies','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["4d17cb174f068dafef4955c063dda439983eb954edea151dfad9f5fd051527139fbc2909f4089dcf5c34e6677610c6d486b30f2b11e396bcfec49cedac0b1d4e", "4d17cb174f068dafef4955c063dda439983eb954edea151dfad9f5fd051527139fbc2909f4089dcf5c34e6677610c6d486b30f2b11e396bcfec49cedac0b1d4e"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('b7522b19-b943-4b15-a404-34cf099611ba'::uuid,'FORCES (MECHANISM)','INTERNAL FORCES','{}','Internal forces arise due to the application of external forces on structures. Analysis of these forces helps in understanding structural behavior under load conditions.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["4d17cb174f068dafef4955c063dda439983eb954edea151dfad9f5fd051527139fbc2909f4089dcf5c34e6677610c6d486b30f2b11e396bcfec49cedac0b1d4e"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('96eb3350-6de4-4c0a-bb76-4fb8e2e448aa'::uuid,'COORDINATE AXES X, Y, Z','MATERIAL','{}','Coordinate axes are used to decompose and analyze resultant force vectors and moments, aiding in the detailed analysis of internal forces in structural components','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["4d17cb174f068dafef4955c063dda439983eb954edea151dfad9f5fd051527139fbc2909f4089dcf5c34e6677610c6d486b30f2b11e396bcfec49cedac0b1d4e"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('d3b8801f-2ca3-4188-838f-831cfbed5efa'::uuid,'CENTROID','COMPONENT','{}','The centroid is used as a reference point for drawing coordinate axes on a cross-section','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["aea6c651ec0fecfc47e79f37f7a830a1f5a1d8931712fbbf248dce3638450697754592ecf22476fe4edc6597c8adadaaa0a8594141780b5e85c35377ad4d489c"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('7f00cfae-efc2-4d28-aeac-dac0acb5efeb'::uuid,'COORDINATE_AXES_X_Y_Z','SYSTEM','{}','Coordinates drawn through the centroid, consisting of X and Y in the plane of the section and Z perpendicular to it','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["aea6c651ec0fecfc47e79f37f7a830a1f5a1d8931712fbbf248dce3638450697754592ecf22476fe4edc6597c8adadaaa0a8594141780b5e85c35377ad4d489c"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('c4d1bdce-1650-49a6-bf2f-53ffd3dc15a3'::uuid,'SHEAR_FORCES_QX_QY','COMPONENT','{}','"Shear forces" Qx and Qy are components of the resultant force vector, acting perpendicularly to axial direction in the plane of cross-section','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["aea6c651ec0fecfc47e79f37f7a830a1f5a1d8931712fbbf248dce3638450697754592ecf22476fe4edc6597c8adadaaa0a8594141780b5e85c35377ad4d489c"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('fdaeee76-7c4e-43e5-a9c4-45f2bb3d006c'::uuid,'BENDING_MOMENTS_MX_MY','MECHANISM','{}','"Bending moments" Mx and My are moment vectors that cause bending along coordinate axes X and Y respectively','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["aea6c651ec0fecfc47e79f37f7a830a1f5a1d8931712fbbf248dce3638450697754592ecf22476fe4edc6597c8adadaaa0a8594141780b5e85c35377ad4d489c"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('d81f05c8-4869-4c9e-9385-3d79f6ef483e'::uuid,'TORQUE_MZ','COMPONENT','{}','Torque component Mz is an internal force causing rotational action around the Z axis, as per the force decomposition into moments','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["aea6c651ec0fecfc47e79f37f7a830a1f5a1d8931712fbbf248dce3638450697754592ecf22476fe4edc6597c8adadaaa0a8594141780b5e85c35377ad4d489c"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('d9067e49-def8-4bf6-bd8e-9ebc1d15e93a'::uuid,'METHOD_OF_SECTIONS','SYSTEM','{}','A method consisting of four steps for determining internal forces: cutting the bar by a cross-sectional plane, discarding one part, replacing action with internal forces, and equilibrating the remaining part; creates mnemonic "CUTD" to remember','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["aea6c651ec0fecfc47e79f37f7a830a1f5a1d8931712fbbf248dce3638450697754592ecf22476fe4edc6597c8adadaaa0a8594141780b5e85c35377ad4d489c"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('b51385bb-0f3b-4883-b0f2-496c45d08009'::uuid,'CUT_PLANE','COMPONENT','{}','A cross-sectional plane used in the method of sections for dividing the bar into two parts','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["aea6c651ec0fecfc47e79f37f7a830a1f5a1d8931712fbbf248dce3638450697754592ecf22476fe4edc6597c8adadaaa0a8594141780b5e85c35377ad4d489c"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('ba1a9f61-2fc4-460c-b7d2-00ab0ca4fff8'::uuid,'REMAINING_PART','PART','{}','Part of the bar left after cutting, which is then analyzed using equilibrium equations','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["aea6c651ec0fecfc47e79f37f7a830a1f5a1d8931712fbbf248dce3638450697754592ecf22476fe4edc6597c8adadaaa0a8594141780b5e85c35377ad4d489c", "aea6c651ec0fecfc47e79f37f7a830a1f5a1d8931712fbbf248dce3638450697754592ecf22476fe4edc6597c8adadaaa0a8594141780b5e85c35377ad4d489c"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('c516c03f-761c-4cfe-a076-5564cbaa1508'::uuid,'INTERNAL_FORCES_ACTORS','COMPONENT','{}','"Internal forces" are applied to the remaining part as a substitute for the discarded piece in the method of sections','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["aea6c651ec0fecfc47e79f37f7a830a1f5a1d8931712fbbf248dce3638450697754592ecf22476fe4edc6597c8adadaaa0a8594141780b5e85c35377ad4d489c", "aea6c651ec0fecfc47e79f37f7a830a1f5a1d8931712fbbf248dce3638450697754592ecf22476fe4edc6597c8adadaaa0a8594141780b5e85c35377ad4d489c"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('19a8e783-a097-407e-8767-4fd2a0f8252c'::uuid,'EQUILIBRIUM_EQUATIONS','MODEL','{}','"Equilibrium equations," six in total, sum up projections of all forces on X, Y, Z axes and sums of moments about these axes','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["aea6c651ec0fecfc47e79f37f7a830a1f5a1d8931712fbbf248dce3638450697754592ecf22476fe4edc6597c8adadaaa0a8594141780b5e85c35377ad4d489c", "aea6c651ec0fecfc47e79f37f7a830a1f5a1d8931712fbbf248dce3638450697754592ecf22476fe4edc6597c8adadaaa0a8594141780b5e85c35377ad4d489c"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('d66197cc-cdba-4877-822f-50c06fe8d95c'::uuid,'STRESS_AT_A_POINT','MATERIAL','{}','Stress is the intensity of the internal force at an arbitrary point, vector quantity representing stress, typically in terms of N/mm² or equivalent SI units','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["aea6c651ec0fecfc47e79f37f7a830a1f5a1d8931712fbbf248dce3638450697754592ecf22476fe4edc6597c8adadaaa0a8594141780b5e85c35377ad4d489c"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('0908dc21-1e0d-4f9b-b4f0-ed233fbdfa27'::uuid,'INFINITESIMAL_ELEMENT_DX_DY_DZ','COMPONENT','{}','Infinitesimally small element used for analyzing stresses and strains around a chosen point K within the solid body; dimensions dx × dy × dz','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["aea6c651ec0fecfc47e79f37f7a830a1f5a1d8931712fbbf248dce3638450697754592ecf22476fe4edc6597c8adadaaa0a8594141780b5e85c35377ad4d489c"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('469891d3-d180-4315-a86c-7f59f37c158d'::uuid,'RELATIVE_LINEAR_STRAINS_ΕX_ΕY','MATERIAL','{}','"Relative linear strains" εx, εy represent relative changes in lengths along X, Y axes respectively when a body deformed by given forces','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["aea6c651ec0fecfc47e79f37f7a830a1f5a1d8931712fbbf248dce3638450697754592ecf22476fe4edc6597c8adadaaa0a8594141780b5e85c35377ad4d489c"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('52fae80b-bd2c-40e2-adc3-c46f81ca9f3f'::uuid,'SHEAR_ANGLE_ΓXY','COMPONENT','{}','"Shear angle γxy" is a measure of the rotation experienced under shear stress; changes with coordinate system rotation around point K','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["aea6c651ec0fecfc47e79f37f7a830a1f5a1d8931712fbbf248dce3638450697754592ecf22476fe4edc6597c8adadaaa0a8594141780b5e85c35377ad4d489c"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('d6e3d3d4-00d0-4e3a-b0ad-846f28c08475'::uuid,'STRAIN_STATE_AT_A_POINT','MODEL','{}','The strain state at any given point within the material body, defined by six relative strains and includes εx, εy, εz, γxy, γyz, γzx representing various modes of deformation and shear','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["aea6c651ec0fecfc47e79f37f7a830a1f5a1d8931712fbbf248dce3638450697754592ecf22476fe4edc6597c8adadaaa0a8594141780b5e85c35377ad4d489c"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('e2df915c-2fe2-4ef3-a534-3a857234ad88'::uuid,'DEFORMATION','SYSTEM','{}','"Deformation" refers to the change in the dimensional arrangement of particles within a material body leading to either changes in dimensions or shape; composed of elastic and residual deformations','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["aea6c651ec0fecfc47e79f37f7a830a1f5a1d8931712fbbf248dce3638450697754592ecf22476fe4edc6597c8adadaaa0a8594141780b5e85c35377ad4d489c"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('830e66f3-bc76-41b0-a219-bb9b56cce9ce'::uuid,'ELASTIC_DEFORMATION','PART','{}','"Elastic deformation" is reversible, disappears after removal of external load, returning the material body back to its original shape and dimensions','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["aea6c651ec0fecfc47e79f37f7a830a1f5a1d8931712fbbf248dce3638450697754592ecf22476fe4edc6597c8adadaaa0a8594141780b5e85c35377ad4d489c"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('e324adb2-1105-4183-9019-77670a1b9d8a'::uuid,'EXTERNAL_LOAD','COMPONENT','{}','"External loads" are forces or moment vectors applied to a structural element causing it to deform; removed results in elastic return to original form for elastic deformation','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["aea6c651ec0fecfc47e79f37f7a830a1f5a1d8931712fbbf248dce3638450697754592ecf22476fe4edc6597c8adadaaa0a8594141780b5e85c35377ad4d489c"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('03c2aaa7-a6ba-4c1a-b0e8-538fff79b28a'::uuid,'RESIDUAL_DEFORMATION','PART','{}','"Residual deformation," irreversible, is permanently present after the removal of an external load affecting final shape and dimensions of the material body)("relationship"','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["aea6c651ec0fecfc47e79f37f7a830a1f5a1d8931712fbbf248dce3638450697754592ecf22476fe4edc6597c8adadaaa0a8594141780b5e85c35377ad4d489c"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('f9177ce7-31f9-4b31-975b-c3a412478353'::uuid,'ELASTIC DEFORMATION','SYSTEM','{}','A type of deformation that disappears after removing the external load and returns to its initial shape','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["11c9a21d6a0a9c5abe6f306c213575c0e955cd0c882c3149ea3e9f2422eeedd68b3e55978e3b0c3e8c74dc92b4bcf8a8e937a6aefe488e4d795bda2147b07272"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('545bf09c-bfc6-4956-b554-7f1d1083b9c8'::uuid,'RESIDUAL (PLASTIC) DEFORMATION','SYSTEM','{}','RESIDUAL (PLASTIC) DEFORMATION refers to a type of deformation characterized by permanent changes in the dimensions and/or shape of an object. This phenomenon occurs when an external force is applied to a material, causing it to rearrange its molecular structure. Once the load is removed or unloaded, these rearranged molecules do not return to their original state, resulting in a permanent alteration in the material''s form and size. This effect highlights the plastic nature of this deformation, where the material undergoes irreversible changes even after the external force has been removed.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["11c9a21d6a0a9c5abe6f306c213575c0e955cd0c882c3149ea3e9f2422eeedd68b3e55978e3b0c3e8c74dc92b4bcf8a8e937a6aefe488e4d795bda2147b07272", "11c9a21d6a0a9c5abe6f306c213575c0e955cd0c882c3149ea3e9f2422eeedd68b3e55978e3b0c3e8c74dc92b4bcf8a8e937a6aefe488e4d795bda2147b07272"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('d796d5ba-7009-4e6e-9983-0c65809a49aa'::uuid,'ELASTICITY','PROPERTY','{}','Elasticity refers to the inherent ability of a material, such as ELASTICITY, to undergo reversible or elastic deformation when subjected to an external force or load. Once the load is removed, the material returns to its original form and shape without any permanent changes or loss of structural integrity. This property allows materials to efficiently absorb energy from applied forces, storing it temporarily in the process of deformation, only to release that energy upon unloading. Thus, elasticity plays a crucial role in various applications where materials need to withstand temporary deformation before reverting back to their initial state, ensuring functionality and safety in structures, devices, and many other fields.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["11c9a21d6a0a9c5abe6f306c213575c0e955cd0c882c3149ea3e9f2422eeedd68b3e55978e3b0c3e8c74dc92b4bcf8a8e937a6aefe488e4d795bda2147b07272", "11c9a21d6a0a9c5abe6f306c213575c0e955cd0c882c3149ea3e9f2422eeedd68b3e55978e3b0c3e8c74dc92b4bcf8a8e937a6aefe488e4d795bda2147b07272"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('41df6503-deb9-4534-a899-331bac01c8ee'::uuid,'PLASTICITY','PROPERTY','{}','PLASTICITY is a fundamental property characterizing materials'' ability to undergo and retain deformations following the removal of external stress. This characteristic enables a material to remain permanently misshapen once the applied load is removed, indicating its persistent deformation or residual strain. Consequently, plasticity describes how materials can be shaped or molded after experiencing sufficient force, which persists even when that force is no longer present, making it crucial in various applications such as manufacturing, engineering, and construction.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["11c9a21d6a0a9c5abe6f306c213575c0e955cd0c882c3149ea3e9f2422eeedd68b3e55978e3b0c3e8c74dc92b4bcf8a8e937a6aefe488e4d795bda2147b07272", "11c9a21d6a0a9c5abe6f306c213575c0e955cd0c882c3149ea3e9f2422eeedd68b3e55978e3b0c3e8c74dc92b4bcf8a8e937a6aefe488e4d795bda2147b07272"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('35917606-2874-443b-a95c-2041b718c831'::uuid,'ISOTROPY','PROPERTY','{}','Material property where elastic behavior does not depend on direction (orientation), characterized by uniform response to stress in all directions','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["11c9a21d6a0a9c5abe6f306c213575c0e955cd0c882c3149ea3e9f2422eeedd68b3e55978e3b0c3e8c74dc92b4bcf8a8e937a6aefe488e4d795bda2147b07272", "11c9a21d6a0a9c5abe6f306c213575c0e955cd0c882c3149ea3e9f2422eeedd68b3e55978e3b0c3e8c74dc92b4bcf8a8e937a6aefe488e4d795bda2147b07272"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('036fc9f6-c573-4eeb-b600-6e5b1a154491'::uuid,'ANISOTROPY','MODEL','{}','ANISOTROPY is a condition characterized by varying elasticity characteristics in materials based on their orientation, differentiating it from isotropy which lacks such directional dependence. This property highlights how mechanical properties can differ significantly depending on the direction in which forces are applied to anisotropic materials, making them distinct from isotropic ones where properties are uniform in all directions.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["11c9a21d6a0a9c5abe6f306c213575c0e955cd0c882c3149ea3e9f2422eeedd68b3e55978e3b0c3e8c74dc92b4bcf8a8e937a6aefe488e4d795bda2147b07272", "11c9a21d6a0a9c5abe6f306c213575c0e955cd0c882c3149ea3e9f2422eeedd68b3e55978e3b0c3e8c74dc92b4bcf8a8e937a6aefe488e4d795bda2147b07272"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('334380bf-272c-4885-9570-10820ed65095'::uuid,'CONTINUOUS BODY','SYSTEM','{}','Body assumed as having no voids, cracks, and uniform material distribution for simplifying analysis purposes in strength of materials science','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["11c9a21d6a0a9c5abe6f306c213575c0e955cd0c882c3149ea3e9f2422eeedd68b3e55978e3b0c3e8c74dc92b4bcf8a8e937a6aefe488e4d795bda2147b07272", "11c9a21d6a0a9c5abe6f306c213575c0e955cd0c882c3149ea3e9f2422eeedd68b3e55978e3b0c3e8c74dc92b4bcf8a8e937a6aefe488e4d795bda2147b07272"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('d70f9703-92d7-4d16-8cb1-9af925f96a53'::uuid,'HOMOGENEOUS MATERIAL','MATERIAL','{}','The HOMOGENEOUS MATERIAL refers to a substance characterized by consistent properties that are uniform and identical throughout its entire composition. This consistency ensures that the material exhibits the same stress-strain relationships at every point within it, allowing for predictable mechanical behaviors under various loading conditions. The homogeneity of this material is assumed to uphold these uniform responses, making it suitable for applications where consistent performance across all parts is essential.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["11c9a21d6a0a9c5abe6f306c213575c0e955cd0c882c3149ea3e9f2422eeedd68b3e55978e3b0c3e8c74dc92b4bcf8a8e937a6aefe488e4d795bda2147b07272", "11c9a21d6a0a9c5abe6f306c213575c0e955cd0c882c3149ea3e9f2422eeedd68b3e55978e3b0c3e8c74dc92b4bcf8a8e937a6aefe488e4d795bda2147b07272"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('507a62ac-fe4e-48aa-be88-455ba01c677e'::uuid,'ISOTROPIC MATERIAL','PROPERTY','{}','Material that exhibits identical elastic behavior regardless of direction (no anisotropy); fundamental assumption in deriving equations used for calculations','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["11c9a21d6a0a9c5abe6f306c213575c0e955cd0c882c3149ea3e9f2422eeedd68b3e55978e3b0c3e8c74dc92b4bcf8a8e937a6aefe488e4d795bda2147b07272", "11c9a21d6a0a9c5abe6f306c213575c0e955cd0c882c3149ea3e9f2422eeedd68b3e55978e3b0c3e8c74dc92b4bcf8a8e937a6aefe488e4d795bda2147b07272"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('f0f5f015-7175-4f5d-9b72-18074393b01e'::uuid,'STRESS-PROPORTIONALITY PRINCIPLE','PRINCIPLE','{}','Assumption stating stresses at any point within a body are directly proportional to the strains experienced, foundational for linear elasticity theory','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["11c9a21d6a0a9c5abe6f306c213575c0e955cd0c882c3149ea3e9f2422eeedd68b3e55978e3b0c3e8c74dc92b4bcf8a8e937a6aefe488e4d795bda2147b07272", "11c9a21d6a0a9c5abe6f306c213575c0e955cd0c882c3149ea3e9f2422eeedd68b3e55978e3b0c3e8c74dc92b4bcf8a8e937a6aefe488e4d795bda2147b07272"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('37591448-167c-4596-9237-b7508b4333c2'::uuid,'SMALL DISPLACEMENTS ASSUMPTION','MODEL','{}','The entity "SMALL DISPLACEMENTS ASSUMPTION" pertains to an essential concept utilized in mechanics analysis. This assumption posits that the displacement of points within a deformable body is insignificant when compared to the overall dimensions of the body. By making this presumption, the mathematical expressions involved in analyzing such systems become much simpler, thereby facilitating easier physical understanding and more straightforward calculations. This simplified approach significantly enhances the practicality and applicability of mechanical models in various engineering and scientific fields where deformation can be considered small relative to the object''s size.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["11c9a21d6a0a9c5abe6f306c213575c0e955cd0c882c3149ea3e9f2422eeedd68b3e55978e3b0c3e8c74dc92b4bcf8a8e937a6aefe488e4d795bda2147b07272", "11c9a21d6a0a9c5abe6f306c213575c0e955cd0c882c3149ea3e9f2422eeedd68b3e55978e3b0c3e8c74dc92b4bcf8a8e937a6aefe488e4d795bda2147b07272"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('c263b57e-9e67-44b9-884a-52604a562b51'::uuid,'PRINCIPLE OF SUPERPOSITION','PRINCIPLE','{}','Postulate stating that resulting quantities (like stress, strain) from multiple loads equals sum of individual responses from each load acting alone','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["11c9a21d6a0a9c5abe6f306c213575c0e955cd0c882c3149ea3e9f2422eeedd68b3e55978e3b0c3e8c74dc92b4bcf8a8e937a6aefe488e4d795bda2147b07272", "11c9a21d6a0a9c5abe6f306c213575c0e955cd0c882c3149ea3e9f2422eeedd68b3e55978e3b0c3e8c74dc92b4bcf8a8e937a6aefe488e4d795bda2147b07272"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('59c5aa70-aec1-488e-8937-bf75a6814a79'::uuid,'AXIAL FORCE','MECHANISM','{}','Axial force is a component of internal forces in a member that acts along the axis of the member, responsible for tension or compression','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["5854fa6da46c1055a30f7e997508937bc42323fe61136724756e5091e3379dbf8c367eccb6153126d536d89eb329b32ca7d3a54fd8d2249be567613ad490f3aa"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('f2bef631-ae41-4716-8bf5-515b448c6293'::uuid,'BAR','DEVICE','{}','Bar is an object subjected to axial forces and composed of segments that can be analyzed using equilibrium equations','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["5854fa6da46c1055a30f7e997508937bc42323fe61136724756e5091e3379dbf8c367eccb6153126d536d89eb329b32ca7d3a54fd8d2249be567613ad490f3aa", "5854fa6da46c1055a30f7e997508937bc42323fe61136724756e5091e3379dbf8c367eccb6153126d536d89eb329b32ca7d3a54fd8d2249be567613ad490f3aa"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('06be1e53-a386-4e09-81de-2b59ed6391bb'::uuid,'SECTION 1–1','COMPONENT','{}','Section 1–1 divides the upper segment into parts used for isolation analysis in determining axial forces','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["5854fa6da46c1055a30f7e997508937bc42323fe61136724756e5091e3379dbf8c367eccb6153126d536d89eb329b32ca7d3a54fd8d2249be567613ad490f3aa", "5854fa6da46c1055a30f7e997508937bc42323fe61136724756e5091e3379dbf8c367eccb6153126d536d89eb329b32ca7d3a54fd8d2249be567613ad490f3aa"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('0d6930fd-1570-497b-a077-3a38c3dbf3dc'::uuid,'SECTION 2–2','COMPONENT','{}','Section 2–2 separates the lower segment, employed for isolating and calculating another set of axial forces','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["5854fa6da46c1055a30f7e997508937bc42323fe61136724756e5091e3379dbf8c367eccb6153126d536d89eb329b32ca7d3a54fd8d2249be567613ad490f3aa", "5854fa6da46c1055a30f7e997508937bc42323fe61136724756e5091e3379dbf8c367eccb6153126d536d89eb329b32ca7d3a54fd8d2249be567613ad490f3aa"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('0ab54153-7d56-46cd-8770-b5dc1006cd4c'::uuid,'POSITITIVE AXIAL FORCE N1','MATERIAL','{}','N1 is a positive force applied in the upper part after isolating it from the lower segment','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["5854fa6da46c1055a30f7e997508937bc42323fe61136724756e5091e3379dbf8c367eccb6153126d536d89eb329b32ca7d3a54fd8d2249be567613ad490f3aa"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('a5cd2a9a-81d9-4726-ba0d-97453f0bbc11'::uuid,'AXIS Z','COMPONENT','{}','Axis Z represents one of the coordinate axes used for defining vertical equilibrium equations and functions','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["5854fa6da46c1055a30f7e997508937bc42323fe61136724756e5091e3379dbf8c367eccb6153126d536d89eb329b32ca7d3a54fd8d2249be567613ad490f3aa", "5854fa6da46c1055a30f7e997508937bc42323fe61136724756e5091e3379dbf8c367eccb6153126d536d89eb329b32ca7d3a54fd8d2249be567613ad490f3aa"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('cbf55e7e-fb27-4427-b972-0d9a5d51d397'::uuid,'POSITIVE AXIAL FORCE N2','MATERIAL','{}','N2 describes a positive axial force applied to the upper part after isolating it from the lower segment, determined by the equilibrium equation including q z2','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["5854fa6da46c1055a30f7e997508937bc42323fe61136724756e5091e3379dbf8c367eccb6153126d536d89eb329b32ca7d3a54fd8d2249be567613ad490f3aa", "5854fa6da46c1055a30f7e997508937bc42323fe61136724756e5091e3379dbf8c367eccb6153126d536d89eb329b32ca7d3a54fd8d2249be567613ad490f3aa"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('c614eb4e-40b0-4a6c-8169-350953d306f4'::uuid,'STRESS','MECHANISM','{}','Stress is internal forces per unit area acting on cross-sections of a bar subject to tension or compression','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["5854fa6da46c1055a30f7e997508937bc42323fe61136724756e5091e3379dbf8c367eccb6153126d536d89eb329b32ca7d3a54fd8d2249be567613ad490f3aa", "5854fa6da46c1055a30f7e997508937bc42323fe61136724756e5091e3379dbf8c367eccb6153126d536d89eb329b32ca7d3a54fd8d2249be567613ad490f3aa"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('0205a460-23ad-4a10-ac85-aca338eab984'::uuid,'STRAIN','MATERIAL','{}','Strain is the fractional change in length, which can be absolute longitudinal strain (ε) and transverse strains (Δ*b* and Δ*h*) for a material under stress','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["5854fa6da46c1055a30f7e997508937bc42323fe61136724756e5091e3379dbf8c367eccb6153126d536d89eb329b32ca7d3a54fd8d2249be567613ad490f3aa", "5854fa6da46c1055a30f7e997508937bc42323fe61136724756e5091e3379dbf8c367eccb6153126d536d89eb329b32ca7d3a54fd8d2249be567613ad490f3aa"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('02cbf580-664d-4f2b-8721-177b0a4414af'::uuid,'POISSON''S RATIO','MECHANISM','{}','Poisson''s ratio (μ) quantifies the ratio of lateral strain to axial strain in materials, measured between 0 and 0.5','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["5854fa6da46c1055a30f7e997508937bc42323fe61136724756e5091e3379dbf8c367eccb6153126d536d89eb329b32ca7d3a54fd8d2249be567613ad490f3aa", "5854fa6da46c1055a30f7e997508937bc42323fe61136724756e5091e3379dbf8c367eccb6153126d536d89eb329b32ca7d3a54fd8d2249be567613ad490f3aa"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('0facd475-ff97-4977-8411-3b564506f060'::uuid,'HOOKE''S LAW','MODEL','{}','Hooke’s law relates normal stress (σ) to longitudinal strain (ε): σ = E ε, where E is Young''s modulus','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["5854fa6da46c1055a30f7e997508937bc42323fe61136724756e5091e3379dbf8c367eccb6153126d536d89eb329b32ca7d3a54fd8d2249be567613ad490f3aa", "5854fa6da46c1055a30f7e997508937bc42323fe61136724756e5091e3379dbf8c367eccb6153126d536d89eb329b32ca7d3a54fd8d2249be567613ad490f3aa"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('9d3bf4e4-44a4-4202-bf32-4c81e576d5c3'::uuid,'STIFFNESS','MATERIAL','{}','Tensile stiffness (EA) measures the resisting force per unit length of a member under tension or compression; units in MPa or kN/cm²','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["5854fa6da46c1055a30f7e997508937bc42323fe61136724756e5091e3379dbf8c367eccb6153126d536d89eb329b32ca7d3a54fd8d2249be567613ad490f3aa", "5854fa6da46c1055a30f7e997508937bc42323fe61136724756e5091e3379dbf8c367eccb6153126d536d89eb329b32ca7d3a54fd8d2249be567613ad490f3aa"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('c226481c-cc7f-4a79-9c11-e268580ef7cd'::uuid,'MAXIMUM SHEAR STRESS','COMPONENT','{}','The entity "MAXIMUM SHEAR STRESS" refers to a critical concept in material mechanics. Maximum shear stresses occur on inclined sections within materials or structures and represent a significant mechanical property affecting structural integrity and material behavior under stress. Specifically, these maximum shear stresses are half the magnitude of the normal stress acting at those points. This relationship indicates that for any given point where normal stress is present, if there is an inclined section experiencing this stress, the maximum shear stress on that section will be precisely one-half of the normal stress value.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["5854fa6da46c1055a30f7e997508937bc42323fe61136724756e5091e3379dbf8c367eccb6153126d536d89eb329b32ca7d3a54fd8d2249be567613ad490f3aa", "5854fa6da46c1055a30f7e997508937bc42323fe61136724756e5091e3379dbf8c367eccb6153126d536d89eb329b32ca7d3a54fd8d2249be567613ad490f3aa"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('eb9b41c5-52f7-48e4-b8b4-06b079583fa8'::uuid,'POSITIVE AXIAL FORCE N1','MATERIAL','{}','N1 is a positive force applied in the upper part after isolating it from the lower segment','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["5854fa6da46c1055a30f7e997508937bc42323fe61136724756e5091e3379dbf8c367eccb6153126d536d89eb329b32ca7d3a54fd8d2249be567613ad490f3aa"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('cf5a74da-2d86-4732-aa78-7ee8e3072f11'::uuid,'TENSILE STIFFNESS','MATERIAL','{}','"Tensile stiffness refers to the ability of a material or structure to resist deformation under axial tensile forces, which can be analyzed through stress and strain relations as described in Fig. 2.3b."','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["8b32ca58020b8954e30b675c9ce908081657304f06a9f556d8bd4206b77e8886584f55cedc137d75ad1fdfb5059f1147bcf8f982955b00ecb4cfb926e088a893"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('75ce9d3b-b49d-4c7f-a8a8-eb74e1ecd966'::uuid,'COMPRESSIVE STIFFNESS','MATERIAL','{}','"Compressive stiffness is analogous to tensile stiffness but measures the resistance against compression (compressive forces), with normal stresses acting on cross-sections of a bar or column under such loads, and shear stresses being significant on inclined sections at 45° to the longitudinal axis as illustrated in Fig. 2.3b."','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["8b32ca58020b8954e30b675c9ce908081657304f06a9f556d8bd4206b77e8886584f55cedc137d75ad1fdfb5059f1147bcf8f982955b00ecb4cfb926e088a893"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('ad69edf7-44b0-4dd7-b85c-d9f8e2184994'::uuid,'STRESS STATE','SYSTEM','{}','"Stress state involves the analysis of internal forces within a material. Normal stresses are observed on cross-sections, with no stress on longitudinal faces and shear stresses arising on inclined sections at 45° to the bar’s longitudinal axis as depicted in Fig. 2.3b."','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["8b32ca58020b8954e30b675c9ce908081657304f06a9f556d8bd4206b77e8886584f55cedc137d75ad1fdfb5059f1147bcf8f982955b00ecb4cfb926e088a893"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('7793ea28-610f-49e7-a657-e53200793331'::uuid,'SAINT-VENANT''S PRINCIPLE','MODEL','{}','"Saint-Venant’s Principle states that the way external forces are applied, only affects stress distribution over relatively short segments near load application points; this concept is confirmed by experimental evidence shown in Fig. 2.4."','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["8b32ca58020b8954e30b675c9ce908081657304f06a9f556d8bd4206b77e8886584f55cedc137d75ad1fdfb5059f1147bcf8f982955b00ecb4cfb926e088a893"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('e06552f5-dc7b-4945-b28e-af73006a83a9'::uuid,'SPECIMEN','COMPONENT','{}','"Specimens made of various materials serve as test subjects on machines and installations to determine material characteristics according to specific shapes, dimensions, and testing procedures defined by technical standards (Fig. 2.6)."','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["8b32ca58020b8954e30b675c9ce908081657304f06a9f556d8bd4206b77e8886584f55cedc137d75ad1fdfb5059f1147bcf8f982955b00ecb4cfb926e088a893"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('c3ed7302-f9a8-4d2b-a1f7-e3dcc310167b'::uuid,'TESTING MACHINE/INSTALLATION','DEVICE','{}','"Testing devices follow strict protocols to record the magnitudes of tensile or compressive forces and longitudinal strains, generating stress-strain diagrams that are analyzed for mechanical strength characteristics as described in Fig. 2.6."','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["8b32ca58020b8954e30b675c9ce908081657304f06a9f556d8bd4206b77e8886584f55cedc137d75ad1fdfb5059f1147bcf8f982955b00ecb4cfb926e088a893"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('893ff5aa-27bc-4848-8d1d-3f33ba3371cf'::uuid,'STRESS-STRAIN DIAGRAM','MODEL','{}','"Stress-strain diagrams plot relative longitudinal strain ε on the abscissa against normal stress σ on the ordinate, used to determine various mechanical properties such as proportionality limit, elastic limit, yield strength, ultimate tensile strength, and modulus of elasticity."','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["8b32ca58020b8954e30b675c9ce908081657304f06a9f556d8bd4206b77e8886584f55cedc137d75ad1fdfb5059f1147bcf8f982955b00ecb4cfb926e088a893"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('1cfe1429-5aa3-436c-86fa-8c319078958b'::uuid,'MODULUS OF ELASTICITY','MATERIAL','{}','"The slope of the straight-line portion OA on a stress-strain diagram equals the modulus of elasticity, which measures a material''s ability to resist deformation under tension or compression (Fig. 2.6)."','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["8b32ca58020b8954e30b675c9ce908081657304f06a9f556d8bd4206b77e8886584f55cedc137d75ad1fdfb5059f1147bcf8f982955b00ecb4cfb926e088a893"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('f309b580-ec65-4105-b61a-0f2ae2e6deb4'::uuid,'ELASTIC LIMIT Σ_У','MODEL','{}','"Elastic limit indicates the threshold stress at which residual longitudinal strain becomes minimal, typically within a range of 0.02…0.05%, marking the transition from elastic to potentially plastic deformation (Fig. 2.6)."','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["8b32ca58020b8954e30b675c9ce908081657304f06a9f556d8bd4206b77e8886584f55cedc137d75ad1fdfb5059f1147bcf8f982955b00ecb4cfb926e088a893"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('c7855083-3676-4e60-85e4-3b4ac18ea42a'::uuid,'YIELD STRENGTH Σ_Т','MODEL','{}','"Yield strength signifies the stress point at which strains increase without an associated increase in load, characterized by a plateau on the stress-strain diagram or by proof stress σ₀.₂ if no well-defined yield platea (Fig. 2.6)."','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["8b32ca58020b8954e30b675c9ce908081657304f06a9f556d8bd4206b77e8886584f55cedc137d75ad1fdfb5059f1147bcf8f982955b00ecb4cfb926e088a893"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('40237e28-9ead-4c23-ac72-11cc9a31fdd1'::uuid,'ULTIMATE TENSILE STRENGTH Σ_В','MODEL','{}','"Ultimate tensile strength is the highest stress level that a material can withstand before failing under load, represented as the maximum load point on the specimen in a tension test diagram (Fig. 2.6)."','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["8b32ca58020b8954e30b675c9ce908081657304f06a9f556d8bd4206b77e8886584f55cedc137d75ad1fdfb5059f1147bcf8f982955b00ecb4cfb926e088a893"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('7375ced4-28f0-489f-9994-9d29c6bd9535'::uuid,'LL₁','SEGMENT','{}','LL₁ is a straight line parallel to the initial portion OA','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["5d7651a3b3696fb6035ceec93c2758d36c8e35b07b25de5ba53e7352573cd4ea709e865b3da28cbc013cfd5ad720acff00ce21a93b8d112d4e1f91ad7a9a1179"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('5ac5c56e-d2e0-43c3-9dbe-ccc4bd8e6d3d'::uuid,'OL₁','SEGMENT','{}','OL₁ represents residual deformation Δl_ост','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["5d7651a3b3696fb6035ceec93c2758d36c8e35b07b25de5ba53e7352573cd4ea709e865b3da28cbc013cfd5ad720acff00ce21a93b8d112d4e1f91ad7a9a1179", "5d7651a3b3696fb6035ceec93c2758d36c8e35b07b25de5ba53e7352573cd4ea709e865b3da28cbc013cfd5ad720acff00ce21a93b8d112d4e1f91ad7a9a1179"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('8aca282e-38a1-4c77-97c8-006497aaa66e'::uuid,'L₁L₂','SEGMENT','{}','L₁L₂ indicates elastic deformation Δl_упр','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["5d7651a3b3696fb6035ceec93c2758d36c8e35b07b25de5ba53e7352573cd4ea709e865b3da28cbc013cfd5ad720acff00ce21a93b8d112d4e1f91ad7a9a1179", "5d7651a3b3696fb6035ceec93c2758d36c8e35b07b25de5ba53e7352573cd4ea709e865b3da28cbc013cfd5ad720acff00ce21a93b8d112d4e1f91ad7a9a1179"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('53dfdff6-02fb-4c1c-ac25-4eced8eacf93'::uuid,'TOTAL DEFORMATION AT POINT L','SYSTEM','{}','The total deformation at point L is the sum of residual and elastic deformations, i.e., Δl = Δl_ост + Δl_уппр','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["5d7651a3b3696fb6035ceec93c2758d36c8e35b07b25de5ba53e7352573cd4ea709e865b3da28cbc013cfd5ad720acff00ce21a93b8d112d4e1f91ad7a9a1179"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('4f8548c1-bb52-4017-8cb9-5cb30e61f2af'::uuid,'POINT L','POINT','{}','Point L marks the end of residual deformation and beginning of elastic deformation','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["5d7651a3b3696fb6035ceec93c2758d36c8e35b07b25de5ba53e7352573cd4ea709e865b3da28cbc013cfd5ad720acff00ce21a93b8d112d4e1f91ad7a9a1179", "5d7651a3b3696fb6035ceec93c2758d36c8e35b07b25de5ba53e7352573cd4ea709e865b3da28cbc013cfd5ad720acff00ce21a93b8d112d4e1f91ad7a9a1179"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('1c706369-4c25-4850-9618-e739eff84c23'::uuid,'H YSTERESIS LOOP','SYSTEM','{}','The hysteresis loop is a curved segment L₁L caused by irreversible energy losses','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["5d7651a3b3696fb6035ceec93c2758d36c8e35b07b25de5ba53e7352573cd4ea709e865b3da28cbc013cfd5ad720acff00ce21a93b8d112d4e1f91ad7a9a1179"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('9b461a4c-2a86-4bff-bce9-41b6de7323ae'::uuid,'POINT M','POINT','{}','Point M indicates the rupture or failure point of the specimen','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["5d7651a3b3696fb6035ceec93c2758d36c8e35b07b25de5ba53e7352573cd4ea709e865b3da28cbc013cfd5ad720acff00ce21a93b8d112d4e1f91ad7a9a1179", "5d7651a3b3696fb6035ceec93c2758d36c8e35b07b25de5ba53e7352573cd4ea709e865b3da28cbc013cfd5ad720acff00ce21a93b8d112d4e1f91ad7a9a1179"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('484ff571-e125-4c3a-8c7a-4b13d2be80cb'::uuid,'OM₂','SEGMENT','{}','Segment OM₂ represents total deformation before rupture Δl_р','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["5d7651a3b3696fb6035ceec93c2758d36c8e35b07b25de5ba53e7352573cd4ea709e865b3da28cbc013cfd5ad720acff00ce21a93b8d112d4e1f91ad7a9a1179", "5d7651a3b3696fb6035ceec93c2758d36c8e35b07b25de5ba53e7352573cd4ea709e865b3da28cbc013cfd5ad720acff00ce21a93b8d112d4e1f91ad7a9a1179"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('32a1e319-336d-4e86-908e-7f57333e2f66'::uuid,'OM₁','SEGMENT','{}','Segment OM₁ measures residual deformation after failure Δl_ост','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["5d7651a3b3696fb6035ceec93c2758d36c8e35b07b25de5ba53e7352573cd4ea709e865b3da28cbc013cfd5ad720acff00ce21a93b8d112d4e1f91ad7a9a1179", "5d7651a3b3696fb6035ceec93c2758d36c8e35b07b25de5ba53e7352573cd4ea709e865b3da28cbc013cfd5ad720acff00ce21a93b8d112d4e1f91ad7a9a1179"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('c8a90077-07dc-44e7-8fe0-0cc0830f5d65'::uuid,'STRESS-STRAIN DIAGRAM DURING UNLOADING AND RELOADING','SYSTEM','{}','It has a form similar to the loading diagram, with changes in material properties during unloading and reloading','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["5d7651a3b3696fb6035ceec93c2758d36c8e35b07b25de5ba53e7352573cd4ea709e865b3da28cbc013cfd5ad720acff00ce21a93b8d112d4e1f91ad7a9a1179"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('81f30c78-15be-4bd4-8918-67661d1f10f8'::uuid,'PROPORTIONALITY LIMIT INCREASES','PROPERTY','{}','The increase of the proportionality limit from σ_пц to σ_пц⁽ⁿ⁾ due to cold working or strain hardening','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["5d7651a3b3696fb6035ceec93c2758d36c8e35b07b25de5ba53e7352573cd4ea709e865b3da28cbc013cfd5ad720acff00ce21a93b8d112d4e1f91ad7a9a1179"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('298af4b4-fbd5-40db-8bb0-6249e027f0ba'::uuid,'YIELD PLATEAU DISAPPEARS','PROPERTY','{}','Strain hardening causes the yield plateau to disappear, indicating changes in material behavior','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["5d7651a3b3696fb6035ceec93c2758d36c8e35b07b25de5ba53e7352573cd4ea709e865b3da28cbc013cfd5ad720acff00ce21a93b8d112d4e1f91ad7a9a1179"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('e4d54505-e1ba-4a66-8fa9-d2df2b2f79c0'::uuid,'SEGMENT L₁M₂','SEGMENT','{}','Segment L₁M₂ shows deformation before failure after cold working, shorter than OM₂ due to decreased ductility','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["5d7651a3b3696fb6035ceec93c2758d36c8e35b07b25de5ba53e7352573cd4ea709e865b3da28cbc013cfd5ad720acff00ce21a93b8d112d4e1f91ad7a9a1179"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('67bfef73-498d-49fc-88d3-f2a7c20f88c8'::uuid,'GAUGE LENGTH L₀','MEASUREMENT','{}','Gauge length L₀ is measured before testing for determining the initial cross-sectional area A₀','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["5d7651a3b3696fb6035ceec93c2758d36c8e35b07b25de5ba53e7352573cd4ea709e865b3da28cbc013cfd5ad720acff00ce21a93b8d112d4e1f91ad7a9a1179"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('e9919230-adac-4a29-bbd4-d40e02d99325'::uuid,'CROSS-SECTINAL DIMENSIONS AT FRACITURE SITE','MEASUREMENT','{}','These dimensions are measured after failure to compute the final cross-sectional area A₁','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["5d7651a3b3696fb6035ceec93c2758d36c8e35b07b25de5ba53e7352573cd4ea709e865b3da28cbc013cfd5ad720acff00ce21a93b8d112d4e1f91ad7a9a1179"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('e5d72b9c-f91f-40c3-a8eb-59ec9c217d1b'::uuid,'PERCENTAGE ELONGATION AFTER FRACTURE Δ','CALCULATION','{}','δ = (L₁ − L₀)/L₀ × 100% computes the percentage change in length of the specimen before and after failure','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["5d7651a3b3696fb6035ceec93c2758d36c8e35b07b25de5ba53e7352573cd4ea709e865b3da28cbc013cfd5ad720acff00ce21a93b8d112d4e1f91ad7a9a1179"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('070083b4-ea5b-42cd-954d-79b7ad833e9e'::uuid,'% REDUCTION OF AREA Ψ','CALCULATION','{}','ψ = (A₀ − A₁)/A₀ × 100% measures the reduction in cross-sectional area, indicative of material hardening','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["5d7651a3b3696fb6035ceec93c2758d36c8e35b07b25de5ba53e7352573cd4ea709e865b3da28cbc013cfd5ad720acff00ce21a93b8d112d4e1f91ad7a9a1179"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('7c7daa8a-d29d-46b9-8139-e36db62096f3'::uuid,'CYLINDRICAL STEEL AND CAST-IRON SPECIMENS','DEVICE','{}','These specimens with diameters d₀ = 6…25 mm and L₀/d₀ ratio of 1…2 are used for compression tests','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["5d7651a3b3696fb6035ceec93c2758d36c8e35b07b25de5ba53e7352573cd4ea709e865b3da28cbc013cfd5ad720acff00ce21a93b8d112d4e1f91ad7a9a1179"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('9b79ef33-16a4-40aa-b419-d886a0e2b752'::uuid,'IRON SPECIMENS','MATERIAL','{}','Iron specimens with a diameter range of 6…25 mm are used in the experiments. The length to diameter ratio L₀/d₀ varies from 1 to 2.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["505daa15cbea14b13f2f7492eb480c452a365dc8a047f6c2292e974d156c07a2c5b349dee0fe6cfd6455953f8f53913648f5bcf35c450aa7516e5fb440c2377f"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('b9cb6644-4de4-4ce4-8d32-ad4a08cae595'::uuid,'STEEL SPECIMEN','MATERIAL','{}','Steel specimen which is used for tension and compression tests, its stress-strain diagram shows a linear portion initially, then bends at the yield point where the strength properties are calculated based on forces F_п and F_т. The ultimate compressive strength of steel equals its tensile strength if no distinct yield plateau can be observed.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["505daa15cbea14b13f2f7492eb480c452a365dc8a047f6c2292e974d156c07a2c5b349dee0fe6cfd6455953f8f53913648f5bcf35c450aa7516e5fb440c2377f", "505daa15cbea14b13f2f7492eb480c452a365dc8a047f6c2292e974d156c07a2c5b349dee0fe6cfd6455953f8f53913648f5bcf35c450aa7516e5fb440c2377f"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('6a88f643-cc86-46f1-92ac-70c31a17bcd6'::uuid,'COMPRESSION STRESS- STRAIN DIAGRAM','DEVICE','{}','A graphical representation used to observe the behavior of materials under compression, displaying both linear and non-linear portions in steel specimens and only a curving nature for cast iron specimens','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["505daa15cbea14b13f2f7492eb480c452a365dc8a047f6c2292e974d156c07a2c5b349dee0fe6cfd6455953f8f53913648f5bcf35c450aa7516e5fb440c2377f", "505daa15cbea14b13f2f7492eb480c452a365dc8a047f6c2292e974d156c07a2c5b349dee0fe6cfd6455953f8f53913648f5bcf35c450aa7516e5fb440c2377f"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('07b2343d-6fae-4c6d-a256-d6463199ab93'::uuid,'FORCE F_П AND F_Т','COMPONENT','{}','Forces measured during the stress-strain test on steel specimens; used to determine yield strength and the proportionality limit, while not applicable directly for cast iron as it does not have a clear linear portion','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["505daa15cbea14b13f2f7492eb480c452a365dc8a047f6c2292e974d156c07a2c5b349dee0fe6cfd6455953f8f53913648f5bcf35c450aa7516e5fb440c2377f", "505daa15cbea14b13f2f7492eb480c452a365dc8a047f6c2292e974d156c07a2c5b349dee0fe6cfd6455953f8f53913648f5bcf35c450aa7516e5fb440c2377f"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('cac70713-ffbe-4b67-829e-120931a4f161'::uuid,'YIELD STRENGTH OF STEEL IN COMPRESSION','SYSTEM','{}','It is closely equivalent to tensile strength. Determined after the initial stress-strain curve bends in steel specimens due to yielding','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["505daa15cbea14b13f2f7492eb480c452a365dc8a047f6c2292e974d156c07a2c5b349dee0fe6cfd6455953f8f53913648f5bcf35c450aa7516e5fb440c2377f", "505daa15cbea14b13f2f7492eb480c452a365dc8a047f6c2292e974d156c07a2c5b349dee0fe6cfd6455953f8f53913648f5bcf35c450aa7516e5fb440c2377f"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('96f56d07-aea6-4958-bdf9-e7937636bc8d'::uuid,'ULTIMATE COMPRESSIVE STRENGTH OF STEEL','COMPONENT','{}','(Conceptually equal but not practically determined) for steel, it is often considered as its tensile strength if no clear yield point can be observed. It''s typically equated with the maximum stress the material can withstand in compression without failure','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["505daa15cbea14b13f2f7492eb480c452a365dc8a047f6c2292e974d156c07a2c5b349dee0fe6cfd6455953f8f53913648f5bcf35c450aa7516e5fb440c2377f", "505daa15cbea14b13f2f7492eb480c452a365dc8a047f6c2292e974d156c07a2c5b349dee0fe6cfd6455953f8f53913648f5bcf35c450aa7516e5fb440c2377f"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('94ed5f69-b26a-4656-8eb8-3955cc864f39'::uuid,'CAST IRON SPECIMEN','MATERIAL','{}','Cast iron specimens used in tension and compression tests, failing by a sudden break rather than yielding; compressive strength calculated using F_max / A₀ formula.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["505daa15cbea14b13f2f7492eb480c452a365dc8a047f6c2292e974d156c07a2c5b349dee0fe6cfd6455953f8f53913648f5bcf35c450aa7516e5fb440c2377f", "505daa15cbea14b13f2f7492eb480c452a365dc8a047f6c2292e974d156c07a2c5b349dee0fe6cfd6455953f8f53913648f5bcf35c450aa7516e5fb440c2377f"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('eb133b23-9696-4c82-a949-1af5b7e933b0'::uuid,'LONGITUDINAL STRAINS','COMPONENT','{}','Small elongations seen during the compression test of cast iron where the specimen assumes a mild barrel shape with cracks at 45° to the axis. Failure is by shear along inclined planes','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["505daa15cbea14b13f2f7492eb480c452a365dc8a047f6c2292e974d156c07a2c5b349dee0fe6cfd6455953f8f53913648f5bcf35c450aa7516e5fb440c2377f", "505daa15cbea14b13f2f7492eb480c452a365dc8a047f6c2292e974d156c07a2c5b349dee0fe6cfd6455953f8f53913648f5bcf35c450aa7516e5fb440c2377f"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('fea00641-c64b-4452-b9c1-6b8bdbbabc5b'::uuid,'ULTIMATE TENSION STRENGTH OF STEEL','MODEL','{}','(Assumed characteristic property) The tensile strength that characterizes Steel''s resistance to failure under tensile stress, equal to its ultimate compressive strength due to their close proximity in most steels','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["505daa15cbea14b13f2f7492eb480c452a365dc8a047f6c2292e974d156c07a2c5b349dee0fe6cfd6455953f8f53913648f5bcf35c450aa7516e5fb440c2377f", "505daa15cbea14b13f2f7492eb480c452a365dc8a047f6c2292e974d156c07a2c5b349dee0fe6cfd6455953f8f53913648f5bcf35c450aa7516e5fb440c2377f"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('6baebf2d-c864-4627-883d-dcd30970b8c9'::uuid,'ALLOWABLE STRESS METHOD','MODEL','{}','A safety-based design approach where the allowable stress is a fraction of the material''s ultimate strength, used with a safety factor n > 1 for various uncertainties. It provides a way to ensure safe structural integrity and operates under conditions of known load scenarios','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["505daa15cbea14b13f2f7492eb480c452a365dc8a047f6c2292e974d156c07a2c5b349dee0fe6cfd6455953f8f53913648f5bcf35c450aa7516e5fb440c2377f", "505daa15cbea14b13f2f7492eb480c452a365dc8a047f6c2292e974d156c07a2c5b349dee0fe6cfd6455953f8f53913648f5bcf35c450aa7516e5fb440c2377f"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('716941d4-5d9b-4376-88d3-5d16c6fff132'::uuid,'ULTIMATE LOAD METHOD','MODEL','{}','(A strength design criterion) The ultimate load method evaluates system stability by the maximum stress or strain that can be tolerated before failure, often used in critical engineering applications requiring robustness against catastrophic failure, especially under variable loading conditions.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["505daa15cbea14b13f2f7492eb480c452a365dc8a047f6c2292e974d156c07a2c5b349dee0fe6cfd6455953f8f53913648f5bcf35c450aa7516e5fb440c2377f", "505daa15cbea14b13f2f7492eb480c452a365dc8a047f6c2292e974d156c07a2c5b349dee0fe6cfd6455953f8f53913648f5bcf35c450aa7516e5fb440c2377f"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('82e14225-4ade-40d0-99a3-5d6e8d1394a2'::uuid,'LIMIT STATE METHOD','MODEL','{}','(An advanced safety assessment methodology) This approach defines failure as reaching a specific safety limit state wherein the system ceases to perform its intended function; it is crucial for ensuring the safety and reliability of structures subjected to various types of loads over different time periods. The limit states could be ultimate (maximum load capacity), serviceability (minimum acceptable performance level during usage), or both.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["505daa15cbea14b13f2f7492eb480c452a365dc8a047f6c2292e974d156c07a2c5b349dee0fe6cfd6455953f8f53913648f5bcf35c450aa7516e5fb440c2377f", "505daa15cbea14b13f2f7492eb480c452a365dc8a047f6c2292e974d156c07a2c5b349dee0fe6cfd6455953f8f53913648f5bcf35c450aa7516e5fb440c2377f"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('9b21a2c4-b51b-40e5-b7fa-42357acd24d4'::uuid,'DANGEROUS STRESS Σ_ОП','COMPONENT','{}','(Term in allowable stress method) Representing an extreme level of stress in the structure, often linked to either yield strength or ultimate failure; used as a threshold for safe operational limits','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["505daa15cbea14b13f2f7492eb480c452a365dc8a047f6c2292e974d156c07a2c5b349dee0fe6cfd6455953f8f53913648f5bcf35c450aa7516e5fb440c2377f", "505daa15cbea14b13f2f7492eb480c452a365dc8a047f6c2292e974d156c07a2c5b349dee0fe6cfd6455953f8f53913648f5bcf35c450aa7516e5fb440c2377f"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('b29f49cc-06b9-44b7-a562-65426f7a9654'::uuid,'SAFETY FACTOR N','MODEL','{}','SAFETY FACTOR N is a critical component in allowable stress methods used to ensure the safe operation of structures under various load conditions. This coefficient accounts for variability and uncertainty factors such as material imperfections, environmental conditions, among others, guaranteeing that structures can withstand not only expected loads but also unexpected ones exceeding their calculated yield strength or ultimate capacity. By incorporating these variability and uncertainty factors, SAFETY FACTOR N plays a pivotal role in enhancing the reliability and safety of structural designs.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["505daa15cbea14b13f2f7492eb480c452a365dc8a047f6c2292e974d156c07a2c5b349dee0fe6cfd6455953f8f53913648f5bcf35c450aa7516e5fb440c2377f", "505daa15cbea14b13f2f7492eb480c452a365dc8a047f6c2292e974d156c07a2c5b349dee0fe6cfd6455953f8f53913648f5bcf35c450aa7516e5fb440c2377f"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('26d436b9-5308-45c1-96d0-45e9758e62eb'::uuid,'STRESS STATE AT A POINT','SYSTEM','{}','A systematic approach to analyze stress around a point K in a body, involving principal stresses and types of stress states (uniaxial, biaxial, triaxial)','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["233e80da46cbcaf9ec1723be666d6564d71c2b8b935f7be261d7531339ea192a2e9710a4ae0bf9365bb45e3c7975bf7e7ad0e869f8bd26f85dbe8f9c15f0cfbb"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('9be7cde6-c4e7-432c-b21a-5a93338a8304'::uuid,'PRINCIPAL PLANE','SYSTEM','{}','Faces where only normal stresses act on them at a given point in a body','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["233e80da46cbcaf9ec1723be666d6564d71c2b8b935f7be261d7531339ea192a2e9710a4ae0bf9365bb45e3c7975bf7e7ad0e869f8bd26f85dbe8f9c15f0cfbb"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('b3212bf0-01db-4749-88ec-47524aff50b8'::uuid,'PRINCIPAL STRESS','PART','{}','"σ₁", "σ₂", and "σ₃" where σ₁ is the largest, σ₂ is intermediate, and σ₃ is the smallest of the principal stresses under consideration. Principal stresses are derived from normal stresses on planes that remove shear stresses at a point in a body','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["233e80da46cbcaf9ec1723be666d6564d71c2b8b935f7be261d7531339ea192a2e9710a4ae0bf9365bb45e3c7975bf7e7ad0e869f8bd26f85dbe8f9c15f0cfbb"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('f552223a-518b-402f-b9d7-f1ca488a1f7c'::uuid,'UNIAXIAL STRESS STATE','SYSTEM','{}','One-dimensional stress condition where only one axis experiences significant stress, typically along with no shear stresses acting perpendicular to it','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["233e80da46cbcaf9ec1723be666d6564d71c2b8b935f7be261d7531339ea192a2e9710a4ae0bf9365bb45e3c7975bf7e7ad0e869f8bd26f85dbe8f9c15f0cfbb"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('9f6801f2-171d-40a7-8330-09bae17ae3ec'::uuid,'BIAXIAL STRESS STATE','SYSTEM','{}','Two-dimensional plane stress condition in which normal and shear stresses act on planes of a body. Principal planes are at 45° angles relative to the original coordinate axes for this type of stress state','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["233e80da46cbcaf9ec1723be666d6564d71c2b8b935f7be261d7531339ea192a2e9710a4ae0bf9365bb45e3c7975bf7e7ad0e869f8bd26f85dbe8f9c15f0cfbb"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('6a6f18a3-3c50-4af8-96a9-384da5e13981'::uuid,'TRIAXIAL STRESS STATE','SYSTEM','{}','Three-dimensional space where stress is present along three perpendicular axes, indicating complex interaction of stresses in all directions around a point. This involves the highest level of complexity in determining principal stresses and planes','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["233e80da46cbcaf9ec1723be666d6564d71c2b8b935f7be261d7531339ea192a2e9710a4ae0bf9365bb45e3c7975bf7e7ad0e869f8bd26f85dbe8f9c15f0cfbb"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('51188539-00a8-4bad-8aaf-3f07d58b3bc5'::uuid,'PLANE STRESS STATE','SYSTEM','{}','A specific type of biaxial stress condition confined to two dimensions of an element, with negligible normal or shear stresses acting along the third dimension perpendicular to the plane for thin plates or elements under certain loading conditions','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["233e80da46cbcaf9ec1723be666d6564d71c2b8b935f7be261d7531339ea192a2e9710a4ae0bf9365bb45e3c7975bf7e7ad0e869f8bd26f85dbe8f9c15f0cfbb"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('d9f433c1-c0aa-437d-9229-65b28ca22846'::uuid,'ALLOWABLE STRESS','MATERIAL','{}','Allowable stress is a critical limiting value used in determining structural requirements.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["233e80da46cbcaf9ec1723be666d6564d71c2b8b935f7be261d7531339ea192a2e9710a4ae0bf9365bb45e3c7975bf7e7ad0e869f8bd26f85dbe8f9c15f0cfbb"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('5daf0f8c-9142-48eb-b645-f58bdf219893'::uuid,'PRINCIPAL PLANES','PART','{}','Principal planes are specific orientations where no shear stresses act, aiding in the calculation of principal stresses (σ₁, σ₂, σ₃).','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["233e80da46cbcaf9ec1723be666d6564d71c2b8b935f7be261d7531339ea192a2e9710a4ae0bf9365bb45e3c7975bf7e7ad0e869f8bd26f85dbe8f9c15f0cfbb"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('426e9daa-1e85-4383-a4f2-cfde3b4d475f'::uuid,'PRINCIPAL STRESSES','MECHANISM','{}','Principal stresses are calculated by averaging principal stresses and adding or subtracting half of the square root term, and they act on planes inclined at 45° to the principal planes','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["ba4a007bb365126aa7e8e33dc56899336b43dcbbadb346956c52c0a58b0c709f36261ef69bd522c34f568acb3261563a7cc0f462aa9f987b85cee763f3d4ee40"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('9bf4cc44-799c-4f1a-8b73-04595589712f'::uuid,'NORMAL STRAINS Ε\_X, Ε\_Y','<MATERIAL','{}','Linear strains arise due to acting normal stresses, with coefficients (1/E) for σ\_x and (1/E) for σ\_y respectively','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["ba4a007bb365126aa7e8e33dc56899336b43dcbbadb346956c52c0a58b0c709f36261ef69bd522c34f568acb3261563a7cc0f462aa9f987b85cee763f3d4ee40", "ba4a007bb365126aa7e8e33dc56899336b43dcbbadb346956c52c0a58b0c709f36261ef69bd522c34f568acb3261563a7cc0f462aa9f987b85cee763f3d4ee40"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('8676f68b-534e-45fc-94c0-56b03512059c'::uuid,'SHEAR STRESS','MECHANISM','{}','SHEAR STRESS is a type of mechanical stress that occurs when parallel forces act tangentially along adjacent surfaces of contacting elements of a material. It is characterized by its action on mutually perpendicular planes and is mathematically related to the shear modulus (G) through Hooke''s law, expressed as τ = G γ, where γ represents the shear angle between affected elements. This relationship indicates that the magnitude of shear stress (τ) is directly proportional to the shear modulus (G) and the shear angle (γ), establishing a fundamental connection in material mechanics for understanding deformation under tangential forces.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["ba4a007bb365126aa7e8e33dc56899336b43dcbbadb346956c52c0a58b0c709f36261ef69bd522c34f568acb3261563a7cc0f462aa9f987b85cee763f3d4ee40", "ba4a007bb365126aa7e8e33dc56899336b43dcbbadb346956c52c0a58b0c709f36261ef69bd522c34f568acb3261563a7cc0f462aa9f987b85cee763f3d4ee40"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('89fe8541-ba63-4fce-a712-ec31ea6e1c70'::uuid,'YOUNG''S MODULUS E','MODEL','{}','Young''s modulus (E) relates linear strains to normal stresses in elastic bodies','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["ba4a007bb365126aa7e8e33dc56899336b43dcbbadb346956c52c0a58b0c709f36261ef69bd522c34f568acb3261563a7cc0f462aa9f987b85cee763f3d4ee40", "ba4a007bb365126aa7e8e33dc56899336b43dcbbadb346956c52c0a58b0c709f36261ef69bd522c34f568acb3261563a7cc0f462aa9f987b85cee763f3d4ee40"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('6b632849-bb1d-4b75-95d7-943f47aa132a'::uuid,'POISSON''S RATIO Μ','MECHANISM','{}','Poisson''s ratio (μ) modifies the relationship between longitudinal and lateral strains, impacting the values of ε\_x and ε\_y','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["ba4a007bb365126aa7e8e33dc56899336b43dcbbadb346956c52c0a58b0c709f36261ef69bd522c34f568acb3261563a7cc0f462aa9f987b85cee763f3d4ee40", "ba4a007bb365126aa7e8e33dc56899336b43dcbbadb346956c52c0a58b0c709f36261ef69bd522c34f568acb3261563a7cc0f462aa9f987b85cee763f3d4ee40"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('68d28dad-09e2-4ed5-b015-45bbd07443e8'::uuid,'SHEAR MODULUS G','MODEL','{}','Shear modulus (G) quantifies an elastic material''s stiffness with respect to pure shear deformation. It is related to E by: G = E / [2(1 + μ)]','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["ba4a007bb365126aa7e8e33dc56899336b43dcbbadb346956c52c0a58b0c709f36261ef69bd522c34f568acb3261563a7cc0f462aa9f987b85cee763f3d4ee40", "ba4a007bb365126aa7e8e33dc56899336b43dcbbadb346956c52c0a58b0c709f36261ef69bd522c34f568acb3261563a7cc0f462aa9f987b85cee763f3d4ee40"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('198f08cd-ba3b-4ccb-b75e-60acd3ac5e75'::uuid,'PRINCIPAL STRESS Σ\_1, Σ\_3','MECHANISM','{}','Principal stresses in a three-dimensional stress state are numerically equal to the maximum and minimum shear stresses (σ₁ = τ, σ₃ = −τ) when acted upon pure shear stress planes','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["ba4a007bb365126aa7e8e33dc56899336b43dcbbadb346956c52c0a58b0c709f36261ef69bd522c34f568acb3261563a7cc0f462aa9f987b85cee763f3d4ee40", "ba4a007bb365126aa7e8e33dc56899336b43dcbbadb346956c52c0a58b0c709f36261ef69bd522c34f568acb3261563a7cc0f462aa9f987b85cee763f3d4ee40"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('7ba4f7d7-7440-4312-9c55-fc97d4786a11'::uuid,'NORMAL STRESSES','PRINCIPAL STRESSES','{}','Normal stresses are the principal stresses within a material, ordered such that \( \sigma_1 \geq \sigma_2 \geq \sigma_3 \)','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["f1924e428147d032214a827807ef8f3ae81a4a9a21a9475005384b86a1f6a254489f6244b8458ae3e7a32a74c614e716d0e2e0063444283f4bb51a4c47f265a0"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('8aaebbdc-618f-4b99-aa31-b00a1dfac8f5'::uuid,'STRESS TENSOR','SYSTEM','{}','The stress tensor represents the state of stress at a point in a material and is expressed as a 3x3 matrix with components: \( \text{T}_{\sigma} = \begin{vmatrix} \sigma_x & \tau_{xy} & \tau_{xz} \\ \tau_{yx} & \sigma_y & \tau_{yz} \\ \tau_{zx} & \tau_{zy} & \sigma_z \end{vmatrix} \)','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["f1924e428147d032214a827807ef8f3ae81a4a9a21a9475005384b86a1f6a254489f6244b8458ae3e7a32a74c614e716d0e2e0063444283f4bb51a4c47f265a0"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('6cdb6b3b-2116-429c-86d4-6946ba432f91'::uuid,'PRINCIPAL STRESSES EQUATION','EQUATION','{}','The cubic equation for finding principal stresses is \( \sigma^3 - I_1\sigma^2 + I_2\sigma - I_3 = 0 \), where \(I_1, I_2, I_3\) are invariants of the stress tensor','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["f1924e428147d032214a827807ef8f3ae81a4a9a21a9475005384b86a1f6a254489f6244b8458ae3e7a32a74c614e716d0e2e0063444283f4bb51a4c47f265a0"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('e763a455-c4d2-49bb-b7a0-1b0b3bb1c16a'::uuid,'RELATIVE LINEAR STRAINS','Ε_X, Ε_Y, Ε_Z','{}','Relative linear strains describe the deformations in the material including elongations along the principal directions \( \varepsilon_x, \varepsilon_y, \varepsilon_z \)','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["f1924e428147d032214a827807ef8f3ae81a4a9a21a9475005384b86a1f6a254489f6244b8458ae3e7a32a74c614e716d0e2e0063444283f4bb51a4c47f265a0"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('9a3ee189-47dc-4a1d-a02b-1796ab2f2801'::uuid,'SHEAR STRAIN TENSOR','SYSTEM','{}','The shear strain tensor is expressed as a 3x3 matrix with components: \( \text{T}_{\epsilon} = \begin{vmatrix} \varepsilon_x & \gamma_{yx}/2 & \gamma_{zx}/2 \\ \gamma_{xy}/2 & \varepsilon_y & \gamma_{zy}/2 \\ \gamma_{xz}/2 & \gamma_{yz}/2 & \varepsilon_z \end{vmatrix} \)','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["f1924e428147d032214a827807ef8f3ae81a4a9a21a9475005384b86a1f6a254489f6244b8458ae3e7a32a74c614e716d0e2e0063444283f4bb51a4c47f265a0"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('0d14d920-7ade-4e32-be50-936b9125a3c2'::uuid,'PRINCIPAL STRAINS','Ε₁, Ε₂, Ε₃','{}','Principal strains are those that occur along the principal axes where shear strains vanish and satisfy \( \varepsilon_1 \geq \varepsilon_2 \geq \varepsilon_3 \)','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["f1924e428147d032214a827807ef8f3ae81a4a9a21a9475005384b86a1f6a254489f6244b8458ae3e7a32a74c614e716d0e2e0063444283f4bb51a4c47f265a0"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('71685b91-26d5-4e24-842b-54d9c8e8b1da'::uuid,'GENERALIZED HOOKES LAW','EQUATION','{}','Generalized Hooke''s law for an isotropic material is given by:\[\begin{align*}\varepsilon_x &= \frac{1}{E}[\sigma_x - \mu(\sigma_y + \sigma_z)], \\\gamma_{xy} &= \tau_{xy}/G, \\\varepsilon_y &= \frac{1}{E}[\sigma_y - \mu(\sigma_x + \sigma_z)], \\\gamma_{yz} &= \tau_{yz}/G, \\\varepsilon_z &= \frac{1}{E}[\sigma_z - \mu(\sigma_x + \sigma_y)], \\\gamma_{zx} &= \tau_{zx}/G.\end{align*}\]','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["f1924e428147d032214a827807ef8f3ae81a4a9a21a9475005384b86a1f6a254489f6244b8458ae3e7a32a74c614e716d0e2e0063444283f4bb51a4c47f265a0"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('197d6d5b-3501-46f2-b6d9-8059d1454619'::uuid,'PRESSURE','STRESS','{}','Normal stresses can include pressure, particularly in isotropic materials where \( \sigma_x = -p, \sigma_y = -p, \sigma_z = -p \)','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["f1924e428147d032214a827807ef8f3ae81a4a9a21a9475005384b86a1f6a254489f6244b8458ae3e7a32a74c614e716d0e2e0063444283f4bb51a4c47f265a0"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('ec32e429-83a7-4750-9268-5fd1b016ea61'::uuid,'INVARIENTS OF STRESS TENSOR','INVARIANTS','{}','The invariants of the stress tensor are given by I₁, I₂, I₃ and are constant for a given point regardless of orientation','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["f1924e428147d032214a827807ef8f3ae81a4a9a21a9475005384b86a1f6a254489f6244b8458ae3e7a32a74c614e716d0e2e0063444283f4bb51a4c47f265a0"]}','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','2026-07-17 16:45:38.667334','sopromat_v1'),
	 ('bb806af5-f8ea-4361-b05d-768a5d4797c8'::uuid,'GAUZES','MECHANISM','{}','GAUZES, components utilized in wind tunnel design, play a crucial role in enhancing flow quality and reducing turbulence levels. These gauzes were developed through advancements led by Gustave Eiffel, who incorporated them to improve the testing environment in his wind tunnels. Later, further refinements and experimental improvements contributed by L. Prandtl and other researchers built upon these initial developments, ensuring that gauges continued to serve as effective tools for achieving better flow quality in advanced wind tunnel systems. Through collaborative efforts and iterative improvements, GAUZES have become essential elements in the continuous refinement of aerodynamic testing methodologies.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["6c043286a724707e324c0aa9bd1e28f9c44eaaaa396eebf578400d5cb0cb167ac12bec61fdd45d7cfa6f63f53e15f92c08aeae6493271704143d122caa10dcec", "6c043286a724707e324c0aa9bd1e28f9c44eaaaa396eebf578400d5cb0cb167ac12bec61fdd45d7cfa6f63f53e15f92c08aeae6493271704143d122caa10dcec"]}','2026-07-17 13:19:24.183818','2026-07-17 13:19:24.183818','history_development_aeronautics');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('af7b60f0-97b2-4627-b500-e211d4f7c28c'::uuid,'ZHUKOVSKY TUNNEL','SYSTEM','{}','The Zhukovsky Tunnel, closely associated with the pioneering work of Nikolai Zhukovsky at Moscow University in Russia around 1902, refers to a wind tunnel that was constructed by Zhukovsky. The tunnel featured a straight square section design with windows, designed for aerodynamic research and experimentation. Although specific details about its exact specifications were not fully detailed in the available information, it is clear that this significant engineering project was completed during the same year or very close to 1902. This structure played an important role in advancing aviation technology and theoretical aeronautical science within the institution, marking a crucial milestone in early aerodynamics studies by Zhukovsky and his contemporaries.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["af0b7dc953d20f99423204bc6976714fb8bc794b04cf5ce8101cfceef20985a957bc6eca2691ec075aaa01420b302e2b2b0c8d5a5c0d508a6dabb65c91d84d5a", "f2ee2a48ece9792c2a41e9ef8523bac39c978616667ba97f16a7e58a5f9587b6b64e5046d7ff5d1443f11029123fc3893dc0c15cfc70ec93778bbea10e47f9f7"]}','2026-07-17 13:19:24.183818','2026-07-17 13:19:24.183818','history_development_aeronautics'),
	 ('508edd29-bd41-49f1-b6c0-f8e0fd0458e5'::uuid,'FULL SCALE TURBULENCE MEASUREMENTS','SYSTEM','{}','(Unclear) photograph of a full-size tunnel with fan smaller than the tunnel size, possibly different from the half-scale model used for measurements.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["af0b7dc953d20f99423204bc6976714fb8bc794b04cf5ce8101cfceef20985a957bc6eca2691ec075aaa01420b302e2b2b0c8d5a5c0d508a6dabb65c91d84d5a"]}','2026-07-17 13:19:24.183818','2026-07-17 13:19:24.183818','history_development_aeronautics'),
	 ('99b8b85d-9f18-4599-8b6e-24e87dff6695'::uuid,'LUDWIG PRANDTL''S FLOW CHANNEL','DEVICE','{}','LUDWIG PRANDTL''S FLOW CHANNEL was an experimental device utilized by Prandtl to examine diverse aspects of fluid dynamics. This apparatus played a crucial role in his investigations into starting and stopping flows, as well as the behavior of fluids around objects with varying profiles. As a result of these studies conducted in 1904, Prandtl proposed the boundary layer theory, a fundamental concept that has significantly impacted the field of fluid dynamics. The flow channel served as an indispensable tool for Prandtl''s groundbreaking work, contributing to his formulation of one of the key theories underpinning modern aerodynamics and hydrodynamics.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["f2ee2a48ece9792c2a41e9ef8523bac39c978616667ba97f16a7e58a5f9587b6b64e5046d7ff5d1443f11029123fc3893dc0c15cfc70ec93778bbea10e47f9f7", "f2ee2a48ece9792c2a41e9ef8523bac39c978616667ba97f16a7e58a5f9587b6b64e5046d7ff5d1443f11029123fc3893dc0c15cfc70ec93778bbea10e47f9f7"]}','2026-07-17 13:19:24.183818','2026-07-17 13:19:24.183818','history_development_aeronautics'),
	 ('6d29d362-8520-41c8-bf63-2c2639c2c54a'::uuid,'CASELLI ANEMOMETERS','DEVICE','{}','Devices for measuring airspeed used in the Zhukovsky''s wind tunnel alongside with micromanometer.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["ef3abb8012f6cecd19692d0c1a9ddb0f78b2d363feb6706a8c630bfb0c9dea1ef09ecd3ec44494748f1d9f3cbdbbbfde6c63f36fea8fe1cf8ffb674a245603d3"]}','2026-07-17 13:19:24.183818','2026-07-17 13:19:24.183818','history_development_aeronautics'),
	 ('5c4a3a85-038d-4cef-b109-594dd97e6e33'::uuid,'G.A. CROCCO''S WIND TUNNEL (1908 TUNNE)','SYSTEM','{}','A 1m by 0.8? square section open jet type wind tunnel, with a centrifugal blower fan and electric motor capable of speeds up to 29 m/s, used for testing airship models and propellers.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["ef3abb8012f6cecd19692d0c1a9ddb0f78b2d363feb6706a8c630bfb0c9dea1ef09ecd3ec44494748f1d9f3cbdbbbfde6c63f36fea8fe1cf8ffb674a245603d3"]}','2026-07-17 13:19:24.183818','2026-07-17 13:19:24.183818','history_development_aeronautics'),
	 ('94ff1bb0-4d8a-4860-8d8d-7bde9c26b9e2'::uuid,'DIFFUSER','MECHANISM','{}','The DIFFUSER, a critical component introduced into the RAF87 wind tunnel by the National Physical Laboratory (NPL), plays a vital role in reducing return turbulence within the wind tunnel system. This optimization ensures more accurate and reliable test results by improving airflow conditions and minimizing turbulent disturbances that could otherwise compromise aerodynamic testing accuracy. By addressing turbulence, the DIFFUSER enhances the overall performance and reliability of the RAF87 wind tunnel, making it an essential element for maintaining high standards in aeronautical research and development activities conducted within this facility.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["6c043286a724707e324c0aa9bd1e28f9c44eaaaa396eebf578400d5cb0cb167ac12bec61fdd45d7cfa6f63f53e15f92c08aeae6493271704143d122caa10dcec", "6c043286a724707e324c0aa9bd1e28f9c44eaaaa396eebf578400d5cb0cb167ac12bec61fdd45d7cfa6f63f53e15f92c08aeae6493271704143d122caa10dcec"]}','2026-07-17 13:19:24.183818','2026-07-17 13:19:24.183818','history_development_aeronautics'),
	 ('bd2bb085-db2b-419c-a5f0-eb546fbaf925'::uuid,'EIFFEL TUNNEL AT CHAMP DES MARS','DEVICE','{}','The EIFFEL TUNNEL AT CHAMP DES MARS is a significant engineering structure that has served as a vital facility for aerodynamic testing for over five decades. This large wind tunnel, featuring a 1.5 m diameter and an open jet design with a sealed room, was initially established by the renowned engineer Gustave Eiffel in 1909. The tunnel continued to be in active use until approximately 1960, signifying its enduring reliability and relevance in the field of aerodynamics throughout that period. This equipment played a crucial role in advancing our understanding of air flow dynamics and contributed to various technological developments during its operational lifespan.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["6c043286a724707e324c0aa9bd1e28f9c44eaaaa396eebf578400d5cb0cb167ac12bec61fdd45d7cfa6f63f53e15f92c08aeae6493271704143d122caa10dcec", "6c043286a724707e324c0aa9bd1e28f9c44eaaaa396eebf578400d5cb0cb167ac12bec61fdd45d7cfa6f63f53e15f92c08aeae6493271704143d122caa10dcec"]}','2026-07-17 13:19:24.183818','2026-07-17 13:19:24.183818','history_development_aeronautics'),
	 ('24c8d3d2-6f51-4b8e-95b9-74eb9b3c3652'::uuid,'HONEYCOMB','MECHANISM','{}','HONEYCOMB is an instrument designed to reduce swirling effects and enhance flow uniformity within wind tunnels. Its development and application are associated with significant advancements in wind tunnel engineering, stemming from both Gustave Eiffel''s research on closed return design and experiments conducted by Ludwig Prandtl. HONEYCOMB plays a crucial role in improving the quality and consistency of airflow, which is essential for accurate风洞实验的。这个装置通过减少湍流并提高气流均匀性，成为提升风洞技术水平的关键部件，不仅应用于埃菲尔设计的封闭环路风洞中，在普朗特的实验研究中也得到了验证和发展。
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('67323a96-b083-473a-b7f9-9ebcf232f517'::uuid,'CR体结构中的原子、分子或离子的空间周期性排列','SYSTEM','{}','crystalline structure involves the periodic arrangement of particles such as atoms, molecules, or ions in solids. It is determined by the spatial geometry of the crystal and its parameters.">','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["c443500ac401640e03812c68676ef2dc1b1766ba215011910bb4f476158764d339513dcb296b6be6ef5e21add844b582b4bb8f06949f4f8226ad3f8655aedb9b"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('47401964-c9ce-40a0-80d2-1bce24fa5410'::uuid,'CRYSTAL LATTICE','MODEL','{}','The CRYSTAL LATTICE is a geometric model that represents the spatial arrangement of atoms, molecules, or ions within a crystal. This model is defined by three non-coplanar vectors known as lattice parameters, denoted as ''a'', ''b'', and ''c''. These vectors are crucial for understanding the periodicity and distribution of structural units (such as atoms, molecules, or ions) in space. Essentially, the CRYSTAL LATTICE provides a comprehensive description of how these fundamental units are organized and positioned within the solid structure of materials at atomic and molecular levels.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["c443500ac401640e03812c68676ef2dc1b1766ba215011910bb4f476158764d339513dcb296b6be6ef5e21add844b582b4bb8f06949f4f8226ad3f8655aedb9b", "c443500ac401640e03812c68676ef2dc1b1766ba215011910bb4f476158764d339513dcb296b6be6ef5e21add844b582b4bb8f06949f4f8226ad3f8655aedb9b"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('dae0fa72-cfee-452a-84d7-901902ea7043'::uuid,'ATOMS, MOLECULES, IONS','COMPONENT','{}','The entities "atoms, molecules, and ions" represent the fundamental building blocks that constitute the crystalline structures found within solid materials. These units are meticulously organized in a periodic pattern, forming what is known as a crystal lattice. This arrangement significantly influences various physical properties of the material. Atoms, which can aggregate into molecules or dissociate to form ions, are the primary components responsible for creating this ordered structure. Together, they establish a regular spatial order that pervades throughout the crystalline substance, thereby dictating its macroscopic characteristics.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["c443500ac401640e03812c68676ef2dc1b1766ba215011910bb4f476158764d339513dcb296b6be6ef5e21add844b582b4bb8f06949f4f8226ad3f8655aedb9b", "c443500ac401640e03812c68676ef2dc1b1766ba215011910bb4f476158764d339513dcb296b6be6ef5e21add844b582b4bb8f06949f4f8226ad3f8655aedb9b"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('adc922e2-b37d-45c5-8374-0918e48cad3a'::uuid,'LATTICE PARAMETERS (A, B, C)','MATERIAL','{}','"Lattice parameters (A, B, C) are vectors that define the lengths and angles between them in the crystal lattice. These parameters are crucial for understanding the geometry and physical properties of crystalline structures. They play an essential role in determining key aspects of crystal morphology and material behavior."','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["c443500ac401640e03812c68676ef2dc1b1766ba215011910bb4f476158764d339513dcb296b6be6ef5e21add844b582b4bb8f06949f4f8226ad3f8655aedb9b", "c443500ac401640e03812c68676ef2dc1b1766ba215011910bb4f476158764d339513dcb296b6be6ef5e21add844b582b4bb8f06949f4f8226ad3f8655aedb9b"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('57f214a0-b198-4af9-bc07-7ebacfcc2d63'::uuid,'LATTICE PARAMETER','MECHANISM','{}','Three non-coplanar vectors (a, b, c) that define the positions in a lattice structure and help to reconstruct the spatial lattice completely>','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["be33f42641907295f83a337f4d06f95089e64774104fe7cec50db44a6a96d197ee77d4d46980237695981aeb6aed7f1827d31db11ce1ba5714986292f916aee0"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('d2a9fbec-d2f8-4f3d-8ac6-429bf9fe244a'::uuid,'SOLID STATE PHYSICS','SYSTEM','{}','SOLID STATE PHYSICS is a scientific field dedicated to investigating the physical properties of solid materials. This discipline utilizes quantum-statistical methods to comprehend the behavior and interactions among particles that form single-crystal lattices, thereby explaining the diverse properties exhibited by crystalline solids. Solid state physics explores not only the structure and composition but also delves into understanding how these microscopic interactions influence macroscopic properties of crystals, providing a bridge between fundamental physical laws and practical applications in materials science and engineering.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["c443500ac401640e03812c68676ef2dc1b1766ba215011910bb4f476158764d339513dcb296b6be6ef5e21add844b582b4bb8f06949f4f8226ad3f8655aedb9b", "c443500ac401640e03812c68676ef2dc1b1766ba215011910bb4f476158764d339513dcb296b6be6ef5e21add844b582b4bb8f06949f4f8226ad3f8655aedb9b"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('95be3ce1-4aa8-41f2-8c70-a5ec595d2982'::uuid,'PRACTICAL APPLICATIONS OF SOLIDS','SYSTEM','{}','The practical applications of solids extend beyond their natural states and involve a deep understanding of their crystalline structures. This knowledge is crucial for developing various technologies, including those used in space exploration and nuclear energy. The properties and structural analysis of these solids must be meticulously studied to effectively utilize them in everyday items and advanced technological applications. Thus, comprehending the intricate details of solid materials'' properties and structures paves the way for innovative practical uses across different fields, ensuring that we harness their full potential in real-world scenarios such as space missions and energy production processes.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["c443500ac401640e03812c68676ef2dc1b1766ba215011910bb4f476158764d339513dcb296b6be6ef5e21add844b582b4bb8f06949f4f8226ad3f8655aedb9b", "c443500ac401640e03812c68676ef2dc1b1766ba215011910bb4f476158764d339513dcb296b6be6ef5e21add844b582b4bb8f06949f4f8226ad3f8655aedb9b"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('7e3bec8e-f0d1-4a77-b547-77e6c8daa6e0'::uuid,'TEACHING AID','MODEL','{}','TEACHING AID refers to a comprehensive educational document crafted to support both teachers and learners in the study of physics. This resource encapsulates detailed explanations and discussions of fundamental physics laws and concepts, making it an essential tool for enhancing the understanding of these principles. It is designed to engage students through practical applications, offering solved problems that enable them to apply their knowledge effectively. Additionally, the document includes practice and self-assessment exercises, facilitating a deeper comprehension and reinforcement of learned material. Overall, TEACHING AID serves as a vital aid in ensuring both interactive and effective learning experiences within the realm of physics education.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["c443500ac401640e03812c68676ef2dc1b1766ba215011910bb4f476158764d339513dcb296b6be6ef5e21add844b582b4bb8f06949f4f8226ad3f8655aedb9b", "c443500ac401640e03812c68676ef2dc1b1766ba215011910bb4f476158764d339513dcb296b6be6ef5e21add844b582b4bb8f06949f4f8226ad3f8655aedb9b"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('945d9a95-d6a2-43db-81f8-2ac3300433aa'::uuid,'THEORETICAL EXPLANATIONS AND PROBLEMS','COMPONENT','{}','"Theoretical explanations and problems constitute a comprehensive component of the teaching aid. This section delves into the detailed descriptions of physical laws and concepts, providing students with a deep understanding through thorough explanations. It includes illustrative examples designed to elucidate complex ideas and problem-solving exercises for students to practice their skills. Additionally, self-assessment questions are incorporated to facilitate evaluation of comprehension and ensure that learners can gauge their own understanding effectively."','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["c443500ac401640e03812c68676ef2dc1b1766ba215011910bb4f476158764d339513dcb296b6be6ef5e21add844b582b4bb8f06949f4f8226ad3f8655aedb9b", "c443500ac401640e03812c68676ef2dc1b1766ba215011910bb4f476158764d339513dcb296b6be6ef5e21add844b582b4bb8f06949f4f8226ad3f8655aedb9b"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('cd50dcac-581a-4efa-88cf-1634717efaf2'::uuid,'FREE ELECTRON GAS','MODEL','{}','The Free Electron Gas is a simplified model utilized extensively in the field of solid-state physics. This model characterizes a system where electrons are not bound to any specific atoms or ions but instead contribute to the physical properties, notably electrical conductivity, observed within crystalline materials. In this model, the behavior of free electrons is assumed to be crucial for understanding and predicting various phenomena at the microscopic level in metals and semiconductors. This simplified framework allows physicists to simplify complex electron interactions into more manageable calculations and theories, providing insights into how these materials conduct electricity under different conditions.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["c443500ac401640e03812c68676ef2dc1b1766ba215011910bb4f476158764d339513dcb296b6be6ef5e21add844b582b4bb8f06949f4f8226ad3f8655aedb9b", "c443500ac401640e03812c68676ef2dc1b1766ba215011910bb4f476158764d339513dcb296b6be6ef5e21add844b582b4bb8f06949f4f8226ad3f8655aedb9b"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('48d1c22b-8ee4-4ed8-a2cd-1a1f5672917c'::uuid,'C体结构中的原子、分子或离子的空间周期性排列','COMPONENT','{}','"These components are regularly arranged in space to form the crystalline structure and determine physical properties such as rigidity and thermal conductivity.">','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["c443500ac401640e03812c68676ef2dc1b1766ba215011910bb4f476158764d339513dcb296b6be6ef5e21add844b582b4bb8f06949f4f8226ad3f8655aedb9b"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('86a07f33-4af5-4627-b0da-4d30221e6a1c'::uuid,'TEST QUESTIONS FOR SELF-ASSESSMENT','COMPONENT','{}','"Questions included in the teaching aid for students to evaluate their understanding of the material on crystalline structures and related properties." >','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["c443500ac401640e03812c68676ef2dc1b1766ba215011910bb4f476158764d339513dcb296b6be6ef5e21add844b582b4bb8f06949f4f8226ad3f8655aedb9b"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('a6db5719-d9ea-4477-b08a-979285519234'::uuid,'REFERENCE LIST','COMPONENT','{}','"A list at the end of the book containing additional resources for further exploration of topics related to crystalline structures. It supports deeper understanding through varied sources." >','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["c443500ac401640e03812c68676ef2dc1b1766ba215011910bb4f476158764d339513dcb296b6be6ef5e21add844b582b4bb8f06949f4f8226ad3f8655aedb9b"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('ab2309a9-38ea-4020-b361-c7653b60c523'::uuid,'CUBIC LATTICE','SYSTEM','{}','A system describing the mutual arrangement of atoms where the spatial arrangement follows specific geometric rules>','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["be33f42641907295f83a337f4d06f95089e64774104fe7cec50db44a6a96d197ee77d4d46980237695981aeb6aed7f1827d31db11ce1ba5714986292f916aee0"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('223c1a8f-931a-4495-839e-d2a0b75d7e32'::uuid,'LATTICE NODE','COMPONENT','{}','A point of intersection where translations meet to define the spatial lattice. May or may not be located at an atom''s center of mass>','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["be33f42641907295f83a337f4d06f95089e64774104fe7cec50db44a6a96d197ee77d4d46980237695981aeb6aed7f1827d31db11ce1ba5714986292f916aee0"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('f0066a8a-7842-4e19-b627-7507dcee9ec7'::uuid,'UNIT CELL','SYSTEM','{}','A unit cell is an essential geometric concept used to understand the structure of crystals. Specifically, it refers to the Wigner–Seitz cell process and is defined as a specific geometric shape in three-dimensional space. This shape repeats itself when translated in all three directions by integer multiples of its dimensions, thus generating the entire crystal structure. The unit cell is characterized by three angles (α, β, and γ) and three cell parameters, which together determine the shape and volume of the unit cell. Additionally, the Bravais method plays a crucial role in defining the smallest cell, or lattice point, that completely describes the crystal structure. This smallest unit encompasses all necessary information about the crystal’s symmetry and periodicity, making it a fundamental tool for crystallography and materials science research.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 3, "text_unit_ids": ["be33f42641907295f83a337f4d06f95089e64774104fe7cec50db44a6a96d197ee77d4d46980237695981aeb6aed7f1827d31db11ce1ba5714986292f916aee0", "de853bfe49f3934f3f091e273d7f490dd0799663d94d77bcd0cf7c1bbdee2bd4306455461b629588031c9581ff98e284a6026eebc4f0f469865a92862692afbc", "091c2bdcc29b966207eedad51eb8990dd1419da9354df05045326857c5fbf87d3c068e7c25d9b5302985a77f5c66a9a1a57d7703770ab76d586d72af540195a3"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('145ad87b-f20b-4535-8220-9cefa8678cf6'::uuid,'BRAVIS CELL','MODEL','{}','A type of unit cell used to describe diversity in crystal structures, differing by 14 lattices based on their symmetry>','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["be33f42641907295f83a337f4d06f95089e64774104fe7cec50db44a6a96d197ee77d4d46980237695981aeb6aed7f1827d31db11ce1ba5714986292f916aee0"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('9ccfc2c1-8be2-4468-92da-3805c8b4cb28'::uuid,'CELL PARAMETER','MEASUREMENT','{}','The distances between the nearest atoms along coordinate axes, chosen for a crystallographic coordinate system>','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["be33f42641907295f83a337f4d06f95089e64774104fe7cec50db44a6a96d197ee77d4d46980237695981aeb6aed7f1827d31db11ce1ba5714986292f916aee0"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('3f67ff6f-743e-42d8-8319-a363e2e3baef'::uuid,'OBLIQUE CRYSTALLOGRAPHIC COORDINATE SYSTEM','SYSTEM','{}','A coordinate system whose axes align with translation vectors in a lattice, used to describe unit cells geometrically','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["be33f42641907295f83a337f4d06f95089e64774104fe7cec50db44a6a96d197ee77d4d46980237695981aeb6aed7f1827d31db11ce1ba5714986292f916aee0"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('63b0c0e5-0b22-4eb6-a933-d6b9fa7c1576'::uuid,'SPACE LATTICE','SYSTEM','{}','Describes the three-dimensional array of points representing the positions in a crystal structure, defined by lattice parameters and nodes','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["be33f42641907295f83a337f4d06f95089e64774104fe7cec50db44a6a96d197ee77d4d46980237695981aeb6aed7f1827d31db11ce1ba5714986292f916aee0"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('9a6735c3-302f-4754-a1b3-b75e985020f5'::uuid,'VECTOR','MECHANISM','{}','Vectors (a, b, c) used to define the spatial arrangement of atoms in a crystal through the lattice parameters','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["be33f42641907295f83a337f4d06f95089e64774104fe7cec50db44a6a96d197ee77d4d46980237695981aeb6aed7f1827d31db11ce1ba5714986292f916aee0"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('c03095f7-e19e-4637-8342-f67ccfa58c09'::uuid,'PRIMITIVE CELL','SYSTEM','{}','A primitive cell is one where nodes are present only at the vertices of the parallelepiped','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["de853bfe49f3934f3f091e273d7f490dd0799663d94d77bcd0cf7c1bbdee2bd4306455461b629588031c9581ff98e284a6026eebc4f0f469865a92862692afbc"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('e0429ba8-c9ff-43b1-a046-2e74e2b58393'::uuid,'COMPLEX CELL','SYSTEM','{}','Complex cells, like non-primitive cells, reflect more accurately the symmetry of a crystal and have additional nodes in their structure','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["de853bfe49f3934f3f091e273d7f490dd0799663d94d77bcd0cf7c1bbdee2bd4306455461b629588031c9581ff98e284a6026eebc4f0f469865a92862692afbc"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('29c80cf1-c2c4-4f3f-9019-24da612600a2'::uuid,'BODY-CENTRED I-CELL','SYSTEM','{}','Body-centred (I) cells are a type of Bravais lattice with an additional node at the center of the cell','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["de853bfe49f3934f3f091e273d7f490dd0799663d94d77bcd0cf7c1bbdee2bd4306455461b629588031c9581ff98e284a6026eebc4f0f469865a92862692afbc"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('8667d25b-fb48-4901-84d5-8fd941ee5d68'::uuid,'FACE-CENTRED F-CELL','SYSTEM','{}','Face-centred (F) cells have additional nodes located at the centers of each face in their structure','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["de853bfe49f3934f3f091e273d7f490dd0799663d94d77bcd0cf7c1bbdee2bd4306455461b629588031c9581ff98e284a6026eebc4f0f469865a92862692afbc"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('520f89e3-c029-4c0c-b70a-6084dfc71240'::uuid,'BASE-CENTRED CELL','SYSTEM','{}','Base-centred cells have additional nodes at the centres of opposite faces and are used to describe certain types of Bravais lattices','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["de853bfe49f3934f3f091e273d7f490dd0799663d94d77bcd0cf7c1bbdee2bd4306455461b629588031c9581ff98e284a6026eebc4f0f469865a92862692afbc"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('fbbe0176-ed5f-4992-b8fb-2d1ca72524b8'::uuid,'CUBIC CELL','MODEL','{}','Cubic cells represent the most symmetric structure among all crystal lattice forms, characterized by equal cell parameters a=b=c','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["de853bfe49f3934f3f091e273d7f490dd0799663d94d77bcd0cf7c1bbdee2bd4306455461b629588031c9581ff98e284a6026eebc4f0f469865a92862692afbc"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('ca03777b-fa8a-4f3f-9a7e-e854925b6a94'::uuid,'TRICLINIC CELL','MODEL','{}','Triclinic cells are the least symmetric type of cell with different angles α, β, and γ between its axes and unequal cell parameters a, b, c','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["de853bfe49f3934f3f091e273d7f490dd0799663d94d77bcd0cf7c1bbdee2bd4306455461b629588031c9581ff98e284a6026eebc4f0f469865a92862692afbc"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('929cd676-09f0-4305-b0d4-6bb908118c0b'::uuid,'WIGNER-SEITZ CELL','SYSTEM','{}','The Wigner-Seitz cell is a primitive cell formed by connecting lattice points to their nearest neighbors through vectors; it encloses an area (or volume in 3D) that plays a crucial role in solid state electronic theory','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["de853bfe49f3934f3f091e273d7f490dd0799663d94d77bcd0cf7c1bbdee2bd4306455461b629588031c9581ff98e284a6026eebc4f0f469865a92862692afbc"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('9d00e9d3-9272-4cd0-ae97-d3b1bed44bd1'::uuid,'BRAVIAS LATICE TYPE PRIMITIVE (P)','MODEL','{}','The P type Bravais lattice is characterized by nodes only at the vertices, forming a primitive cell','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["de853bfe49f3934f3f091e273d7f490dd0799663d94d77bcd0cf7c1bbdee2bd4306455461b629588031c9581ff98e284a6026eebc4f0f469865a92862692afbc"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('f9d0dbd7-6b42-4e1b-8f36-25317e88c02e'::uuid,'BRAVIAS LATICE TYPE BASE-CENTRED (A, B, C)','MODEL','{}','Base-centred lattices like A, B, and C have additional nodes at the centers of opposite faces in their structure','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["de853bfe49f3934f3f091e273d7f490dd0799663d94d77bcd0cf7c1bbdee2bd4306455461b629588031c9581ff98e284a6026eebc4f0f469865a92862692afbc"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('5e1d885b-cf17-44f9-a085-640463fcc5c5'::uuid,'BRAVIAS LATICE TYPE BODY-CENTRED (I)','MODEL','{}','Body-centred (I) lattice has an additional node located centrally within the cell','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["de853bfe49f3934f3f091e273d7f490dd0799663d94d77bcd0cf7c1bbdee2bd4306455461b629588031c9581ff98e284a6026eebc4f0f469865a92862692afbc"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('c9f53d39-044f-4786-96cb-6fe740b629a0'::uuid,'BRAVIAS LATICE TYPE FACE-CENTRED (F)','MODEL','{}','Face-centred (F) cell includes nodes at the centers of each face, providing a fully detailed geometry representation','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["de853bfe49f3934f3f091e273d7f490dd0799663d94d77bcd0cf7c1bbdee2bd4306455461b629588031c9581ff98e284a6026eebc4f0f469865a92862692afbc"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('41e0e0d1-c5c7-493e-bcf3-6c2701ac7c17'::uuid,'SIMPLE METAL CRYSTALS','SYSTEM','{}','Simple metals crystallize into highly symmetric structures such as cubic cells, showcasing uniform atomic arrangements','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["de853bfe49f3934f3f091e273d7f490dd0799663d94d77bcd0cf7c1bbdee2bd4306455461b629588031c9581ff98e284a6026eebc4f0f469865a92862692afbc"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('ec4a3da1-0de8-4c4e-8237-f24f602aeb8a'::uuid,'METAL AND NON-METAL COMPOUNDS','SYSTEM','{}','Compounds containing both metal and non-metal elements like oxides or carbides typically exhibit less symmetry compared to simple solid metals','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["de853bfe49f3934f3f091e273d7f490dd0799663d94d77bcd0cf7c1bbdee2bd4306455461b629588031c9581ff98e284a6026eebc4f0f469865a92862692afbc"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('ea1eab96-9044-48f2-b4bb-971fdb46143c'::uuid,'CELL PARAMETER OR LATTICE PARAMETER','MODEL','{}','In a crystal lattice, distances between nearest atoms are chosen as cell parameters or lattice parameters; these parameters along with angles fully describe the unit cell shape','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["de853bfe49f3934f3f091e273d7f490dd0799663d94d77bcd0cf7c1bbdee2bd4306455461b629588031c9581ff98e284a6026eebc4f0f469865a92862692afbc"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('c286fc8f-67dc-4697-9b83-379ab2404b8f'::uuid,'COORDINATE AXES','SYSTEM','{}','Coordinate axes are used to define directions in the crystal lattice, with distances between nearest atoms known as cell parameters or lattice parameters','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["de853bfe49f3934f3f091e273d7f490dd0799663d94d77bcd0cf7c1bbdee2bd4306455461b629588031c9581ff98e284a6026eebc4f0f469865a92862692afbc"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('ce1bda57-12ef-4772-8a9c-c58607f9aa93'::uuid,'WIGNER-SEIZT CELL','SYSTEM','{}','The Wigner–Seitz cell plays an important role in the theory of electronic properties of solids and is defined by the unit cell enclosed by planes. The main property associated with it is long-range order or translational symmetry','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["091c2bdcc29b966207eedad51eb8990dd1419da9354df05045326857c5fbf87d3c068e7c25d9b5302985a77f5c66a9a1a57d7703770ab76d586d72af540195a3"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('d0754bc1-b644-45b8-af2f-9e483dfbe2d4'::uuid,'CRYSTAL','MATERIAL','{}','A solid material characterized by long-range order or translational symmetry and defined by its atomic arrangement. It can be understood through the concepts of unit cells and lattices','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["091c2bdcc29b966207eedad51eb8990dd1419da9354df05045326857c5fbf87d3c068e7c25d9b5302985a77f5c66a9a1a57d7703770ab76d586d72af540195a3"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('d78796aa-1500-482c-ab9c-a0ea938271aa'::uuid,'TRANSLATIONAL SYMMETRY','MECHANISM','{}','The physical property inherent to crystals, meaning that some property F of a crystal is identical at two points related by a translation vector. This symmetry influences properties such as the reinforcement or cancellation observed in X-ray diffraction','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["091c2bdcc29b966207eedad51eb8990dd1419da9354df05045326857c5fbf87d3c068e7c25d9b5302985a77f5c66a9a1a57d7703770ab76d586d72af540195a3"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('e0cdb49f-e63a-4ef2-b337-e7a4448aeb25'::uuid,'X-RAY DIFFRACTION','MODEL','{}','A method used for determining the structure of solids, including type and parameters of unit cells. It operates based on the Bragg–Wulff relation to measure atomic distances between crystal planes through the reflection of X-rays at certain angles','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["091c2bdcc29b966207eedad51eb8990dd1419da9354df05045326857c5fbf87d3c068e7c25d9b5302985a77f5c66a9a1a57d7703770ab76d586d72af540195a3"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('783d4607-d6a6-4227-bc53-66c24ef789b1'::uuid,'INTERPLANAR SPACING','MATERIAL','{}','The distance between adjacent parallel atomic planes in a crystal, crucial for determining crystalline structure using X-ray diffraction techniques and represented by ''d'' in Eq. (1.3)','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["091c2bdcc29b966207eedad51eb8990dd1419da9354df05045326857c5fbf87d3c068e7c25d9b5302985a77f5c66a9a1a57d7703770ab76d586d72af540195a3"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('5fd9d70a-5eeb-4b0c-ab39-461bf48603b0'::uuid,'BRAGG-WULLF RELATION','MODEL','{}','A mathematical relation that links the angle of incidence of X-rays with the interplanar spacing to determine the crystal''s structure, expressed as 2d sin θ = nλ','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["091c2bdcc29b966207eedad51eb8990dd1419da9354df05045326857c5fbf87d3c068e7c25d9b5302985a77f5c66a9a1a57d7703770ab76d586d72af540195a3"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('aa4705ab-f786-4fae-8632-18cb7572dcc8'::uuid,'ATOMIC PLANE','COMPONENT','{}','Atomic planes are fundamental components in defining the structure of crystals. Their spacing is crucial in determining interatomic distances and is used in Bragg''s law for X-ray diffraction experiments','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["091c2bdcc29b966207eedad51eb8990dd1419da9354df05045326857c5fbf87d3c068e7c25d9b5302985a77f5c66a9a1a57d7703770ab76d586d72af540195a3"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('af77b8b8-039a-4c1c-bad3-9c9c13f739fc'::uuid,'AU','MATERIAL','{}','Gold, with an atomic radius of 0.144 nm and a lattice parameter of 0.408 nm','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["53b04af596a3f009b0b172d98500b34c3db439936f372536e19461beaac3c19f398b3faf0edd2566c35cf6cf60e602f2e382880f31675f6dbd7eb9926bc2496f"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('ab2a7297-c25f-4030-890e-c9ed9a309ccd'::uuid,'INTERATOMIC DISTANCE','MATERIAL','{}','Interatomic distance refers to the space between adjacent atoms, a key parameter in understanding crystal structures and physical properties like the Bragg–Wulff relation. It ranges from 0.2 to 0.6 nm in solids','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["091c2bdcc29b966207eedad51eb8990dd1419da9354df05045326857c5fbf87d3c068e7c25d9b5302985a77f5c66a9a1a57d7703770ab76d586d72af540195a3"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('dfaa89c1-38c5-45eb-81ea-5c0fa8595b6b'::uuid,'REPRESENTATIVE ATOM','PART','{}','A specific atom or particle within a unit cell that is used as a reference point for understanding atomic arrangements and properties in crystalline materials','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["091c2bdcc29b966207eedad51eb8990dd1419da9354df05045326857c5fbf87d3c068e7c25d9b5302985a77f5c66a9a1a57d7703770ab76d586d72af540195a3"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('9724b23f-a1d9-4fb1-b55c-bc289632348d'::uuid,'AMORPHOUS BODY','SYSTEM','{}','Amorphous bodies are found in nature and lack long-range order, but have short-range order','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["53b04af596a3f009b0b172d98500b34c3db439936f372536e19461beaac3c19f398b3faf0edd2566c35cf6cf60e602f2e382880f31675f6dbd7eb9926bc2496f"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('43cddebb-d5d8-46c4-ac3e-d502f8ad3f96'::uuid,'QUARTZ','MODEL','{}','Quartz is a crystalline form of silicon dioxide (SiO₂) characterized by its specific and well-defined lattice parameters. This structured arrangement of atoms gives quartz unique physical properties, making it applicable in various contexts beyond its basic chemical composition.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["53b04af596a3f009b0b172d98500b34c3db439936f372536e19461beaac3c19f398b3faf0edd2566c35cf6cf60e602f2e382880f31675f6dbd7eb9926bc2496f", "53b04af596a3f009b0b172d98500b34c3db439936f372536e19461beaac3c19f398b3faf0edd2566c35cf6cf60e602f2e382880f31675f6dbd7eb9926bc2496f"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('76b54d96-425d-4c77-b3ed-61bc328a1f81'::uuid,'ORDINARY GLASS','MODEL','{}','Amorphous form of silicon dioxide SiO₂, lacks long-range order in atomic arrangement but has short-range order','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["53b04af596a3f009b0b172d98500b34c3db439936f372536e19461beaac3c19f398b3faf0edd2566c35cf6cf60e602f2e382880f31675f6dbd7eb9926bc2496f"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('4f79c02b-e7b1-432b-8c11-3be935cb02de'::uuid,'SILICON DIOXIDE (SIO2)','MATERIAL','{}','A compound that can exist in either crystalline or amorphous states depending on the structure and arrangement of atoms','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["53b04af596a3f009b0b172d98500b34c3db439936f372536e19461beaac3c19f398b3faf0edd2566c35cf6cf60e602f2e382880f31675f6dbd7eb9926bc2496f"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('e99720e0-7d02-4060-976f-44842399896d'::uuid,'CRYSTAL STRUCTURE','SYSTEM','{}','Characterized by both chemical composition and spatial atomic arrangement with periodicity, leading to diffraction peaks at specific angles','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["53b04af596a3f009b0b172d98500b34c3db439936f372536e19461beaac3c19f398b3faf0edd2566c35cf6cf60e602f2e382880f31675f6dbd7eb9926bc2496f"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('61f106ad-4f47-4a64-9c3b-0fe3f90ab52f'::uuid,'AMORPHOUS STATE','SYSTEM','{}','State where long-range order is absent but short-range order exists, with particle trajectories changing continuously when interacting with radiation','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["53b04af596a3f009b0b172d98500b34c3db439936f372536e19461beaac3c19f398b3faf0edd2566c35cf6cf60e602f2e382880f31675f6dbd7eb9926bc2496f"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('40731938-0ba6-45a2-8638-7e22ca676207'::uuid,'ORDERED SIO2 UNITS','COMPONENT','{}','Inglass, atoms of silicon dioxide (SiO₂) are arranged chaotically at the macroscopic level but can have local order up to a certain scale in amorphous states','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["53b04af596a3f009b0b172d98500b34c3db439936f372536e19461beaac3c19f398b3faf0edd2566c35cf6cf60e602f2e382880f31675f6dbd7eb9926bc2496f"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('ea254c7e-33a9-4f47-8538-9d95316628da'::uuid,'V','MATERIAL','{}','Vanadium, with an atomic radius of 0.131 nm and a lattice parameter of 0.303 nm','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["53b04af596a3f009b0b172d98500b34c3db439936f372536e19461beaac3c19f398b3faf0edd2566c35cf6cf60e602f2e382880f31675f6dbd7eb9926bc2496f"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('b4077134-be48-47d7-8981-8df8804d8264'::uuid,'CR','MATERIAL','{}','Chromium, with an atomic radius of 0.127 nm and a lattice parameter of 0.288 nm','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["53b04af596a3f009b0b172d98500b34c3db439936f372536e19461beaac3c19f398b3faf0edd2566c35cf6cf60e602f2e382880f31675f6dbd7eb9926bc2496f"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('4eb16827-b27c-4bff-ab8a-f1f1e1d0ab25'::uuid,'FE','MATERIAL','{}','Iron, with an atomic radius of 0.126 nm and a lattice parameter of 0.287 nm','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["53b04af596a3f009b0b172d98500b34c3db439936f372536e19461beaac3c19f398b3faf0edd2566c35cf6cf60e602f2e382880f31675f6dbd7eb9926bc2496f"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('fdde011c-853c-4b74-8eea-676f5e046da5'::uuid,'NI','MATERIAL','{}','Nickel, with an atomic radius of 0.124 nm and a lattice parameter of 0.352 nm','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["53b04af596a3f009b0b172d98500b34c3db439936f372536e19461beaac3c19f398b3faf0edd2566c35cf6cf60e602f2e382880f31675f6dbd7eb9926bc2496f"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('57e3c9cd-79ee-42b8-a9d8-8c0f34af7cc2'::uuid,'CU','MATERIAL','{}','Copper, with an atomic radius of 0.128 nm and a lattice parameter of 0.362 nm','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["53b04af596a3f009b0b172d98500b34c3db439936f372536e19461beaac3c19f398b3faf0edd2566c35cf6cf60e602f2e382880f31675f6dbd7eb9926bc2496f"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('d80d1727-c2e4-4779-8bd0-065eead5ba0e'::uuid,'MO','MATERIAL','{}','Molybdenum, with an atomic radius of 0.140 nm and a lattice parameter of 0.315 nm','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["53b04af596a3f009b0b172d98500b34c3db439936f372536e19461beaac3c19f398b3faf0edd2566c35cf6cf60e602f2e382880f31675f6dbd7eb9926bc2496f"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('b4201130-fb09-470c-9e63-b876633734b7'::uuid,'AG','MATERIAL','{}','Silver, with an atomic radius of 0.144 nm and a lattice parameter of 0.408 nm','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["53b04af596a3f009b0b172d98500b34c3db439936f372536e19461beaac3c19f398b3faf0edd2566c35cf6cf60e602f2e382880f31675f6dbd7eb9926bc2496f"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('0b4877cc-09aa-4e65-8c87-69ba4dfe03e1'::uuid,'W','MATERIAL','{}','Tungsten, with an atomic radius of 0.141 nm and a lattice parameter of 0.316 nm','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["53b04af596a3f009b0b172d98500b34c3db439936f372536e19461beaac3c19f398b3faf0edd2566c35cf6cf60e602f2e382880f31675f6dbd7eb9926bc2496f"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('3dfe8596-d80c-47d6-891f-755549597af0'::uuid,'ACTED PARTICLES','PART','{}','Acted particles are core entities in a crystalline structure, influenced by surrounding rings corresponding to average interatomic distances.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["00143051310245f816588fb716da03e26c16bc4e7bceee44f164ad9fcb43cb30be624db6179e62ee993abaffba0e87685e16d6a70ad71f73a8df1bbb25b96d33"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('c70a8822-15b9-4a5d-9f1d-dbe8749e0e2a'::uuid,'RINGS','SYSTEM','{}','A series of annular arrangements around acted particles which correspond to frequent average interatomic distances found within the substance.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["00143051310245f816588fb716da03e26c16bc4e7bceee44f164ad9fcb43cb30be624db6179e62ee993abaffba0e87685e16d6a70ad71f73a8df1bbb25b96d33", "00143051310245f816588fb716da03e26c16bc4e7bceee44f164ad9fcb43cb30be624db6179e62ee993abaffba0e87685e16d6a70ad71f73a8df1bbb25b96d33"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('5be904c0-5d8c-43ba-86e7-d0ca14b8f355'::uuid,'CRYSTAL GEOMETRY','MODEL','{}','The entity "Crystal Geometry" is characterized by the distinctive geometric formations that arise from diffraction patterns. These formations are a direct result of the periodicity and symmetry evident in the arrangement of atoms within crystal structures. Diffraction patterns, which occur when waves (such as X-rays or electrons) pass through a crystal, reveal the underlying atomic lattice''s orderly arrangement with remarkable precision. This systematic structuring leads to the predictable and often aesthetically pleasing shapes observed in crystalline materials, making them a subject of both scientific study and artistic admiration.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["00143051310245f816588fb716da03e26c16bc4e7bceee44f164ad9fcb43cb30be624db6179e62ee993abaffba0e87685e16d6a70ad71f73a8df1bbb25b96d33", "00143051310245f816588fb716da03e26c16bc4e7bceee44f164ad9fcb43cb30be624db6179e62ee993abaffba0e87685e16d6a70ad71f73a8df1bbb25b96d33"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('6b9245d0-3ea9-4699-b83e-394e3625e25e'::uuid,'UNIT CELLS','COMPONENT','{}','Smallest repeating units in crystals that can fill space without any gaps. Shapes are limited by rotational symmetries such as 2-, 3-, 4-, or 6-fold axes.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["00143051310245f816588fb716da03e26c16bc4e7bceee44f164ad9fcb43cb30be624db6179e62ee993abaffba0e87685e16d6a70ad71f73a8df1bbb25b96d33", "00143051310245f816588fb716da03e26c16bc4e7bceee44f164ad9fcb43cb30be624db6179e62ee993abaffba0e87685e16d6a70ad71f73a8df1bbb25b96d33"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('3f0d379d-3c14-46b5-aa1c-124299a85530'::uuid,'POLYHEDRA WITH AXES OF SYMMETRY','MODEL','{}','"POLYHEDRA WITH AXES OF SYMMETRY": Only specific polyhedral shapes possessing axes of symmetry corresponding to symmetry orders of 2, 3, 4, or 6 are capable of filling three-dimensional space without leaving any gaps in crystal structures. This unique property ensures that such polyhedra can be arranged in a precise and orderly manner to form the intricate lattice patterns observed in various crystalline materials. These symmetrical polyhedral shapes play crucial roles not only in crystallography but also in fields such as material science, where their properties and applications continue to be of significant interest.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["00143051310245f816588fb716da03e26c16bc4e7bceee44f164ad9fcb43cb30be624db6179e62ee993abaffba0e87685e16d6a70ad71f73a8df1bbb25b96d33", "00143051310245f816588fb716da03e26c16bc4e7bceee44f164ad9fcb43cb30be624db6179e62ee993abaffba0e87685e16d6a70ad71f73a8df1bbb25b96d33"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('ed9f5baa-bdfc-4774-992e-6efdeb34878d'::uuid,'ICOSAHEDRON','MATERIAL','{}','ICOSAHEDRON is a type of quasicrystal characterized by its icosahedral structural framework. It contains fivefold rotation axes and displays a non-periodic atomic arrangement, making it distinct from conventional crystals which have periodic structures. This unique atomic configuration contributes to the fascinating properties observed in ICOSAHEDRON, such as unusual physical and chemical behaviors that differ from those of typical quasicrystals.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["00143051310245f816588fb716da03e26c16bc4e7bceee44f164ad9fcb43cb30be624db6179e62ee993abaffba0e87685e16d6a70ad71f73a8df1bbb25b96d33", "00143051310245f816588fb716da03e26c16bc4e7bceee44f164ad9fcb43cb30be624db6179e62ee993abaffba0e87685e16d6a70ad71f73a8df1bbb25b96d33"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('02e277e0-3dea-4836-9dce-5608044244b2'::uuid,'DEFECTS IN CRYSTAL LATTICES','MODEL','{}','In reality, crystalline structures have irregularities or defects that deviate from the ideal infinite lattice model; these are fundamental for understanding physical and chemical processes like plastic deformation and diffusion.|','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["00143051310245f816588fb716da03e26c16bc4e7bceee44f164ad9fcb43cb30be624db6179e62ee993abaffba0e87685e16d6a70ad71f73a8df1bbb25b96d33"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('111ae15b-946d-4c9e-91ea-a1317c53b48c'::uuid,'DECAGONAL SYMMETRY','MODEL','{}','Decagonal symmetry is observed in certain quasicrystals with a 10-fold rotational axis.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["00143051310245f816588fb716da03e26c16bc4e7bceee44f164ad9fcb43cb30be624db6179e62ee993abaffba0e87685e16d6a70ad71f73a8df1bbb25b96d33"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('45e216ae-f3cc-44a1-b7e4-84f691a4e697'::uuid,'DODECAGONAL SYMMETRY','MODEL','{}','Dodecagonal symmetry is observed in certain quasicrystals with a 20-fold rotational axis.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["00143051310245f816588fb716da03e26c16bc4e7bceee44f164ad9fcb43cb30be624db6179e62ee993abaffba0e87685e16d6a70ad71f73a8df1bbb25b96d33"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('55cb8747-551b-472e-96f7-32cd59de7230'::uuid,'QUASICRYSTALS','SYSTEM','{}','Crystals with complex non-periodic structures, such as icosahedral, decagonal, or dodecagonal symmetries. Often formed by rapid crystallization of melts containing specific metal alloys.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["00143051310245f816588fb716da03e26c16bc4e7bceee44f164ad9fcb43cb30be624db6179e62ee993abaffba0e87685e16d6a70ad71f73a8df1bbb25b96d33"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('cf5d4a2b-f180-4886-a84b-63ef81094ce8'::uuid,'ALUMINIUM–MANGANESE ALLOYS','MATERIAL','{}','An example of an alloy that can form quasicrystals with icosahedral symmetry when rapidly crystallized from a melt.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["00143051310245f816588fb716da03e26c16bc4e7bceee44f164ad9fcb43cb30be624db6179e62ee993abaffba0e87685e16d6a70ad71f73a8df1bbb25b96d33"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('60f701aa-24b1-4401-857e-ea85e59032f8'::uuid,'AL–LI–CU SYSTEMS','SYSTEM','{}','A system where rapid crystallization can lead to the formation of decagonal or dodecagonal quasicrystals, depending on specific composition and conditions.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["00143051310245f816588fb716da03e26c16bc4e7bceee44f164ad9fcb43cb30be624db6179e62ee993abaffba0e87685e16d6a70ad71f73a8df1bbb25b96d33"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('99cc7e43-713d-4112-b103-6c184faf6870'::uuid,'AL–LI–CU–MG SYSTEMS','SYSTEM','{}','Another example of a multi-metal alloy mix capable of forming complex non-periodic structures like icosahedral or decagonal quasicrystals during rapid crystallization processes.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["00143051310245f816588fb716da03e26c16bc4e7bceee44f164ad9fcb43cb30be624db6179e62ee993abaffba0e87685e16d6a70ad71f73a8df1bbb25b96d33"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('0ad84869-825f-4700-93a7-062d0d00ba15'::uuid,'PLASTIC DEFORMATION','MODEL','{}','Physical process that occurs due to the presence of defects in crystal lattices, which can affect the mechanical properties of materials.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["00143051310245f816588fb716da03e26c16bc4e7bceee44f164ad9fcb43cb30be624db6179e62ee993abaffba0e87685e16d6a70ad71f73a8df1bbb25b96d33"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('b97a0e83-9ef5-44d5-8ac0-42e05870ae99'::uuid,'POINT DEFECTS','DEFECT','{}','Point defects are zero-dimensional defects in crystals where none of the dimensions exceed interatomic distances and include vacancies, interstitial atoms, impurity atoms in interstitial positions, and substitutional impurity atoms','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["04e37a7e999dd7ea10edd012b31ba278d3dde8496945384b5318b8f1d083d8cd81d9ee0db494cc9b78073b5f10e73fad99713a4eba14be927c0a56bbec698a00"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('955a2cb7-113e-4eda-b07a-433693787a68'::uuid,'ZERO-DIMENSIONAL (POINT DEFECTS)','DEFECT','{}','Zero-dimensional defects are point defects and have all three dimensions comparable to the interatomic distance','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["04e37a7e999dd7ea10edd012b31ba278d3dde8496945384b5318b8f1d083d8cd81d9ee0db494cc9b78073b5f10e73fad99713a4eba14be927c0a56bbec698a00"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('f71505fe-5baa-4202-9faf-4b991a7e4cd6'::uuid,'VOIDS','DEFECT','{}','Voids are a type of three-dimensional bulk defect in crystals that can form through thermal processes, specifically through the Schottky mechanism','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["04e37a7e999dd7ea10edd012b31ba278d3dde8496945384b5318b8f1d083d8cd81d9ee0db494cc9b78073b5f10e73fad99713a4eba14be927c0a56bbec698a00"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('3329a05e-6342-41c1-8be3-4c902215b230'::uuid,'INTERSTITIAL ATOMS','DEFECT','{}','Interstitial atoms represent a category of point defects within materials that occur by occupying void spaces or gaps between regular atomic lattice sites. These atoms are smaller than interatomic distances, allowing them to fit into the crystal lattice structure without entirely replacing an existing atom. Due to their position in the lattice, interstitial atoms lead to significant mechanical stress and structural distortion around them. The degree of this stress is inversely proportional to the cube of the distance from the defect, meaning that stresses are most pronounced very close to the interstitial atom before gradually decreasing with increasing distance.
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('78cdd2d8-be79-42e4-addf-3130a0a5ca67'::uuid,'SPATIAL DIMENSIONS','MECHANISM','{}','Spatial dimensions mechanism categorizes defects based on their sizes relative to atomic bonds, distinguishing between zero-dimensional point, one-dimensional linear, two-dimensional surface, and three-dimensional bulk defects','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["04e37a7e999dd7ea10edd012b31ba278d3dde8496945384b5318b8f1d083d8cd81d9ee0db494cc9b78073b5f10e73fad99713a4eba14be927c0a56bbec698a00"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('6fdcd081-1483-46c4-b077-10486b40045a'::uuid,'MACROPOROSITIES','DEFECT','{}','Macroporosities refer to significant three-dimensional defects within solid materials, characterized by dimensions that surpass interatomic scales. These defects can manifest as holes or voids and play a crucial role in influencing the mechanical properties of various materials. Macroporosities are notable for their impact on material integrity, potentially affecting structural stability, durability, and other physical characteristics due to their substantial size relative to atomic or molecular levels.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["04e37a7e999dd7ea10edd012b31ba278d3dde8496945384b5318b8f1d083d8cd81d9ee0db494cc9b78073b5f10e73fad99713a4eba14be927c0a56bbec698a00", "04e37a7e999dd7ea10edd012b31ba278d3dde8496945384b5318b8f1d083d8cd81d9ee0db494cc9b78073b5f10e73fad99713a4eba14be927c0a56bbec698a00"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('022dbe0f-0298-4801-949c-c58b2eae08b4'::uuid,'DISLOCATIONS AND DISCLINATIONS','DEFECT','{}','Linear defects, dislocations and disclinations, have one dimension much larger than interatomic distances but comparable in other two directions; they significantly affect crystal symmetry and are common in many solids','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["04e37a7e999dd7ea10edd012b31ba278d3dde8496945384b5318b8f1d083d8cd81d9ee0db494cc9b78073b5f10e73fad99713a4eba14be927c0a56bbec698a00"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('3e1018cc-d6c8-462e-b17a-fabb300330bc'::uuid,'FREE SURFACE OF CRYSTAL','DEFECT','{}','Two-dimensional surface defects occur where the periodic arrangement of atoms is interrupted by free surfaces, impacting mechanical properties such as tensile strength and ductility','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["04e37a7e999dd7ea10edd012b31ba278d3dde8496945384b5318b8f1d083d8cd81d9ee0db494cc9b78073b5f10e73fad99713a4eba14be927c0a56bbec698a00"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('beecd7e3-cba1-4084-ae7e-5bca46812c96'::uuid,'DEFECTS','DEFECT','{}','Defects alter the periodic arrangement of atoms in solids, affecting their properties and behavior','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["04e37a7e999dd7ea10edd012b31ba278d3dde8496945384b5318b8f1d083d8cd81d9ee0db494cc9b78073b5f10e73fad99713a4eba14be927c0a56bbec698a00"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('474cbf35-b060-4501-97a7-52a027ec58e1'::uuid,'VACANCIES','DEFECT','{}','Vacancies are point defects representing sites where an atom is missing from its usual position in a crystal lattice','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["04e37a7e999dd7ea10edd012b31ba278d3dde8496945384b5318b8f1d083d8cd81d9ee0db494cc9b78073b5f10e73fad99713a4eba14be927c0a56bbec698a00"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('a92a6b77-3322-4207-99c0-06e908d62648'::uuid,'FREESURFACE OF CRYSTAL','DEFECT','{}','Free surfaces are two-dimensional defects where the periodic arrangement of atoms is interrupted, impacting crystal properties like tensile strength and ductility','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["04e37a7e999dd7ea10edd012b31ba278d3dde8496945384b5318b8f1d083d8cd81d9ee0db494cc9b78073b5f10e73fad99713a4eba14be927c0a56bbec698a00"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('4c86113b-bc13-4f9f-acc5-5b168741b04a'::uuid,'SUPERFICIAL LAYER ATOMS','PART','{}','Superficial layer atoms can participate in thermal processes leading to the formation of vacancies on the surface due to temperature changes','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["04e37a7e999dd7ea10edd012b31ba278d3dde8496945384b5318b8f1d083d8cd81d9ee0db494cc9b78073b5f10e73fad99713a4eba14be927c0a56bbec698a00"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('bdf67b42-59d6-4867-ac87-37872199a6ff'::uuid,'DISLOCATIONS','MECHANISM','{}','Dislocations are one-dimensional linear defects that significantly affect lattice structure and mechanical properties through glide or climb mechanisms','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["04e37a7e999dd7ea10edd012b31ba278d3dde8496945384b5318b8f1d083d8cd81d9ee0db494cc9b78073b5f10e73fad99713a4eba14be927c0a56bbec698a00"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('7b259547-9850-4a49-a672-22f41c9cd29d'::uuid,'DISCLINATIONS','MECHANISM','{}','Disclinations, a type of one-dimensional defect, create distortion in the crystal structure primarily along two dimensions but significantly larger than interatomic distances','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["04e37a7e999dd7ea10edd012b31ba278d3dde8496945384b5318b8f1d083d8cd81d9ee0db494cc9b78073b5f10e73fad99713a4eba14be927c0a56bbec698a00"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('03b99aae-570d-41a9-bc7e-212c415fd125'::uuid,'ATOM','PART','{}','An atom from a deeper layer moves to the site of the departed atom creating a vacancy in the crystal structure.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["9651f9ef226458d8100848f8540f45409867d23ece33da35cb3c57333cbab04b77632d78621d7486868c651fa88359e8040c411ec03226f838f13f2a4cb3584f"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('9c29f6d4-8229-4fc9-bbc2-2da727a80bac'::uuid,'CRISTAL VACANCY','SYSTEM','{}','A void or missing atom within the crystal lattice caused by an atom moving, leading to the creation of vacancies that can move into the crystal interior.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["9651f9ef226458d8100848f8540f45409867d23ece33da35cb3c57333cbab04b77632d78621d7486868c651fa88359e8040c411ec03226f838f13f2a4cb3584f", "9651f9ef226458d8100848f8540f45409867d23ece33da35cb3c57333cbab04b77632d78621d7486868c651fa88359e8040c411ec03226f838f13f2a4cb3584f"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('360dbf0a-90ac-42fe-935a-8e148e1ef410'::uuid,'CRYSTAL INTERIOR','COMPONENT','{}','The internal parts of the crystal where atoms and vacancies can move.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["9651f9ef226458d8100848f8540f45409867d23ece33da35cb3c57333cbab04b77632d78621d7486868c651fa88359e8040c411ec03226f838f13f2a4cb3584f", "9651f9ef226458d8100848f8540f45409867d23ece33da35cb3c57333cbab04b77632d78621d7486868c651fa88359e8040c411ec03226f838f13f2a4cb3584f"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('e3075668-3376-47f3-bd87-be8dea73a6ff'::uuid,'HIGH-ENERGY CHARGED PARTICLES','MECHANISM','{}','Particles that, upon irradiation of the crystal, knock atoms out of lattice sites creating Frenkel pairs (an interstitial atom and a vacancy).','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["9651f9ef226458d8100848f8540f45409867d23ece33da35cb3c57333cbab04b77632d78621d7486868c651fa88359e8040c411ec03226f838f13f2a4cb3584f", "9651f9ef226458d8100848f8540f45409867d23ece33da35cb3c57333cbab04b77632d78621d7486868c651fa88359e8040c411ec03226f838f13f2a4cb3584f"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('dc8f9939-1971-41af-a597-5bb2dd458e6d'::uuid,'FRENKEL PAIR','SYSTEM','{}','A pair consisting of an interstitial atom and a vacancy created due to high-energy particle bombardment onto the crystal lattice.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["9651f9ef226458d8100848f8540f45409867d23ece33da35cb3c57333cbab04b77632d78621d7486868c651fa88359e8040c411ec03226f838f13f2a4cb3584f", "9651f9ef226458d8100848f8540f45409867d23ece33da35cb3c57333cbab04b77632d78621d7486868c651fa88359e8040c411ec03226f838f13f2a4cb3584f"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('cf42814e-1bc4-4b65-afa5-bf101a3db99e'::uuid,'IMPIURITY ATOMS','PART','{}','Atoms that could be introduced into the crystal structure via ion implantation or other technological processes, forming point defects.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["9651f9ef226458d8100848f8540f45409867d23ece33da35cb3c57333cbab04b77632d78621d7486868c651fa88359e8040c411ec03226f838f13f2a4cb3584f", "9651f9ef226458d8100848f8540f45409867d23ece33da35cb3c57333cbab04b77632d78621d7486868c651fa88359e8040c411ec03226f838f13f2a4cb3584f"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('c0a1ce53-bd21-4b50-b00f-505ceda6ea02'::uuid,'ION IMPLANTATION','MECHANISM','{}','A process by which impurity atoms can be implanted into a crystal lattice to form point defects.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["9651f9ef226458d8100848f8540f45409867d23ece33da35cb3c57333cbab04b77632d78621d7486868c651fa88359e8040c411ec03226f838f13f2a4cb3584f", "9651f9ef226458d8100848f8540f45409867d23ece33da35cb3c57333cbab04b77632d78621d7486868c651fa88359e8040c411ec03226f838f13f2a4cb3584f"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('5d7666fa-00d2-4ef0-83da-b28bec8f743d'::uuid,'HELMHOLTZ FREE ENERGY','MODEL','{}','The minimum free energy F of the crystal at equilibrium, given as \(F = U - TS\), where U is internal energy, T is temperature, and S is entropy.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["9651f9ef226458d8100848f8540f45409867d23ece33da35cb3c57333cbab04b77632d78621d7486868c651fa88359e8040c411ec03226f838f13f2a4cb3584f", "9651f9ef226458d8100848f8540f45409867d23ece33da35cb3c57333cbab04b77632d78621d7486868c651fa88359e8040c411ec03226f838f13f2a4cb3584f"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('0f2041f4-5d60-42bf-90f9-5e3036e0354a'::uuid,'VACANCY CONCENTRATION','SYSTEM','{}','The number of vacancies in a crystal under thermodynamic conditions, which balances between the increase in internal energy due to increased vacancy concentration and the increase in bound energy through entropy changes.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["9651f9ef226458d8100848f8540f45409867d23ece33da35cb3c57333cbab04b77632d78621d7486868c651fa88359e8040c411ec03226f838f13f2a4cb3584f", "9651f9ef226458d8100848f8540f45409867d23ece33da35cb3c57333cbab04b77632d78621d7486868c651fa88359e8040c411ec03226f838f13f2a4cb3584f"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('7dfe1d63-079f-43f2-9ba3-1a923314b54d'::uuid,'HEAT <3K','COMPONENT','{}','The temperature at which thermal fluctuations are low enough for certain mechanisms such as Frenkel defect formation to occur without significant energy fluctuations.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["9651f9ef226458d8100848f8540f45409867d23ece33da35cb3c57333cbab04b77632d78621d7486868c651fa88359e8040c411ec03226f838f13f2a4cb3584f", "9651f9ef226458d8100848f8540f45409867d23ece33da35cb3c57333cbab04b77632d78621d7486868c651fa88359e8040c411ec03226f838f13f2a4cb3584f"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('90da7743-8cf6-4b45-bac8-dcc44fa1d3a9'::uuid,'FORMATION ENERGY OF VACANCIES','SYSTEM','{}','Energy required to create a vacancy in the crystal lattice, approximately 1 eV.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["9651f9ef226458d8100848f8540f45409867d23ece33da35cb3c57333cbab04b77632d78621d7486868c651fa88359e8040c411ec03226f838f13f2a4cb3584f"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('18a377f4-f7a1-458c-8ba4-774269090be0'::uuid,'FORMATION ENERGY OF INTERSTITIAL ATOMS','SYSTEM','{}','Energy required to create an interstitial atom in the crystal lattice, typically between 3 and 4 eV.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["9651f9ef226458d8100848f8540f45409867d23ece33da35cb3c57333cbab04b77632d78621d7486868c651fa88359e8040c411ec03226f838f13f2a4cb3584f"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('061a2d64-c975-4476-ae95-56a55ce3adec'::uuid,'ENTROPY','SYSTEM','{}','Entropy is a measure of the number of accessible microstates, given by S = k ln W, where W represents the number of microstates. Entropy consists of two parts: vibrational and configurational.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["9b40aeeee926e9f06b82ce0583b77840ada76a848e877abeda1fe25c37d3511249a17db306eabf3940c7987d16afdb9a598d693aa693ba661c12d71e90e7f8c7", "9b40aeeee926e9f06b82ce0583b77840ada76a848e877abeda1fe25c37d3511249a17db306eabf3940c7987d16afdb9a598d693aa693ba661c12d71e90e7f8c7"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('a9b344f2-bd98-42f1-8701-5630136be93c'::uuid,'CONFIGURATIONAL ENTROPY','PART','{}','Configurational entropy increases with the addition of vacancies, as each vacancy can be located in any position among N sites','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["9b40aeeee926e9f06b82ce0583b77840ada76a848e877abeda1fe25c37d3511249a17db306eabf3940c7987d16afdb9a598d693aa693ba661c12d71e90e7f8c7", "9b40aeeee926e9f06b82ce0583b77840ada76a848e877abeda1fe25c37d3511249a17db306eabf3940c7987d16afdb9a598d693aa693ba661c12d71e90e7f8c7"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('3fe9c99a-edde-4b19-9c48-77066e819ed9'::uuid,'VIBRATIONAL ENTROPY','PART','{}','Vibrational entropy refers to the change in frequency of atomic vibration near point defects, leading to an increase in probable microstates and thus increasing vibrational entropy','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["9b40aeeee926e9f06b82ce0583b77840ada76a848e877abeda1fe25c37d3511249a17db306eabf3940c7987d16afdb9a598d693aa693ba661c12d71e90e7f8c7", "9b40aeeee926e9f06b82ce0583b77840ada76a848e877abeda1fe25c37d3511249a17db306eabf3940c7987d16afdb9a598d693aa693ba661c12d71e90e7f8c7"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('d1b02a92-de36-4a27-92b4-166a048233fb'::uuid,'ENTROPY FUNCTION','MODEL','{}','The total entropy is described by S = k ln W + n S₀, where k is the Boltzmann constant, W is the number of microstates, *n* is the number of vacancies, and S₀ is the vibrational entropy per vacancy','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["9b40aeeee926e9f06b82ce0583b77840ada76a848e877abeda1fe25c37d3511249a17db306eabf3940c7987d16afdb9a598d693aa693ba661c12d71e90e7f8c7", "9b40aeeee926e9f06b82ce0583b77840ada76a848e877abeda1fe25c37d3511249a17db306eabf3940c7987d16afdb9a598d693aa693ba661c12d71e90e7f8c7"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('340de8f6-f2bf-40a3-82eb-178f4e21ba1c'::uuid,'STIRLING''S APPROXIMATION','MODEL','{}','Stirling''s approximation, ln x! ≈ x ln x − x, is used to simplify the calculation of entropy change in a crystal lattice with vacancies','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["9b40aeeee926e9f06b82ce0583b77840ada76a848e877abeda1fe25c37d3511249a17db306eabf3940c7987d16afdb9a598d693aa693ba661c12d71e90e7f8c7", "9b40aeeee926e9f06b82ce0583b77840ada76a848e877abeda1fe25c37d3511249a17db306eabf3940c7987d16afdb9a598d693aa693ba661c12d71e90e7f8c7"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('682efe53-c8b5-43a3-83f7-7d9cce8be44c'::uuid,'FREE ENERGY','SYSTEM','{}','Free energy change (ΔF), a key parameter in thermodynamics, is fundamentally linked to changes in entropy and internal energy within a system. Mathematically, it can be expressed as ΔF = ΔU - T ΔS, where ΔU represents the change in internal energy and T ΔS accounts for the product of temperature (T) and change in entropy (ΔS). This expression is particularly relevant when considering systems with complex microstructures, such as those containing vacancies or exhibiting significant vibrational activity. In these contexts, additional terms related to vacancy energy and vibrational entropy are incorporated into the free energy equation, reflecting their contributions to the overall thermodynamic state of the system.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["9b40aeeee926e9f06b82ce0583b77840ada76a848e877abeda1fe25c37d3511249a17db306eabf3940c7987d16afdb9a598d693aa693ba661c12d71e90e7f8c7", "9b40aeeee926e9f06b82ce0583b77840ada76a848e877abeda1fe25c37d3511249a17db306eabf3940c7987d16afdb9a598d693aa693ba661c12d71e90e7f8c7"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('1fca38ec-4479-4a40-b49f-02662dd4ddce'::uuid,'N','PART','{}','The entity "N" refers to the total number of sites or atoms within a given system, such as in materials science or quantum physics contexts. The description also mentions its counterpart "n," which is used to represent vacancies within that system. Specifically, "n" denotes the number of vacancies (unoccupied sites), while "n(N−n)" calculates the exact number of unoccupied sites by multiplying the total number of sites represented by "N" with the difference between "N" and "n." This relationship highlights the interdependence between the total number of atoms/sites and the vacant ones, providing a comprehensive framework for understanding site occupancy in various scientific studies.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["feb8132e243d0aba3105b9fda04babb7ff24966287dbd84d7443bd6ee305915675585dead0112565c0b93f8c31cd5761338aff2e29ded78c1bc21cc2f9750580", "feb8132e243d0aba3105b9fda04babb7ff24966287dbd84d7443bd6ee305915675585dead0112565c0b93f8c31cd5761338aff2e29ded78c1bc21cc2f9750580"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('f2aede00-1001-4c3e-a06e-b1449c7deec5'::uuid,'S₀','MATERIAL','{}','A constant representing vibrational entropy that is negligible under most circumstances due to its small value compared to other terms in the equations','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["feb8132e243d0aba3105b9fda04babb7ff24966287dbd84d7443bd6ee305915675585dead0112565c0b93f8c31cd5761338aff2e29ded78c1bc21cc2f9750580"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('f32697e5-438e-4422-be01-e417d0231185'::uuid,'E₀','MECHANISM','{}','The activation energy for vacancy formation, a key parameter in calculating equilibrium concentrations of vacancies','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["feb8132e243d0aba3105b9fda04babb7ff24966287dbd84d7443bd6ee305915675585dead0112565c0b93f8c31cd5761338aff2e29ded78c1bc21cc2f9750580"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('39c4449a-0316-425f-80b5-e178d858643c'::uuid,'K','MODEL','{}','Boltzmann''s constant which relates temperature and energy at the atomic scale in statistical mechanics equations','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["feb8132e243d0aba3105b9fda04babb7ff24966287dbd84d7443bd6ee305915675585dead0112565c0b93f8c31cd5761338aff2e29ded78c1bc21cc2f9750580"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('994a9cb5-0cbf-4350-a939-087a9777904e'::uuid,'"C_V"','SYSTEM','{}','Equilibrium vacancy concentration (n/N) as a system in thermal equilibrium with the crystal''s crystal lattice','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["feb8132e243d0aba3105b9fda04babb7ff24966287dbd84d7443bd6ee305915675585dead0112565c0b93f8c31cd5761338aff2e29ded78c1bc21cc2f9750580"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('b2627475-15ad-41fb-ad26-65f2bb5d7b21'::uuid,'"DIVACANCIES/TRIVACANCIES','SYSTEM','{}','Complex structures formed by vacancies as a result of their random movement and combination in crystals)','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["feb8132e243d0aba3105b9fda04babb7ff24966287dbd84d7443bd6ee305915675585dead0112565c0b93f8c31cd5761338aff2e29ded78c1bc21cc2f9750580"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('64e62ab2-9d7c-4f8a-80cc-32764ce1f596'::uuid,'"VIBRATIONAL ENTROPY"','MATERIAL','{}','The vibrational entropy term (S₀/k) that is considered negligible in many cases but still important for general understanding','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["feb8132e243d0aba3105b9fda04babb7ff24966287dbd84d7443bd6ee305915675585dead0112565c0b93f8c31cd5761338aff2e29ded78c1bc21cc2f9750580"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('f0ef5118-569c-44db-9d5c-596f36a863a7'::uuid,'"CU"','MATERIAL','{}','"Cu" represents copper, a specific material discussed for vacancy formation energies and equilibrium concentrations','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["feb8132e243d0aba3105b9fda04babb7ff24966287dbd84d7443bd6ee305915675585dead0112565c0b93f8c31cd5761338aff2e29ded78c1bc21cc2f9750580"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('78c3f401-cdc3-4024-82f5-3118f36d102a'::uuid,'1.1 EV','MATERIAL','{}','The activation energy for vacancy formation in copper, a specific value used as an example','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["feb8132e243d0aba3105b9fda04babb7ff24966287dbd84d7443bd6ee305915675585dead0112565c0b93f8c31cd5761338aff2e29ded78c1bc21cc2f9750580"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('89c31b79-9835-40be-8261-c03c8c321c8e'::uuid,'"DIVACANCIE/TRIVACANCIES"','SYSTEM','{}','(Complex structures formed by vacancies are also systems in the crystal lattice that affect overall stability and behavior','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["feb8132e243d0aba3105b9fda04babb7ff24966287dbd84d7443bd6ee305915675585dead0112565c0b93f8c31cd5761338aff2e29ded78c1bc21cc2f9750580"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('bf927b85-7b18-40b1-9432-ed1bc10f3469'::uuid,'"FREE SURFACE"','COMPONENT','{}','Free surfaces are components of the crystal where vacancies can interact and potentially disappear','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["feb8132e243d0aba3105b9fda04babb7ff24966287dbd84d7443bd6ee305915675585dead0112565c0b93f8c31cd5761338aff2e29ded78c1bc21cc2f9750580"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('a4a5842e-c029-4863-90d4-84043650d6b3'::uuid,'"GRAIN BOUNDARIES"','COMPONENT','{}','(Grain boundaries are components where vacancies can interact and potentially disappear, influencing local vacancy concentration','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["feb8132e243d0aba3105b9fda04babb7ff24966287dbd84d7443bd6ee305915675585dead0112565c0b93f8c31cd5761338aff2e29ded78c1bc21cc2f9750580"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('29b9c54d-3d47-47bf-9514-dc03f9be5404'::uuid,'"INTERPHASE BOUNDARIES"','COMPONENT','{}','(Interphase boundaries are components where vacancies can interact and potentially disappear, influencing local vacancy concentration','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["feb8132e243d0aba3105b9fda04babb7ff24966287dbd84d7443bd6ee305915675585dead0112565c0b93f8c31cd5761338aff2e29ded78c1bc21cc2f9750580"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('ba9c3ec5-cfd6-4beb-9068-d7bb47ea6666'::uuid,'FREE SURFACE','COMPONENT','{}','Free surface acts as a sink for vacancies, capturing them and leading to their decrease','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["3eac214f7fab6c0b35e16309a9844dde6f2c66036fa9039ffca4d76bd4ffe9a1fb7edd786c2fd1c7bd56b5907044f909a896b1fd021161eb1fe0c6c57452b413"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('a1ddd3d8-2ae2-4cbd-a4cd-d89d8da24612'::uuid,'GRAIN BOUNDARIES','COMPONENT','{}','Grain boundaries serve as sinks for vacancies through migration processes','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["3eac214f7fab6c0b35e16309a9844dde6f2c66036fa9039ffca4d76bd4ffe9a1fb7edd786c2fd1c7bd56b5907044f909a896b1fd021161eb1fe0c6c57452b413"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('db7d50b2-1e94-4ebd-8725-08413e63790c'::uuid,'INTERPHASE BOUNDARIES','COMPONENT','{}','Interphase boundaries function as sinks where vacancies can get captured, helping reduce their concentration in the solid after thermal treatment','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["3eac214f7fab6c0b35e16309a9844dde6f2c66036fa9039ffca4d76bd4ffe9a1fb7edd786c2fd1c7bd56b5907044f909a896b1fd021161eb1fe0c6c57452b413", "3eac214f7fab6c0b35e16309a9844dde6f2c66036fa9039ffca4d76bd4ffe9a1fb7edd786c2fd1c7bd56b5907044f909a896b1fd021161eb1fe0c6c57452b413"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('0a3e2bed-ae21-4dde-8318-366f4e09777d'::uuid,'DISLOCATION','DEVICE','{}','A dislocation is a linear defect introduced into a crystal lattice through an extra atomic plane. It acts effectively to decrease point defects like vacancies by moving and annihilating them','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["3eac214f7fab6c0b35e16309a9844dde6f2c66036fa9039ffca4d76bd4ffe9a1fb7edd786c2fd1c7bd56b5907044f909a896b1fd021161eb1fe0c6c57452b413"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('94b612e1-482e-4d85-8a2a-266fb01883b0'::uuid,'FIGURE 1.6','SYSTEM','{}','Schematic showing the insertion of an additional, incomplete atomic plane (extra-plane) in a crystal, causing lattice distortion near its edge','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["3eac214f7fab6c0b35e16309a9844dde6f2c66036fa9039ffca4d76bd4ffe9a1fb7edd786c2fd1c7bd56b5907044f909a896b1fd021161eb1fe0c6c57452b413"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('108a020a-b029-4710-a85b-b84850f60fd5'::uuid,'EXTRA-PLANE','COMPONENT','{}','An extra-plane is an added atomic plane in crystal structures that introduces dislocations by distorting the lattice structure near its edge','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["3eac214f7fab6c0b35e16309a9844dde6f2c66036fa9039ffca4d76bd4ffe9a1fb7edd786c2fd1c7bd56b5907044f909a896b1fd021161eb1fe0c6c57452b413"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('2cf1c891-8ae0-40f4-997e-fa1d9c3348f4'::uuid,'DISLOCATION DENSITY','MODEL','{}','Dislocation density quantifies the number of dislocation emergences per unit area, used to describe and control defects in crystals','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["3eac214f7fab6c0b35e16309a9844dde6f2c66036fa9039ffca4d76bd4ffe9a1fb7edd786c2fd1c7bd56b5907044f909a896b1fd021161eb1fe0c6c57452b413"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('188953ad-8906-4897-945b-176be5f0c12b'::uuid,'GIBBS FREE ENERGY G','MODEL','{}','G is defined as the minimum energy state for a system at constant temperature and pressure, representing the total energy available to perform work in a thermodynamic process. For solid and liquid phases, it includes potential from intermolecular attractions (U), volume expansion against external pressure (pV), and entropy (−TS)','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["3eac214f7fab6c0b35e16309a9844dde6f2c66036fa9039ffca4d76bd4ffe9a1fb7edd786c2fd1c7bd56b5907044f909a896b1fd021161eb1fe0c6c57452b413"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('22b0f378-0ca6-46d3-b1d4-6503f9416c1e'::uuid,'LIQUID PHASE G_L','SYSTEM','{}','Gibbs free energy of the liquid phase, which becomes stable below a certain temperature T_m in relation to solid phases','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["3eac214f7fab6c0b35e16309a9844dde6f2c66036fa9039ffca4d76bd4ffe9a1fb7edd786c2fd1c7bd56b5907044f909a896b1fd021161eb1fe0c6c57452b413"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('5815048c-7105-4061-a324-df64b6dc4b4a'::uuid,'SOLID PHASE G_S','SYSTEM','{}','Gibbs free energy of the solid phase, which becomes stable above a critical temperature T_m relative to the liquid phase','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["3eac214f7fab6c0b35e16309a9844dde6f2c66036fa9039ffca4d76bd4ffe9a1fb7edd786c2fd1c7bd56b5907044f909a896b1fd021161eb1fe0c6c57452b413"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('a8199bd7-fc76-4605-b2df-1842a49341b0'::uuid,'CRITICAL TEMPERATURE T_M','MODEL','{}','The temperature at which a phase transition occurs between the liquid and solid phases; it signifies the point where Gibbs energies of both phases are equal, leading to equilibrium or instability in one state over another)("relationship"','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["3eac214f7fab6c0b35e16309a9844dde6f2c66036fa9039ffca4d76bd4ffe9a1fb7edd786c2fd1c7bd56b5907044f909a896b1fd021161eb1fe0c6c57452b413"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('3cd68dfc-51f3-43b1-8b30-168fe6180430'::uuid,'DISLOCATION MECHANISM','MECHANISM','{}','The mechanism of dislocation involves the movement and interaction of dislocations within a crystal lattice to affect point defects like vacancies. This process is crucial for understanding plastic deformation in metals','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["3eac214f7fab6c0b35e16309a9844dde6f2c66036fa9039ffca4d76bd4ffe9a1fb7edd786c2fd1c7bd56b5907044f909a896b1fd021161eb1fe0c6c57452b413"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('caabc42c-fc21-497c-b027-00038bd667e2'::uuid,'FIGURE 1.7','SYSTEM','{}','A schematic diagram depicting the Gibbs free energy dependencies for liquid (G_L) and solid phases (G_S), showing phase stability transitions at critical temperature T_m','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["3eac214f7fab6c0b35e16309a9844dde6f2c66036fa9039ffca4d76bd4ffe9a1fb7edd786c2fd1c7bd56b5907044f909a896b1fd021161eb1fe0c6c57452b413"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('cc73b52c-c331-4b51-b468-85f4d591ad5e'::uuid,'CRYSTALLISATION','MODEL','{}','The process of crystallisation, which happens below the critical temperature T_m, is characterized by a decrease in Gibbs free energy G_S making it more stable compared to the liquid state G_L','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["3eac214f7fab6c0b35e16309a9844dde6f2c66036fa9039ffca4d76bd4ffe9a1fb7edd786c2fd1c7bd56b5907044f909a896b1fd021161eb1fe0c6c57452b413"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('74a41515-ff0e-4e54-82b8-f1730b119c54'::uuid,'MELTING','MODEL','{}','The reverse process to crystallisation, melting occurs above the critical temperature T_m when solid phase''s Gibbs free energy G_S exceeds that of the liquid phase G_L, leading to a less stable condition for the solid state)("relationship"','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["3eac214f7fab6c0b35e16309a9844dde6f2c66036fa9039ffca4d76bd4ffe9a1fb7edd786c2fd1c7bd56b5907044f909a896b1fd021161eb1fe0c6c57452b413"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('7f305670-ec3e-4679-aba2-5169bc098a1d'::uuid,'T_M','MODEL','{}','Melting temperature model where G_S < G_L for solid phase stability','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["d6d7f1e636dd37d1d486e1147e50bb55a86e562c7aa76fe7db2fd92b8edc1a5763f08ccea27e0cdfab16c1e418d6907a556395f5d666eb5ad38e350bb4fe96fa"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('d7270e38-dbbe-4898-a111-deb6ff3ce4f8'::uuid,'G_S','MATERIAL','{}','Solid phase free energy, which is compared to liquid phase free energy at T_m for phase stability','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["d6d7f1e636dd37d1d486e1147e50bb55a86e562c7aa76fe7db2fd92b8edc1a5763f08ccea27e0cdfab16c1e418d6907a556395f5d666eb5ad38e350bb4fe96fa", "d6d7f1e636dd37d1d486e1147e50bb55a86e562c7aa76fe7db2fd92b8edc1a5763f08ccea27e0cdfab16c1e418d6907a556395f5d666eb5ad38e350bb4fe96fa"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('6f0e303f-3442-4dec-88bb-a441390bbad7'::uuid,'G_L','MATERIAL','{}','Liquid phase free energy in relation to solid phase free energy G_S at temperature T_m','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["d6d7f1e636dd37d1d486e1147e50bb55a86e562c7aa76fe7db2fd92b8edc1a5763f08ccea27e0cdfab16c1e418d6907a556395f5d666eb5ad38e350bb4fe96fa", "d6d7f1e636dd37d1d486e1147e50bb55a86e562c7aa76fe7db2fd92b8edc1a5763f08ccea27e0cdfab16c1e418d6907a556395f5d666eb5ad38e350bb4fe96fa"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('36115732-1a8d-460b-9575-78c48e16cab2'::uuid,'PHASE TRANSITION','MECHANISM','{}','Phase transition from liquid to solid state occurs at temperature T_m, including crystallisation and melting processes','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["d6d7f1e636dd37d1d486e1147e50bb55a86e562c7aa76fe7db2fd92b8edc1a5763f08ccea27e0cdfab16c1e418d6907a556395f5d666eb5ad38e350bb4fe96fa", "d6d7f1e636dd37d1d486e1147e50bb55a86e562c7aa76fe7db2fd92b8edc1a5763f08ccea27e0cdfab16c1e418d6907a556395f5d666eb5ad38e350bb4fe96fa"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('5c2c0117-ec95-4bf5-9f48-a3e0d8c7164e'::uuid,'LIQUID STATE','STATE','{}','The Liquid State is a phase characterized by the dynamic behavior of its constituent atoms or molecules. In this state, particles exhibit chaotic movements and undergo random positional changes due to relatively low intermolecular forces compared to those in solid states. A key feature of the liquid state is its ability to transition to the solid state through a process known as crystallization, where ordered structures form due to stronger attractive forces overcoming the disordered movement of particles. This transformation signifies a reduction in thermal energy, leading to decreased molecular motion and closer packing of constituent units.','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["d6d7f1e636dd37d1d486e1147e50bb55a86e562c7aa76fe7db2fd92b8edc1a5763f08ccea27e0cdfab16c1e418d6907a556395f5d666eb5ad38e350bb4fe96fa", "d6d7f1e636dd37d1d486e1147e50bb55a86e562c7aa76fe7db2fd92b8edc1a5763f08ccea27e0cdfab16c1e418d6907a556395f5d666eb5ad38e350bb4fe96fa"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('05010720-1743-4886-8a79-505e36567da1'::uuid,'ATOMS','PART','{}','Building blocks in liquids arranged chaotically, become orderly during crystallisation process','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["d6d7f1e636dd37d1d486e1147e50bb55a86e562c7aa76fe7db2fd92b8edc1a5763f08ccea27e0cdfab16c1e418d6907a556395f5d666eb5ad38e350bb4fe96fa", "d6d7f1e636dd37d1d486e1147e50bb55a86e562c7aa76fe7db2fd92b8edc1a5763f08ccea27e0cdfab16c1e418d6907a556395f5d666eb5ad38e350bb4fe96fa"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('c3e62d81-498b-49d9-b955-36f3231268e0'::uuid,'NUCLEUS OF CRYSTALLISATION','COMPONENT','{}','Local region of liquid where arrangement of atoms correspond to solid phase configuration, potentially initiating crystallisation process','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["d6d7f1e636dd37d1d486e1147e50bb55a86e562c7aa76fe7db2fd92b8edc1a5763f08ccea27e0cdfab16c1e418d6907a556395f5d666eb5ad38e350bb4fe96fa"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('62b36d6d-48dd-473e-8539-8808d7955d62'::uuid,'NUCLEUS GROWTH','PROCESS','{}','Growth of the nucleus by attachment of atoms from the liquid which decreases system''s energy and leads to transformation into a solid state, or spontaneous dissolution if energetically unfavourable','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["d6d7f1e636dd37d1d486e1147e50bb55a86e562c7aa76fe7db2fd92b8edc1a5763f08ccea27e0cdfab16c1e418d6907a556395f5d666eb5ad38e350bb4fe96fa"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('78866ae2-efc3-49d9-ac11-9ce644729fb6'::uuid,'HETEROGENEOUS CRYSTALLISATION','MODEL','{}','Crystallisation process where impurities act as ready-made nuclei, leading to faster nucleation than homogeneous process, requiring lower purity melt','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["d6d7f1e636dd37d1d486e1147e50bb55a86e562c7aa76fe7db2fd92b8edc1a5763f08ccea27e0cdfab16c1e418d6907a556395f5d666eb5ad38e350bb4fe96fa"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('89420f9a-663c-4e26-90d9-b991de61cb0b'::uuid,'HOMOGENEOUS CRYSTALLISATION','PROCESS','{}','Crystallisation starting from random formation of a nucleus in the melt volume with high purity requirements and no pre-existing nuclei present','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["d6d7f1e636dd37d1d486e1147e50bb55a86e562c7aa76fe7db2fd92b8edc1a5763f08ccea27e0cdfab16c1e418d6907a556395f5d666eb5ad38e350bb4fe96fa"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('d5464e07-fac1-4900-a66c-54afb4a12725'::uuid,'SPHERICAL NUCLEUS','COMPONENT','{}','Component formed in the melt, radius *r* which can grow through attachment of atoms leading to free energy changes ΔF_V and surface free energy γ effects during growth','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["d6d7f1e636dd37d1d486e1147e50bb55a86e562c7aa76fe7db2fd92b8edc1a5763f08ccea27e0cdfab16c1e418d6907a556395f5d666eb5ad38e350bb4fe96fa"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('3eeb9e07-d9a8-4e6a-949e-6d35198d73ff'::uuid,'ΔF_V','MATERIAL','{}','Change in free energy per unit volume of the growing spherical nucleus due to its volume increase, computed using equation (1.5)','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["d6d7f1e636dd37d1d486e1147e50bb55a86e562c7aa76fe7db2fd92b8edc1a5763f08ccea27e0cdfab16c1e418d6907a556395f5d666eb5ad38e350bb4fe96fa"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('4962ffb7-3a15-4592-ac62-46d5ac7f8ad7'::uuid,'Γ','MATERIAL','{}','Specific surface free energy of the interface between solid and liquid phases which contributes to free energy change ΔF during nucleation growth','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["d6d7f1e636dd37d1d486e1147e50bb55a86e562c7aa76fe7db2fd92b8edc1a5763f08ccea27e0cdfab16c1e418d6907a556395f5d666eb5ad38e350bb4fe96fa"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('3cd7d211-3ace-4533-bfc8-7e287a8d67ee'::uuid,'HOMOGENEOUS CRYSTALLISATION AT FIXED TEMPERATURE T','MODEL','{}','Theoretical scenario for homogeneous nucleation process occurring at a specific temperature','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["d6d7f1e636dd37d1d486e1147e50bb55a86e562c7aa76fe7db2fd92b8edc1a5763f08ccea27e0cdfab16c1e418d6907a556395f5d666eb5ad38e350bb4fe96fa"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1');
INSERT INTO agi_evolution.knowledge_nodes (id,"name",node_type,properties,description,embedding,parameters,metadata,created_at,updated_at,theme_id) VALUES
	 ('7fbf9db6-cf17-472a-bd9b-bf06f4cb34d3'::uuid,'FREE ENERGY, ΔF','MATERIAL','{}','Total free energy change in the system due to nucleus growth and surface area changes during crystallization, composed of volume and surface contributions','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["d6d7f1e636dd37d1d486e1147e50bb55a86e562c7aa76fe7db2fd92b8edc1a5763f08ccea27e0cdfab16c1e418d6907a556395f5d666eb5ad38e350bb4fe96fa"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('f686d6f7-5cf4-45bc-92cc-0133c12b6ed5'::uuid,'ΔU_V','MATERIAL','{}','Change in internal energy per unit volume of the growing nucleus which affects total free energy ΔF','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["d6d7f1e636dd37d1d486e1147e50bb55a86e562c7aa76fe7db2fd92b8edc1a5763f08ccea27e0cdfab16c1e418d6907a556395f5d666eb5ad38e350bb4fe96fa"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('fa12956b-dcff-4b42-ad57-58404a062274'::uuid,'ΔS_V','MATERIAL','{}','Change in entropy per unit volume of the growing nucleus which also influences system''s overall free energy change during nucleation growth','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["d6d7f1e636dd37d1d486e1147e50bb55a86e562c7aa76fe7db2fd92b8edc1a5763f08ccea27e0cdfab16c1e418d6907a556395f5d666eb5ad38e350bb4fe96fa"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('18125798-1d6f-4ba1-bc8b-72d5ec2d7971'::uuid,'HOMO-HETEROGENEOUS TRANSITION TEMPERATURE','MODEL','{}','Theoretical point or range within T_m where homogeneous crystallization turns into a heterogeneous process when impurities act as existing nuclei)("relationship"','{}','{}','{"frequency": 1, "text_unit_ids": ["d6d7f1e636dd37d1d486e1147e50bb55a86e562c7aa76fe7db2fd92b8edc1a5763f08ccea27e0cdfab16c1e418d6907a556395f5d666eb5ad38e350bb4fe96fa"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('49c497de-a910-40b5-977d-1b7717a1a562'::uuid,'-Λ','MATERIAL','{}','Latent heat of the phase transition, indicating heat release during crystallization','{}','{}','{"frequency": 3, "text_unit_ids": ["d2032ae9dddd98b060a009a328f21502528c28113460e17f3cb1218b3536aefa712a61e6b8149a0979cd51a8b20c63a51e821e71df8f19c34d6f0a736a46dac6", "d2032ae9dddd98b060a009a328f21502528c28113460e17f3cb1218b3536aefa712a61e6b8149a0979cd51a8b20c63a51e821e71df8f19c34d6f0a736a46dac6", "d2032ae9dddd98b060a009a328f21502528c28113460e17f3cb1218b3536aefa712a61e6b8149a0979cd51a8b20c63a51e821e71df8f19c34d6f0a736a46dac6"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('351f7a3a-a5ff-4f66-aa29-61ad5cfbd69e'::uuid,'ΔF_V = −Λ - T_M ΔS_V','MODEL','{}','Equation for the change in free energy at arbitrary temperatures','{}','{}','{"frequency": 3, "text_unit_ids": ["d2032ae9dddd98b060a009a328f21502528c28113460e17f3cb1218b3536aefa712a61e6b8149a0979cd51a8b20c63a51e821e71df8f19c34d6f0a736a46dac6", "d2032ae9dddd98b060a009a328f21502528c28113460e17f3cb1218b3536aefa712a61e6b8149a0979cd51a8b20c63a51e821e71df8f19c34d6f0a736a46dac6", "d2032ae9dddd98b060a009a328f21502528c28113460e17f3cb1218b3536aefa712a61e6b8149a0979cd51a8b20c63a51e821e71df8f19c34d6f0a736a46dac6"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('e21d58e7-da83-4f0d-a2c8-f42b01572e5c'::uuid,'ΔS_V = - Λ / T_M','MECHANISM','{}','Change in entropy when considering phase transition specifically at T_m, leading to zero change in free energy at this temperature','{}','{}','{"frequency": 2, "text_unit_ids": ["d2032ae9dddd98b060a009a328f21502528c28113460e17f3cb1218b3536aefa712a61e6b8149a0979cd51a8b20c63a51e821e71df8f19c34d6f0a736a46dac6", "d2032ae9dddd98b060a009a328f21502528c28113460e17f3cb1218b3536aefa712a61e6b8149a0979cd51a8b20c63a51e821e71df8f19c34d6f0a736a46dac6"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('c0d4a814-0d46-4dca-8c11-cc5a194337bc'::uuid,'ΔF_V = −Λ (T_M − T) / T_M','MODEL','{}','The revised expression for the change in free energy when assuming crystallization at T_m and expressing it as a function of arbitrary system temperature T','{}','{}','{"frequency": 3, "text_unit_ids": ["d2032ae9dddd98b060a009a328f21502528c28113460e17f3cb1218b3536aefa712a61e6b8149a0979cd51a8b20c63a51e821e71df8f19c34d6f0a736a46dac6", "d2032ae9dddd98b060a009a328f21502528c28113460e17f3cb1218b3536aefa712a61e6b8149a0979cd51a8b20c63a51e821e71df8f19c34d6f0a736a46dac6", "d2032ae9dddd98b060a009a328f21502528c28113460e17f3cb1218b3536aefa712a61e6b8149a0979cd51a8b20c63a51e821e71df8f19c34d6f0a736a46dac6"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('c00c3020-6f10-41f9-8263-b1a87bd27568'::uuid,'4/3Π R³ Λ (T_M − T)/T_M','SYSTEM','{}','Volume term indicating part of total free energy contribution due to phase transition volume effect, with sign depending on the ratio between crystallization and current temperatures','{}','{}','{"frequency": 3, "text_unit_ids": ["d2032ae9dddd98b060a009a328f21502528c28113460e17f3cb1218b3536aefa712a61e6b8149a0979cd51a8b20c63a51e821e71df8f19c34d6f0a736a46dac6", "d2032ae9dddd98b060a009a328f21502528c28113460e17f3cb1218b3536aefa712a61e6b8149a0979cd51a8b20c63a51e821e71df8f19c34d6f0a736a46dac6", "d2032ae9dddd98b060a009a328f21502528c28113460e17f3cb1218b3536aefa712a61e6b8149a0979cd51a8b20c63a51e821e71df8f19c34d6f0a736a46dac6"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1'),
	 ('fa00a47e-05a7-4c45-85b9-4a00fb9eb464'::uuid,'4Π R² Γ','SYSTEM','{}','Surface tension related component, always positive for the interface formation','{}','{}','{"frequency": 3, "text_unit_ids": ["d2032ae9dddd98b060a009a328f21502528c28113460e17f3cb1218b3536aefa712a61e6b8149a0979cd51a8b20c63a51e821e71df8f19c34d6f0a736a46dac6", "d2032ae9dddd98b060a009a328f21502528c28113460e17f3cb1218b3536aefa712a61e6b8149a0979cd51a8b20c63a51e821e71df8f19c34d6f0a736a46dac6", "d2032ae9dddd98b060a009a328f21502528c28113460e17f3cb1218b3536aefa712a61e6b8149a0979cd51a8b20c63a51e821e71df8f19c34d6f0a736a46dac6"]}','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','2026-07-17 17:14:05.801343','solid_state_physics_v1');
